    legal_principle:
      'A statutory presumption in road traffic legislation that a person found with excess alcohol in their blood is guilty of the offence of drink driving, subject to rebuttal by the defence, was challenged on equality and due process grounds. The Supreme Court upheld the presumption, finding it was rationally connected to the legislative objective of road safety and that it did not disproportionately or irrationally burden one class of citizens over another. The case confirms the conditions under which statutory presumptions can survive constitutional challenge.',
