      'A statutory presumption which shifts an evidential burden to an accused does not violate the equality guarantee where it is rationally connected to a legitimate legislative objective and does not impose an excessive or disproportionate burden on the accused.',
    full_summary:
      "DPP v. Heffernan [2017] 1 IR 82 concerned a constitutional challenge to statutory presumptions in road traffic legislation that effectively required the defence to rebut proof of excess alcohol levels established by an approved device. The defendant argued that these presumptions violated Article 40.1 (equality) and Article 38.1 (trial in due course of law, including the presumption of innocence). The Supreme Court rejected the challenges. On the equality ground, the court found that road traffic offenders who are in possession of excess alcohol as established by device testing are in a relevantly different position from other citizens, and that the presumption reflects this difference rationally and proportionately. The court reaffirmed the principle that equality does not require identical treatment of all citizens but permits distinctions that are rationally grounded and proportionate. On the due process ground, the court held that evidential presumptions, particularly in regulatory offences, are constitutionally permissible provided they do not impose an unreasonable onus on the accused and allow for genuine rebuttal. Heffernan is significant for FE-1 candidates as an up-to-date authority on the interaction of Article 40.1 with criminal procedure and statutory presumptions, and on the court's approach to road traffic regulation as a sphere of significant public interest.",
