    full_summary:
      "Molyneux v. Ireland [1997] IEHC 206 involved a challenge by a person with a disability to the provisions of the Juries Act 1976 that excluded certain categories of disabled persons from jury service. The plaintiff argued that the exclusion constituted discrimination contrary to Article 40.1, as it denied persons with disabilities the opportunity to participate in one of the most fundamental civic institutions in a democratic society. The High Court examined the provisions in the context of Article 40.1 and the broader constitutional principles governing the treatment of citizens with disabilities. The court acknowledged the evolving understanding of disability rights and the increasing recognition that blanket exclusions based on disability \u2014 as opposed to assessments of individual capacity \u2014 are difficult to justify under modern equality standards. While the court's ultimate holding was qualified, the case is significant as an early Irish judicial engagement with disability equality and as a precursor to the more developed disability rights jurisprudence that has subsequently emerged. Molyneux is relevant in FE-1 examinations on the scope of Article 40.1, the treatment of disability as a protected characteristic under Irish constitutional law, and the evolution of equality jurisprudence to encompass non-traditional grounds of discrimination. It is also relevant to discussions of Ireland's obligations under the UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities.",
