      "Donnelly v. Minister for Social Protection [2022] IESC 31 was a Supreme Court case in which the plaintiff, a cohabiting partner who had lived with her deceased partner for many years, challenged the refusal to pay her a bereavement grant under the Social Welfare Consolidation Act 2005, a payment available to married and civilly partnered persons but not to cohabitants. The Supreme Court, in a significant constitutional ruling, held that the total exclusion of qualifying cohabitants from the bereavement grant could not be constitutionally defended. The court engaged with the evolving understanding of Article 40.1 in the context of changing family structures and social norms, noting that the constitutional protection of marriage in Article 41 does not demand that the State deny all recognition to other forms of stable family life. While the Constitution accords a special status to marriage, this status does not entail that the State must treat surviving cohabiting partners \u2014 who may have maintained the same practical dependency and mutual commitment as spouses \u2014 as if they were in an entirely different position. The court's reasoning drew extensively on its prior analysis in cases such as MhicMhath\u00fana and on comparative equality jurisprudence from the ECHR and UK courts, including Re McLaughlin and R(Carson). Donnelly was a direct precursor to O'Meara [2024] IESC 1 and is essential for understanding the trajectory of Irish social welfare equality law. It is a high-priority case for FE-1 constitutional law examinations.",
