      "R (Carson) v. Secretary of State for Work and Pensions [2005] UKHL 37 was a House of Lords decision on the compatibility of the UK's 'frozen pension' policy \u2014 under which the state pension of UK nationals living in certain countries is not uprated annually \u2014 with Article 14 ECHR (prohibition of discrimination) read with Article 1 Protocol 1 ECHR (protection of property). The appellants, pensioners living in South Africa and other non-qualifying countries, argued that they were being treated less favourably than pensioners living in the UK or in countries with reciprocal uprating agreements, and that this differential treatment was discriminatory. The House of Lords held that place of residence is not an analogous ground under Article 14, meaning that the differential treatment did not trigger the prohibition on discrimination in the enjoyment of Convention rights at all. Even if it did, the court was satisfied that the treatment fell within the wide margin of appreciation afforded to states in designing complex social security systems. The case is relevant in Irish constitutional law as a comparative authority on the scope of equality protection in social security matters, the concept of analogous grounds for discrimination, and the margin of appreciation doctrine under the ECHR. It is cited in Irish judgments and scholarship dealing with Article 40.1 and Ireland's ECHR Act 2003 obligations.",
