    full_summary:
      "Re McLaughlin [2018] UKSC 48 is a UK Supreme Court decision in which the appellant, an unmarried partner who had lived with her partner for 23 years before his death, challenged the refusal of the widowed parent's allowance on the basis that the scheme was available only to those who had been legally married to the deceased. The Supreme Court, in a unanimous decision, held that the differential treatment violated Article 14 ECHR read with Article 1 Protocol 1. Lady Hale, delivering the lead judgment, held that the appellant was in an analogous situation to a married bereaved parent and that the State had failed to demonstrate a legitimate aim that could justify the complete exclusion of qualifying cohabitants from the scheme. The court applied the structured Article 14 analysis: analogous situation; difference in treatment; legitimate aim; proportionality. The McLaughlin decision is of direct relevance to Irish constitutional law because the same social welfare equality issue \u2014 the exclusion of non-married bereaved parents from bereavement-related benefits \u2014 was at the heart of Donnelly v. Minister for Social Protection [2022] IESC 31 and O'Meara v. Minister for Social Protection [2024] IESC 1. The Irish Supreme Court drew on McLaughlin's reasoning in both cases. For FE-1 candidates, the case illustrates the cross-jurisdictional dialogue between Irish constitutional equality law and the ECHR framework and demonstrates how developments in UK human rights law inform Irish constitutional reasoning.",
