    citation: 'App No 45851/99 (ECHR, 27 April 2000)',
    year: 2000,
    court: 'ECHR',
    jurisdiction: 'ECHR',
    legal_principle:
      'A cohabiting applicant who was denied bereavement benefits available to married persons following the death of her long-term partner was held by the ECHR to have raised an arguable Article 14 complaint, but the application was declared inadmissible on the basis that the State retained a wide margin of appreciation in drawing distinctions between married and unmarried couples in social security legislation. The case illustrates the limits of ECHR protection for cohabiting couples in the bereavement benefit context as at 2000, and provides a baseline against which later developments in McLaughlin and the Irish Supreme Court cases can be measured.',
    key_quote:
      "States retain a wide margin of appreciation in determining how to organise their social security systems, and a distinction between married and unmarried cohabiting couples in bereavement benefits does not necessarily violate Article 14 ECHR when read with the State's right to regulate social security.",
    full_summary:
      "Shackell v. United Kingdom (App No 45851/99) was an admissibility decision of the European Court of Human Rights in which the applicant, a woman who had cohabited with her partner for 19 years before his death, complained under Articles 8 and 14 ECHR that she had been denied widowhood benefits available to married persons. The ECHR declared the application inadmissible. The court accepted that the applicant was in a broadly analogous situation to a surviving spouse for the purposes of Article 14 ECHR, but held that the difference in treatment was justified by the State's wide margin of appreciation in social security matters. The court noted that while the situation of cohabiting couples and married couples may in many respects be similar, it is not unreasonable for a State to differentiate between them in the social welfare context, at least at the time of the decision. Shackell represents the high-water mark of deference to State margin of appreciation in ECHR bereavement benefit cases. It stands in sharp contrast to the later decisions in Re McLaughlin [2018] UKSC 48 and the Irish Supreme Court cases of Donnelly [2022] and O'Meara [2024], which took a markedly less deferential approach to the same issue. For FE-1 candidates, Shackell provides important comparative context for understanding how the ECHR and domestic courts have moved away from blanket deference to states in social welfare equality cases and towards a more rigorous proportionality analysis.",
