      'The Supreme Court held, by a 3-2 majority, that the criminalisation of consensual male homosexual acts did not violate the Constitution. The majority declined to recognise a constitutional right to privacy extending to such conduct, grounding their reasoning in natural law and Christian morality as embedded in the Constitution. This decision was subsequently overturned by the European Court of Human Rights in Norris v Ireland (1988) 13 EHRR 186.',
