    full_summary:
      "The plaintiffs were required under s.52 of the Offences Against the State Act 1939 to give an account of their movements and actions at a particular time, on pain of criminal sanction for refusal. They challenged this as a breach of their right to silence and privilege against self-incrimination. The Supreme Court confirmed that both rights are constitutionally protected as unenumerated personal rights under Article 40.3. However, the Court articulated and applied a proportionality test \u2014 drawn partly from Canadian and ECHR jurisprudence \u2014 to assess the validity of the statutory restriction. The Court held that the State's interest in combating terrorism and subversive activity was a legitimate aim, and that the restriction in s.52 was proportionate in the context of that aim. The decision is doctrinally significant because it firmly established the proportionality test as the applicable standard when examining legislative restrictions on constitutional rights in Ireland. This test \u2014 requiring that measures: (1) pursue a legitimate aim; (2) be rationally connected to that aim; (3) impair rights as little as reasonably possible; and (4) have effects proportionate to the aim \u2014 has been applied in virtually every constitutional rights case since. The s.52 provision was subsequently found to breach Article 6 ECHR in Heaney and McGuinness v Ireland (2001) 33 EHRR 264.",
