      "Marie Fleming, who suffered from advanced multiple sclerosis, sought a declaration that the absolute prohibition on assisted suicide in s.2(2) of the Criminal Law (Suicide) Act 1993 was unconstitutional as applied to her circumstances. She argued it breached her personal rights under Article 40.3, including an unenumerated right to autonomy and to die with dignity. The High Court and, on appeal, the Supreme Court rejected her claim. The Supreme Court held that Article 40.3.2 imposes a positive obligation on the State to defend and vindicate the right to life, which is fundamentally inconsistent with permitting assisted dying. No constitutional right to assisted suicide existed. The Court also held that even if some personal autonomy right was engaged, the State's interest in protecting vulnerable people from pressure or abuse in end-of-life situations was a weighty and legitimate countervailing interest justifying the prohibition. The decision engages important questions about the limits of unenumerated rights, the relationship between personal autonomy and State paternalism, and the weight to be given to constitutional text versus evolving social norms. Ms Fleming also litigated before the European Court of Human Rights, where the case was declared inadmissible. The case remains the leading Irish authority on the constitutional status of assisted dying.",
