      "The applicant, a man of limited means, was charged with serious criminal offences. He applied for free legal aid but was refused. He argued that his inability to obtain legal representation violated his constitutional right to a fair trial. The Supreme Court held that, as a matter of constitutional law, where a person faces serious criminal charges that could result in loss of liberty and cannot afford legal representation, the State is obliged to provide free legal aid. This obligation arises from the right to a trial in due course of law under Article 38.1 and from the guarantee in Article 40.1 that all citizens are held equal before the law. Permitting an unrepresented accused to face serious criminal proceedings would render the trial fundamentally unfair. The decision predated the Criminal Justice (Legal Aid) Act 1962 \u2014 which already provided a statutory framework \u2014 but grounded legal aid firmly in constitutional entitlement rather than mere statutory discretion. The case remains foundational for the constitutional dimension of the right to legal representation and has been applied in subsequent cases involving the adequacy of legal aid schemes. It also demonstrates the Court's use of implied and unenumerated rights to supplement express constitutional guarantees.",
