    legal_principle:
      'Article 40.3.3 of the Constitution protects the equal right to life of the unborn and the mother. Where there is a real and substantial risk to the life of the mother \u2014 including by suicide \u2014 that can only be averted by the termination of the pregnancy, the right to an abortion within the State is constitutionally protected. The Article 40.3.3 right to travel could not be enjoined in such circumstances.',
    key_quote:
      'If it is established\u2026 that there is a real and substantial risk to the life\u2026 of the mother, which can only be avoided by the termination of her pregnancy, such termination is permissible.',
    full_summary:
      'A 14-year-old girl who had become pregnant as a result of rape was brought to England by her parents for a termination. The Attorney General obtained an interim injunction preventing travel, on the basis that Article 40.3.3 protected the right to life of the unborn. The Supreme Court, by a 4-1 majority, discharged the injunction. The Court held that Article 40.3.3 required a balancing of the equal right to life of the mother and the unborn. Where there was a real and substantial risk to the life of the mother \u2014 the evidence disclosed a risk of suicide \u2014 which could only be averted by termination, the right to travel for that purpose could not be restrained. The case fundamentally reshaped Irish abortion law. It established that termination of pregnancy was lawful in Ireland where there was a real and substantial risk to the life of the mother. Three referenda followed in 1992 to address travel, information, and the substantive issue. The Protection of Life During Pregnancy Act 2013 gave statutory effect to the X case ruling. The Thirty-sixth Amendment (2018) subsequently repealed Article 40.3.3 entirely, permitting abortion legislation under the Health (Regulation of Termination of Pregnancy) Act 2018. The X case remains one of the most significant and consequential decisions in Irish constitutional history.',
