      'NHV, an asylum seeker from Myanmar, had been present in Ireland for several years awaiting determination of his asylum claim. The Refugee Act 1996 (as amended) imposed a blanket prohibition on asylum seekers taking any employment or engaging in any business. He argued this violated his unenumerated constitutional right to earn a livelihood. The Supreme Court, by a 6-1 majority, upheld his challenge. The Court confirmed that the right to earn a livelihood is a personal right under Article 40.3 enjoyed by all persons present in Ireland, not just citizens. Applying the proportionality test from Heaney v Ireland, the Court found that the absolute and indefinite nature of the prohibition \u2014 with no individual assessment, no exceptions, and no fixed end point \u2014 went further than necessary to achieve the legitimate aims of immigration control and preventing pull factors. This was a landmark ruling on the intersection of constitutional rights and immigration law. Following the decision, the International Protection Act 2015 was amended to permit international protection applicants to access the labour market after a defined waiting period. The case also affirmed that non-citizens present in Ireland are entitled to protection of constitutional personal rights, a point of significant ongoing relevance.',
