      "The case involved an Irish citizen, Gorry, who had married a non-national. A deportation order was made against the non-national spouse on grounds of prior illegal presence in the State. The question was whether the deportation violated the constitutional rights of the married family under Article 41. The Supreme Court, in a significant judgment clarifying the interaction between constitutional family rights and immigration law, held that Article 41 imposes real but not absolute constraints on the State's power to deport non-national spouses. The Court rejected both an absolute right of an Irish citizen to have their non-national spouse reside with them and a purely discretionary approach. Instead, a structured proportionality exercise is required, taking into account: the nature and duration of the relationship, the immigration history of the non-national, any family ties in the State and abroad, and the best interests of any children. The decision provided clear guidance replacing the somewhat unclear earlier position from Oguekwe v Minister for Justice [2008] IESC 25. Gorry remains the leading authority on the constitutional treatment of family rights in immigration and deportation decisions and has been applied extensively in subsequent cases.",
