    full_summary:
      "Mrs Cahill brought proceedings against her doctor in negligence. She sought also to challenge the constitutionality of a statutory limitation period which barred her claim. The defendant argued she lacked standing to raise the constitutional issue as the provision affected others differently. The Supreme Court addressed the doctrine of locus standi in constitutional challenges. Henchy J articulated the general rule that a person challenging a statute's constitutionality must show they have personally suffered, or are in imminent danger of suffering, an injury from its operation. One may not ordinarily rely on rights belonging to third parties. Henchy J also recognised the 'jus tertii' exception, acknowledging that in some circumstances \u2014 particularly where the person whose rights are actually affected is unlikely to be in a position to vindicate them \u2014 the court might relax the strict standing requirement. The rule ensures that constitutional challenges are grounded in real factual disputes rather than abstract legal argument, preserving the adversarial character of Irish litigation. Cahill v Sutton is consistently cited as the foundational authority on locus standi in constitutional cases and is almost invariably referenced in any examination question involving standing. The principles were refined and applied in subsequent cases including Crotty v An Taoiseach [1987], Riordan v An Taoiseach [1999], and FIE v Government of Ireland [2020].",
