    full_summary:
      'The applicant, Burke, was detained under the Offences Against the State (Amendment) Act 1940, which permitted internment without trial during emergency periods. He applied for an inquiry into the legality of his detention under Article 40.4.2 of the Constitution (the equivalent of habeas corpus). The Supreme Court held that the detention was unconstitutional. Even though the emergency provisions existed, the Court found that the constitutional guarantee of personal liberty under Article 40.4 could not be overridden in peacetime without lawful statutory authority properly enacted. The internment provisions as applied were held to be repugnant to the Constitution. This case is a landmark early example of the courts using the 1937 Constitution to restrain executive power over individual liberty. It established that Article 40.4 is a live and enforceable constitutional guarantee, not a mere statement of principle. The decision prompted immediate emergency legislative response, and the Offences Against the State (Amendment) Act 1940 was enacted within days to provide a constitutional basis for internment. The case illustrates the tension between national security imperatives and constitutional rights \u2014 a tension that recurs throughout Irish constitutional history and in the subsequent case law on Part V of the Offences Against the State Act 1939.',
