      "IRM was a non-national who had been refused leave to remain in Ireland and faced deportation. He was the husband of an Irish national and the father of Irish citizen children. He challenged the deportation order on the basis that the Minister had not adequately considered his family's constitutional rights under Article 41. The Supreme Court held that the Minister must carry out a genuine, structured, and proportionate assessment of the constitutional family rights at stake. The decision-maker cannot pay mere lip service to the Article 41 rights: the analysis must be specific to the circumstances of the individual family. The Court applied the framework from Gorry and M (A Minor), holding that the proportionality assessment must identify the precise family interests engaged, the weight properly attributable to them, and the reasons why the State's interest in deportation is sufficient to override them. The case is part of a trilogy with Gorry and M (A Minor) and is regularly cited in immigration and family rights cases. Together, these cases have significantly developed the constitutional constraints on deportation decisions affecting family units in Ireland.",
