    legal_principle:
      'The principles of constitutional justice \u2014 audi alteram partem (the right to be heard) and nemo iudex in causa sua (the rule against bias) \u2014 apply not only to courts but to all bodies, including Oireachtas committees, that make determinations adversely affecting the rights or reputation of individuals. A person against whom adverse findings may be made is entitled to know the case made against them, to have access to relevant evidence, and to be given an opportunity to respond.',
    key_quote:
      'The requirements of constitutional justice \u2014 that a person be heard before an adverse finding is made against him and that the decision-maker be free from bias \u2014 apply to all bodies, including committees of the Oireachtas, whose decisions or findings may adversely affect the rights or good name of an individual.',
    full_summary:
      "Re Haughey is the leading Irish authority on the application of fair procedures requirements \u2014 constitutional justice \u2014 to non-judicial bodies, including committees of the Oireachtas. The case arose in the context of a committee of inquiry set up by the D\u00e1il to investigate the expenditure of certain public funds. Mr Haughey, against whom adverse allegations were made, challenged the committee's procedures on the basis that he had not been afforded a fair opportunity to defend himself. The Supreme Court upheld his challenge and held that the principles of natural justice and constitutional justice apply to all bodies, not just courts, that make or may make findings that adversely affect the rights, interests or reputation of individuals. The court specified a number of minimum procedural guarantees: the right to know the nature of the allegations, the right to cross-examine witnesses, the right to give evidence and to call evidence, and the right to legal representation. Re Haughey is one of the most frequently cited cases in Irish administrative law and constitutional law. It is cited as the foundational authority for the proposition that constitutional justice is a general principle of Irish law applicable across the administrative and legislative domains.",
