    full_summary:
      "McDonald v. Bord na gCon is a foundational authority on the application of natural justice to administrative decision-making in Irish law. The plaintiff, who held a greyhound racing licence, had his licence revoked by Bord na gCon without being given notice of the case against him or an opportunity to be heard. He challenged this revocation on the basis that fair procedures had not been observed. The Supreme Court upheld his challenge, holding that the principles of natural justice \u2014 particularly the right to be heard (audi alteram partem) \u2014 applied to the decision of Bord na gCon to revoke the licence, since this was a decision that adversely affected the plaintiff's legal rights. The court confirmed that the audi alteram partem rule applies wherever a statutory body makes a decision that affects the rights or legitimate interests of an individual, and that failure to comply renders the decision void. The case established the twin pillars of Irish administrative fair procedures law and is cited alongside Re Haughey as the principal domestic authority on natural justice in the administrative context.",
