      'The Abbeylara case concerned a sub-committee of the Oireachtas that was established to investigate the fatal shooting of John Carthy by the Garda Emergency Response Unit. The committee proposed to make findings about whether individual members of the Garda had acted appropriately. Members of the Garda applied to the courts to restrain the committee from making such findings. The Supreme Court, by a 4-1 majority, granted the injunction and held that the sub-committee did not have the constitutional or statutory power to conduct an inquiry that would result in findings of fact prejudicial to the reputations and legal interests of named individuals. The court held that such a function, by its nature, constituted the administration of justice within the meaning of Article 34, and that it could only be exercised by a court. The decision caused considerable controversy and was subsequently addressed by a constitutional amendment (the Thirty-Third Amendment) that sought to provide a constitutional basis for Oireachtas inquiries. The case is a key authority on the constitutional limits of Oireachtas committee powers and on the boundary between legislative inquiries and the judicial administration of justice.',
