      "Senator Ivana Bacik and others brought judicial review proceedings challenging the constitutionality of the Seanad electoral system, arguing that aspects of the Seanad's composition and the standing rules governing Seanad elections were unconstitutional. The High Court considered the extent to which the courts can review the internal standing rules and electoral arrangements of the Oireachtas, which has a measure of constitutional autonomy under Article 15. The court held that while significant deference is owed to the Oireachtas in matters relating to its own internal organisation, the courts retain jurisdiction to examine whether standing rules violate constitutional rights, including the right to equality and the right to vote. The case is a relatively recent authority on the limits of parliamentary autonomy and the scope of judicial review of Oireachtas procedures, and it contributes to the developing jurisprudence on the constitutional constraints applicable to the Oireachtas in regulating its own affairs.",
