      "This Article 26 reference is one of the most significant findings of unconstitutionality under the procedure. The Health (Amendment) (No. 2) Bill 2004 was introduced to retrospectively validate charges that had been levied on long-stay patients in Health Board care, charges that had been found to have no legal basis. Rather than refunding the unlawfully collected sums, the legislation sought to retrospectively legalise the charges and extinguish the patients' claims for restitution.\n\nThe Supreme Court found the Bill to be repugnant to the Constitution. The Court held that the retrospective legislation constituted an unjust attack on the property rights of the patients affected, contrary to Article 40.3. The patients had a vested legal right to recover the unlawfully collected money, and the legislation sought to extinguish that right retrospectively. The judgment is a landmark authority on the limits of retrospective legislation and on the constitutional protection of property rights. It confirmed that the State cannot use legislation to retrospectively deprive individuals of acquired legal rights, even where doing so would be financially convenient for the State. The case has significant implications for the constitutional analysis of retrospective legislation generally.",
