      'This landmark 2023 Supreme Court decision addressed the constitutionality of searching digital devices seized during a search of premises under a warrant that did not specifically authorise examination of those devices. The accused challenged the admissibility of evidence obtained from digital devices recovered during a search conducted under a standard Misuse of Drugs Act warrant.\n\nThe Supreme Court, allowing the appeal and overturning the Court of Appeal, held that the search of digital devices required express authorisation in the warrant itself. The Court reasoned that digital devices such as smartphones and laptops contain a qualitatively different category of private information compared to physical documents or objects, encompassing communications, location data, financial records, photographs, and intimate personal information. A blanket premises warrant could not constitutionally authorise access to such material without specific judicial consideration of whether that access was proportionate and necessary.\n\nThe decision built upon and extended the principles established in Damache v. DPP to the digital context, requiring that the issuing judicial authority independently consider whether device-specific authorisation is warranted. Quirke is the most significant Irish constitutional decision on digital privacy to date and has major implications for the conduct of searches in criminal investigations involving digital evidence.',
