      'A search warrant issued under the Misuse of Drugs Act 1977 authorising the search of a dwelling does not implicitly authorise the search of mobile phones found therein; specific authorisation is required to examine the contents of a mobile phone in light of the constitutionally protected right to privacy under Article 40.3.1. The reasonable expectation of privacy in the contents of a mobile phone is of a particularly high order and cannot be overridden without express judicial authorisation directed at the phone itself.',
    key_quote:
      'The contents of a mobile phone are not analogous to documents or physical items found in a searched premises; the degree of intimacy and the volume of personal data stored on a modern phone is such that a distinct reasonable expectation of privacy attaches to the device, which requires specific warrant authorisation before its contents may lawfully be examined.',
    full_summary:
      "In this Supreme Court decision, the Court examined whether a standard statutory search warrant authorising the search of a dwelling extended to the search and forensic examination of mobile phones found at the premises. The accused was convicted following the use of evidence extracted from his mobile phone during a search carried out pursuant to a Misuse of Drugs Act warrant.\n\nThe Supreme Court held that the warrant did not authorise examination of the mobile phone. Building on the principles from Damache v. DPP, the Court applied those principles to the specific context of digital devices, finding that a mobile phone warrants a heightened constitutional protection by virtue of the nature and volume of personal information it contains. The Court drew explicitly on the US Supreme Court's reasoning in Riley v. California, acknowledging it as a persuasive comparative authority.\n\nThe Court's analysis centred on the concept of a reasonable expectation of privacy, finding that Irish constitutional law recognises such an expectation in the contents of a mobile phone independently of any recognised categorical right. The decision clarifies and strengthens the constitutional framework governing digital searches in Ireland and confirmed that the principles of Damache apply with full force to digital devices.",
    subjects: ['constitutional'],
