    case_name: 'Damache v. DPP',
    citation: '[2012] IESC 11; [2012] 2 IR 266',
    year: 2012,
    court: 'Supreme Court',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'A search warrant issued by a Garda officer who is personally involved in the investigation to which the warrant relates is constitutionally invalid because it fails to satisfy the requirement of independent authorisation demanded by Article 40.5 of the Constitution. The inviolability of the dwelling requires that the power to authorise its search be exercised by an independent authority not involved in the investigation, and a statutory provision permitting a Garda superintendent implicated in the investigation to issue the warrant is unconstitutional.',
    key_quote:
      'The right of the dwelling to be inviolate carries with it the requirement that the authority empowered to authorise entry into it must be truly independent of those seeking entry; a police officer who is part of the investigating team cannot constitute such an independent authority.',
    full_summary:
      "Damache v. DPP is a landmark Supreme Court decision that fundamentally reformed Irish search and seizure law. The case arose from a terrorism investigation in which a search warrant for the accused's dwelling was issued by a Garda Chief Superintendent who was himself involved in the investigation. The accused challenged the constitutionality of the provision of the Offences Against the State Act 1939 that permitted such an officer to issue the warrant.\n\nThe Supreme Court, by a 4-1 majority, held that the statutory power to authorise a search must be exercised by a person who is independent of the investigation. A Garda officer who is part of the investigating team cannot constitute an independent authority for the purposes of Article 40.5. The Court struck down the relevant statutory provision as unconstitutional, finding that the constitutional guarantee of inviolability of the dwelling demands a meaningful external check on the decision to authorise entry.\n\nThe decision had immediate and widespread implications, rendering invalid numerous search warrants that had been issued by Garda superintendents under a range of statutory provisions. The Oireachtas subsequently enacted remedial legislation. Damache has also been extended to the digital context in Behan and Quirke, making it the foundational modern authority on constitutional requirements for search authorisation.",
