    case_name: "The People (AG) v. O'Brien",
    citation: '[1965] IR 142',
    year: 1965,
    court: 'Court of Criminal Appeal',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'Evidence obtained as a result of a deliberate and conscious violation of the constitutional rights of the accused must, as a general rule, be excluded from criminal proceedings. The Court of Criminal Appeal established for the first time in Irish law that a constitutional right to exclude illegally obtained evidence exists and that where the breach is deliberate the court has no discretion to admit the evidence; the deliberate and conscious breach test became the cornerstone of the Irish exclusionary rule.',
    key_quote:
      'If a member of the Garda Siochana acting in the course of his duty deliberately and consciously breaks the constitutional rights of a citizen, the evidence obtained as a result of this violation should not, unless there are extraordinary excusing circumstances, be admitted.',
    full_summary:
      "The People (AG) v. O'Brien is the seminal Irish case establishing the constitutional exclusionary rule. The case arose from a search of the accused's dwelling under a search warrant that described an incorrect address. The question was whether evidence discovered during the search, which was technically unlawful by reason of the defective warrant, should be admitted.\n\nThe Court of Criminal Appeal held that the constitutional rights of the accused had been violated and engaged in a detailed analysis of the proper response to such a violation. The Court established the foundational principle that a deliberate and conscious breach of constitutional rights by the Garda\u00ed will ordinarily lead to exclusion of evidence obtained as a result, unless there are extraordinary excusing circumstances. The deliberate/conscious test distinguished between good faith inadvertent violations (where a discretion to admit might be exercised) and deliberate violations (where exclusion was the default rule).\n\nO'Brien was the first Irish decision to articulate a constitutional basis for the exclusionary rule, as distinct from a mere judicial discretion to exclude. The case established the hierarchy of constitutional rights as a basis for evidence law and remained the primary authority until The People (DPP) v. Kenny (1990) strengthened the rule to an absolute exclusionary principle, which was in turn modified by The People (DPP) v. JC (2015).",
