    case_name: 'The People (DPP) v. Kenny',
    citation: '[1990] 2 IR 110',
    year: 1990,
    court: 'Supreme Court',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      "Evidence obtained by means of an unconstitutional search must be absolutely excluded from criminal proceedings regardless of whether the breach was made in good faith or through inadvertence; the constitutional rights of the accused cannot be subordinated to the exigencies of law enforcement by the application of a good faith exception. The Supreme Court extended and hardened the exclusionary rule established in O'Brien into an absolute constitutional mandate, rejecting any balancing of the accused's rights against prosecutorial interests.",
    key_quote:
      'If a right is to be protected by the courts, it must be protected absolutely; to permit evidence obtained by unconstitutional action to be admitted on the grounds of good faith would be to dilute the right to the point of meaninglessness.',
    full_summary:
      "The People (DPP) v. Kenny is the landmark Supreme Court decision that established the absolute exclusionary rule in Irish constitutional law. The case concerned evidence obtained pursuant to a search warrant that was subsequently found to be defective because it failed to state the specific offence under investigation with sufficient precision. The Garda\u00ed had acted in complete good faith in obtaining and executing the warrant.\n\nThe Supreme Court, by a majority, held that the evidence must be excluded absolutely, regardless of the good faith of the Garda\u00ed. The Court rejected the argument that a good faith exception should be imported into the Irish exclusionary rule and held that any dilution of the rule would undermine the constitutional rights of the accused. The majority reasoned that the constitutional guarantee is absolute and cannot be qualified by reference to the blameworthiness of the individual officer.\n\nKenny represented a significant departure from the more nuanced approach in O'Brien and created one of the most stringent exclusionary rules in the common law world. The absolute rule proved controversial, as it led to the exclusion of highly probative evidence where the constitutional breach was entirely technical and inadvertent. The rule was substantially modified 25 years later by The People (DPP) v. JC [2015], which reintroduced a balancing approach, making Kenny an important historical milestone rather than the current governing authority.",
