    case_name: 'The People (DPP) v. JC',
    citation: '[2015] IESC 31; [2017] 1 IR 417',
    year: 2015,
    court: 'Supreme Court',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'The absolute exclusionary rule established in The People (DPP) v. Kenny is overruled; evidence obtained in deliberate and conscious violation of the constitutional rights of the accused must be excluded, but evidence obtained through an unconstitutional act that was not deliberate or grossly negligent may be admitted where the court determines that the interests of justice so require. The Supreme Court re-established a balancing approach that weighs the seriousness of the violation against the public interest in prosecuting serious crime.',
    key_quote:
      'Evidence obtained in breach of constitutional rights ought to be excluded where the breach was deliberate or grossly negligent; but where the breach was neither deliberate nor grossly negligent, a court may, having regard to all the circumstances, admit the evidence where justice so requires.',
    full_summary:
      "The People (DPP) v. JC is the most significant Irish constitutional evidence law decision of the 21st century, overruling the 25-year-old absolute exclusionary rule from Kenny and replacing it with a new balancing test. The case arose from a drugs prosecution in which evidence was obtained pursuant to a search warrant that was subsequently found to be constitutionally defective in light of the Supreme Court's decision in Damache v. DPP, though the Garda\u00ed had acted in complete good faith at the time.\n\nThe Supreme Court, by a 4-3 majority, held that Kenny should be overruled. The majority found that the absolute exclusionary rule produced unjust outcomes by mandating exclusion of highly probative evidence in cases where the constitutional breach was wholly inadvertent and caused no actual prejudice to the accused. The new test requires courts to determine whether the breach was deliberate or grossly negligent, in which case exclusion follows; or whether it was neither, in which case the court exercises a discretion to admit or exclude based on the totality of circumstances.\n\nThe dissenting judges argued that the overruling of Kenny undermined the constitutional guarantee and the incentive for state authorities to comply with constitutional norms. JC remains deeply controversial and is a central topic in FE-1 examinations on constitutional rights in criminal proceedings.",
