    citation: '[1965] IR 70',
    year: 1965,
    court: 'Supreme Court',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'The constitutional guarantee of personal liberty under Article 40.4 and the unenumerated right to bodily integrity comprehend a right not to be unlawfully removed from the jurisdiction or subjected to extradition procedures that violate fundamental constitutional rights; the courts retain jurisdiction under Article 40.4 to protect persons from deportation where the procedures employed are themselves constitutionally defective. The constitutional protections for personal liberty cannot be evaded by administrative action that removes a person from the jurisdiction before constitutional rights can be vindicated.',
    key_quote:
      "The Constitution's guarantee of personal liberty cannot be rendered nugatory by executive action that spirits a person out of the jurisdiction before the courts can act; the courts have both the jurisdiction and the duty to prevent such unconstitutional executive conduct.",
    full_summary:
      "State (Quinn) v. Ryan is a landmark Supreme Court decision addressing the interplay between habeas corpus under Article 40.4 and the executive's power to remove persons from the jurisdiction. The case arose in a highly politically charged context involving persons who had escaped from custody in Northern Ireland and who were sought by the authorities there. The applicants sought to invoke Article 40.4 to prevent their return across the border.\n\nThe Supreme Court held that Article 40.4 confers on the High Court an extensive and non-derogable jurisdiction to inquire into the legality of any detention, and that this jurisdiction cannot be circumvented by executive action. The Court went further and held that the constitutional rights of persons within the jurisdiction cannot be defeated by physically removing the individual from the jurisdiction before the courts can act, and that the executive has no power to frustrate constitutional protections in this way.\n\nThe case is foundational for the proposition that the courts are the ultimate guardians of constitutional rights and that no executive action can place a person beyond the reach of constitutional protection while they remain within the jurisdiction. It is also cited in relation to the right to travel, extradition, and the limits of executive power vis-a-vis the courts.",
