    citation: '[1988] IR 31',
    year: 1988,
    court: 'High Court',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'A search warrant under Article 40.5 must be sufficiently specific to identify the premises to be searched and the purpose of the search; a defective warrant that does not adequately describe the premises to be searched is constitutionally invalid and a search conducted under it violates the right to inviolability of the dwelling. Evidence obtained as a result of such a search is subject to exclusion under the constitutional exclusionary rule.',
    key_quote:
      "A warrant that fails to specify with adequate precision the premises to be searched cannot satisfy the constitutional requirement of a valid warrant; the protection of the dwelling under Article 40.5 requires that any authorisation for its search identify the dwelling with sufficient particularity to allow the occupier to verify the warrant's scope.",
    full_summary:
      "Byrne v. Grey is a High Court decision addressing the constitutional requirements of specificity for search warrants under Article 40.5. The case concerned a search warrant that contained an error in the description of the premises, and the question was whether this defect rendered the warrant constitutionally invalid and the search conducted under it unlawful.\n\nThe High Court held that the inviolability of the dwelling guaranteed by Article 40.5 requires that any warrant authorising entry into a private dwelling must be sufficiently specific to identify the premises with precision. A warrant that is so defective in its description that it could apply to premises other than those intended fails to satisfy the constitutional standard, because it does not provide the occupier with an adequate means of verifying the scope of the authorisation.\n\nThe case reinforced and elaborated upon the principle, traceable to The People (AG) v. O'Brien, that the warrant requirement is a substantive constitutional protection, not a mere procedural formality. Defective warrants produce unlawful searches, and evidence obtained thereby is subject to the exclusionary principles applicable to constitutionally obtained evidence. Byrne v. Grey is frequently cited alongside O'Brien and Damache as authority for the constitutional requirements governing the form and content of search warrants.",
