    citation: '[2003] 2 ILRM 105',
    year: 2003,
    court: 'Court of Criminal Appeal',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'The constitutional protection against arbitrary search and seizure extends to motor vehicles, and the exercise of statutory stop-and-search powers must be based upon reasonable suspicion; a purported exercise of stop-and-search power without the requisite reasonable suspicion violates the constitutional rights of the person subjected to it. Evidence obtained as a result of an unlawful vehicle search is subject to the constitutional exclusionary rule.',
    key_quote:
      'The statutory power to stop and search a vehicle is not a power to be exercised at random or on a mere hunch; it requires a reasonable suspicion based on articulable facts, and its exercise without that foundation constitutes a violation of the constitutional rights of the individual.',
    full_summary:
      "The People (DPP) v. McFadden addressed the constitutional constraints on Garda powers to stop and search motor vehicles under statutory powers. The accused challenged the admissibility of drugs evidence obtained during a search of his vehicle, arguing that the Garda\u00ed had lacked the requisite reasonable suspicion required to exercise the stop-and-search power and that the search was therefore constitutionally unlawful.\n\nThe Court of Criminal Appeal held that the exercise of statutory stop-and-search powers without the necessary reasonable suspicion constituted a breach of the accused's constitutional rights. The Court confirmed that constitutional protection against arbitrary searches is not limited to dwellings under Article 40.5 but extends to persons and their vehicles under the broader constitutional right to privacy and liberty. The reasonable suspicion requirement is a constitutional minimum that cannot be displaced by a broad statutory grant of search power.\n\nThe decision is an important authority for the proposition that all statutory search powers, regardless of the context in which they operate, are subject to constitutional constraints and in particular to the requirement of a factual basis for the exercise of the power. It has been cited in subsequent challenges to vehicle searches and to the constitutionality of random search regimes.",
