      'The constitutional protection of the dwelling requires more than the formal involvement of a judicial officer in the warrant process; the officer must actually consider and independently assess whether the conditions for the issue of a warrant have been met.',
    full_summary:
      'Application of Quinn is a Supreme Court decision addressing the constitutional requirements for the valid issue of a search warrant. The applicant challenged the validity of a search warrant issued in respect of his dwelling, arguing that the District Justice who issued the warrant had not genuinely applied an independent judicial mind to the question of whether the warrant should issue.\n\nThe Supreme Court considered the constitutional status of the warrant requirement and the importance of genuine judicial oversight of search authorisation. The Court held that the constitutional guarantee of inviolability of the dwelling demands not merely the formal participation of a judicial authority but genuine and independent consideration of whether the statutory preconditions for the issue of the warrant have been satisfied. An issuing judicial officer who fails to discharge this function independently does not provide the constitutional safeguard that Article 40.5 requires.\n\nThe case is an important precursor to Damache v. DPP and to the line of cases establishing that independence in the warrant-issuing function is a constitutional requirement. It establishes the principle that judicial oversight of search authorisation must be substantive rather than formal, and is cited as foundational authority for the constitutional role of the issuing authority in warrant law.',
