    case_name: 'Katz v. United States',
    citation: '389 US 347 (1967)',
    year: 1967,
    court: 'Supreme Court',
    jurisdiction: 'US',
    legal_principle:
      "The Fourth Amendment of the United States Constitution protects people, not places, and its protection extends to wherever a person has a reasonable expectation of privacy; government surveillance that intercepts private communications without a warrant violates the Fourth Amendment even where no physical trespass into protected premises occurs. The Katz 'reasonable expectation of privacy' test has been adopted as a touchstone of Fourth Amendment jurisprudence and is cited comparatively in Irish and European digital privacy cases.",
    key_quote:
      'The Fourth Amendment protects people, not places. What a person knowingly exposes to the public, even in his home or office, is not a subject of Fourth Amendment protection. But what he seeks to preserve as private, even in an area accessible to the public, may be constitutionally protected.',
    full_summary:
      "Katz v. United States is the foundational United States Supreme Court decision establishing the 'reasonable expectation of privacy' test as the governing standard under the Fourth Amendment. The case arose from the government's warrantless wiretapping of a public telephone booth used by the accused to make bookmaking calls. The lower courts had dismissed the accused's Fourth Amendment claim on the basis that there was no physical intrusion into a constitutionally protected area.\n\nThe Supreme Court, reversing those decisions, held that the Fourth Amendment protects people's reasonable expectations of privacy rather than physical spaces. Justice Harlan's concurring opinion articulated the now-canonical two-part test: a person must have a subjective expectation of privacy that society is prepared to recognise as reasonable. A telephone booth user who closes the door reasonably expects that his conversation will not be intercepted without a warrant, regardless of the fact that the booth is in a public space.\n\nKatz fundamentally reoriented Fourth Amendment doctrine away from a property-based trespass model to a privacy-based reasonable expectations model. The case has been enormously influential beyond the United States and is regularly cited by the Irish courts and the CJEU in digital privacy cases, including The People (DPP) v. Behan and Quirke, as a comparative authority establishing the conceptual framework for privacy protection in the digital age.",
