    case_name: 'Riley v. California',
    citation: '573 US 373 (2014)',
    year: 2014,
    court: 'Supreme Court',
    jurisdiction: 'US',
    legal_principle:
      'The search of the digital contents of a mobile phone seized incident to arrest requires a warrant under the Fourth Amendment; the vast quantity and intimate nature of data stored on modern smartphones takes them outside the scope of the traditional search-incident-to-arrest exception. The decision established that digital data on mobile devices warrants a categorically higher level of constitutional protection than physical items found on the person, and is cited as a leading comparative authority in Irish and European digital search cases.',
    key_quote:
      "Modern cell phones are not just another technological convenience. With all they contain and all they may reveal, they hold for many Americans 'the privacies of life'. The fact that technology now allows an individual to carry such information in his hand does not make the information any less worthy of the protection for which the Founders fought.",
    full_summary:
      'Riley v. California is the landmark United States Supreme Court decision holding that law enforcement officers must generally obtain a warrant before searching the digital contents of a mobile phone seized from an arrested person. The traditional search-incident-to-arrest exception to the warrant requirement, which allows officers to search physical items found on an arrestee to ensure officer safety and prevent destruction of evidence, does not extend to the digital contents of mobile phones.\n\nThe Supreme Court, in a unanimous decision authored by Chief Justice Roberts, reasoned that mobile phones are qualitatively different from other items that may be found on a person. They contain enormous quantities of sensitive personal information \u2014 communications, photographs, financial records, location data, browsing history \u2014 that far exceeds what could be carried in any physical container. The combination of quantity and intimacy of data distinguishes mobile phones from wallets, address books, or other physical items subject to the search-incident-to-arrest exception.\n\nThe decision has had profound influence beyond the United States and is directly cited by the Irish Supreme Court in The People (DPP) v. Behan and The People (DPP) v. Quirke as a persuasive comparative authority supporting the conclusion that digital devices warrant enhanced constitutional protection in the warrant context. Riley is a foundational case in any discussion of constitutional rights and digital evidence.',
