    case_name: '\u00c1str\u00e1\u00f0sson v. Iceland',
    citation: 'Application No. 26374/18 (Grand Chamber, 2020)',
    year: 2020,
    court: 'European Court of Human Rights (Grand Chamber)',
    jurisdiction: 'ECHR',
    legal_principle:
      'Article 6(1) ECHR guarantees the right to a tribunal established by law, which requires not only that courts be established by a valid legal basis but that the process of judicial appointment complies with the applicable domestic law and does not undermine the rule of law and the separation of powers; a flagrant breach of the domestic rules governing judicial appointments may constitute a violation of Article 6(1), rendering the composition of the tribunal unlawful. The Grand Chamber established a three-limb test for determining when an irregularity in judicial appointment reaches the threshold of a Convention violation.',
    key_quote:
      "The right to a 'tribunal established by law' serves the fundamental objectives of the rule of law and the separation of powers; it does not mean any court, but a court constituted in accordance with the applicable law, and a flagrant disregard of the rules governing judicial appointments will result in a violation of Article 6(1).",
    full_summary:
      "\u00c1str\u00e1\u00f0sson v. Iceland is the Grand Chamber judgment of the European Court of Human Rights that established the definitive ECHR framework on the right to a tribunal established by law under Article 6(1). The case arose from irregularities in the appointment process for judges of the newly established Icelandic Court of Appeals, where the Minister of Justice had deviated from the Judicial Appointments Committee's recommendations without adequate justification and in breach of domestic law.\n\nThe Grand Chamber held that a violation of Article 6(1) in this context requires satisfaction of a three-limb test: (1) whether there was a manifest breach of domestic law; (2) whether the breach concerned a fundamental rule of the judicial appointments procedure; and (3) whether the breach was effective reviewed and remedied by domestic courts. Applying this test, the Court found a violation in the Icelandic case because the Minister's deviation from the committee's recommendations was both a manifest breach of domestic law and a fundamental departure from the rules designed to ensure the independence and impartiality of the judiciary.\n\nThe judgment has become a foundational reference in both ECHR and EU law on judicial independence, cited extensively in CJEU decisions on Polish judicial reforms and referenced by the Irish Supreme Court in the Judicial Appointments Commission reference. It is essential reading for any examination of the constitutional and ECHR dimensions of judicial independence.",
