    case_name: 'A.K. and Others v. S\u0105d Najwy\u017cszy',
    citation: 'Cases C-585/18, C-624/18 and C-625/18, EU:C:2019:982',
    year: 2019,
    court: 'Court of Justice of the European Union',
    jurisdiction: 'EU',
    legal_principle:
      'A body that has been established by legislation enabling the executive to exert undue influence over its composition and functioning may not constitute an independent tribunal for the purposes of Article 47 of the EU Charter; national courts must themselves assess whether a body meets the independence criteria and must disapply any national rule preventing that assessment. The CJEU provided a detailed test for evaluating whether a newly established judicial body satisfies the EU law requirement of independence.',
    key_quote:
      'In order to determine whether a body is an independent court or tribunal within the meaning of Article 47 of the Charter, account must be taken of all relevant factors, including the manner in which its members are appointed and their terms of office, the existence of rules protecting members against external pressures, and whether the body presents an appearance of independence that would prevent any reasonable doubt in the minds of individuals as to its impartiality.',
    full_summary:
      'A.K. and Others addresses the independence of the Disciplinary Chamber of the Polish Supreme Court, a body created by legislation widely regarded as designed to allow the government to discipline judges who gave unwelcome rulings. Serving Polish Supreme Court judges had been subject to proceedings before the Disciplinary Chamber and challenged its status as an independent tribunal under Article 47 of the EU Charter.\n\nThe CJEU provided a comprehensive analytical framework for assessing the independence of judicial bodies under EU law. The Court identified the relevant factors as including: the circumstances of the appointment of members; the duration of tenure; the extent to which the body is shielded from external instructions; and whether the overall institutional design presents an appearance of independence capable of reassuring litigants. The Court further held that the role given to a newly created National Council of the Judiciary \u2014 itself controversially reconstituted \u2014 in nominating members of the Disciplinary Chamber was a relevant factor pointing against independence.\n\nCrucially, the Court also held that a national court seized of a dispute involving EU law must be able to assess whether it is confronted with an independent tribunal and must be able to disapply national rules preventing that assessment. A.K. is an essential case for examinations on judicial independence in EU law and on the relationship between Article 47 of the Charter and Article 19(1) TEU.',
