    citation: 'Case C-896/19, EU:C:2021:311',
    year: 2021,
    court: 'Court of Justice of the European Union',
    jurisdiction: 'EU',
    legal_principle:
      'Article 19(1) TEU does not preclude national judicial appointments procedures that involve a role for political actors such as the Prime Minister, provided that the overall system of appointments and the conditions of judicial tenure are such as to ensure, in practice, the independence of those appointed; the mere fact of political involvement in a judicial appointments procedure does not automatically constitute a violation of EU law.',
    key_quote:
      'Article 19(1) TEU does not require any particular model of judicial appointments, and the involvement of political bodies or actors in the process of appointment does not per se infringe that provision, provided that, once appointed, judges can carry out their functions with the independence demanded by EU law.',
    full_summary:
      "Repubblika v. Il-Prim Ministru is a CJEU decision arising from a challenge by a Maltese civil society organisation to the system of judicial appointments in Malta, under which the Prime Minister has a central role in recommending judicial appointments. The applicant argued that this system was incompatible with the requirement of judicial independence under Article 19(1) TEU.\n\nThe CJEU held that Article 19(1) TEU does not mandate any specific model of judicial appointments and does not require that political actors be entirely excluded from the process. What the provision requires is that, however judges are appointed, the overall conditions of judicial tenure and the practical operation of the judicial system ensure their independence in the exercise of their functions. A Prime Minister's role in appointments does not per se violate EU law, provided that the appointments are not conditioned on political compliance and that appointed judges enjoy adequate guarantees of independence thereafter.\n\nThe judgment provides an important counterbalance to the aggressive application of Article 19(1) TEU in the Polish cases, confirming that the provision is concerned with genuine independence in practice rather than a formalistic prohibition on any political involvement in judicial appointments. It is cited in Irish law in the context of the Judicial Appointments Commission reference and is important for comparative analysis of constitutional arrangements for judicial appointments across EU Member States.",
