    case_name: 'VQ v. Land Hessen',
    citation: 'Case C-272/19, EU:C:2020:535',
    year: 2020,
    court: 'Court of Justice of the European Union',
    jurisdiction: 'EU',
    legal_principle:
      'The independence requirements of Article 47 of the EU Charter apply to administrative tribunals adjudicating in areas covered by EU law as well as to ordinary courts; a body constituted by the executive without sufficient guarantees regarding the appointment, tenure, and removal of its members may not satisfy the independence requirement even if it exercises functions characterised as judicial in nature under domestic law.',
    key_quote:
      'The requirement of independence under Article 47 of the Charter encompasses the requirement that the body concerned exercise its functions wholly autonomously, without being subject to any hierarchical constraint or subordinated to any other body, and without taking orders or instructions from any source, thereby being protected against external interventions or pressure liable to impair the independent judgment of its members.',
    full_summary:
      'VQ v. Land Hessen is a CJEU preliminary reference decision examining whether a German administrative tribunal handling data protection matters constituted an independent body satisfying Article 47 of the EU Charter. The referring court asked whether a hearing panel whose members were civil servants subject to the ordinary civil service regime, without specific guarantees of independence or security of tenure, satisfied EU law requirements.\n\nThe CJEU held that Article 47 requires that adjudicative bodies operating in areas covered by EU law must meet minimum standards of independence, including protection of their members from external pressure, adequate security of tenure, and freedom from hierarchical subordination to the executive. The Court emphasised that the appearance of independence, as perceived by litigants, is as important as actual independence, since confidence in the impartiality of adjudicative bodies is fundamental to the rule of law.\n\nThe decision is valuable for its clear and systematic articulation of the components of judicial or tribunal independence under Article 47, distinguishing between external independence (freedom from governmental pressure) and internal independence (freedom from hierarchical pressure within the judicial institution itself). It is cited in discussions of what EU law requires of all adjudicative bodies, not just supreme or constitutional courts.',
