    case_name: 'Valente v. The Queen',
    citation: '[1985] 2 SCR 673',
    year: 1985,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Canada',
    jurisdiction: 'CA',
    legal_principle:
      'Judicial independence is a constitutional principle in Canadian law that encompasses three core conditions: security of tenure, financial security, and institutional independence of the court as a whole from the executive and legislative branches; these conditions must exist not only in form but in substance and in public appearance, as the reasonable perception of independence is itself constitutionally required.',
    key_quote:
      'The essence of security of tenure for purposes of s. 11(d) is a tenure, whether until an age of retirement, for a fixed term, or for a specific adjudicative task, that is secure against interference by the Executive or other appointing authority in a discretionary or arbitrary manner.',
    full_summary:
      'Valente v. The Queen is the foundational Supreme Court of Canada decision on judicial independence, establishing the three-component framework that has become the standard reference point in Canadian constitutional law and has been widely cited across common law jurisdictions including Ireland. The case arose from a challenge by a criminal defendant to the independence of Ontario Provincial Court judges, whose terms of office, salaries, and institutional arrangements differed from those of superior court judges.\n\nChief Justice Dickson, writing for the Court, held that the right to a fair hearing before an independent tribunal under section 11(d) of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms requires three conditions: first, security of tenure, meaning protection against arbitrary removal; second, financial security, meaning remuneration fixed by law rather than subject to executive discretion; and third, institutional independence, meaning that the court as a body has sufficient control over matters directly and necessarily related to the exercise of its judicial function to be free from executive interference.\n\nThe Valente framework has been adopted and cited by the Irish Supreme Court, the ECHR, and the CJEU as a comprehensive and analytically rigorous account of the essential components of judicial independence. It is a key comparative authority in FE-1 examinations on judicial independence and is frequently cited alongside \u00c1str\u00e1\u00f0sson and the CJEU decisions on Polish judicial reforms.',
