    case_name: 'Review of Judgment in Simpson v. Council and HG v. Commission',
    citation: 'Cases C-542/18 RX-II and C-543/18 RX-II, EU:C:2020:232',
    year: 2020,
    court: 'Court of Justice of the European Union',
    jurisdiction: 'EU',
    legal_principle:
      'The right to a tribunal established by law under Article 47 of the EU Charter applies to EU courts and institutions as well as to national courts; an irregularity in the appointment procedure of a judge to the EU General Court may, where it constitutes a manifest breach of the applicable rules, give rise to a violation of Article 47 and require review of judgments delivered by a panel including that judge. The CJEU confirmed that judicial independence and the right to a lawfully constituted tribunal bind the EU institutions themselves.',
    key_quote:
      'Article 47 of the Charter requires that the EU institutions and organs themselves observe the requirement of a tribunal established by law; an irregularity in the appointment of a judge to the General Court that constitutes a flagrant disregard of the applicable rules for appointment may infringe Article 47 and necessitate the review of judgments in which that judge participated.',
    full_summary:
      "This review judgment arose from an exceptional procedure under the Statute of the Court of Justice, pursuant to which the CJEU Reviews judgments of the General Court in cases where a serious issue affecting the unity or consistency of EU law arises. The relevant question was whether irregularities in the selection and appointment of a judge to the EU General Court \u2014 specifically, a deviation from the procedure laid down in Article 255 TFEU and the relevant secondary legislation \u2014 constituted a violation of Article 47 of the EU Charter.\n\nThe CJEU held that Article 47 is binding on the EU institutions themselves in the context of judicial appointments to EU courts. Applying the three-step test from \u00c1str\u00e1\u00f0sson (by analogy), the Court assessed whether the irregularity in the appointment procedure constituted a manifest breach of the applicable rules, whether it concerned a fundamental rule of the judicial appointment procedure, and whether it had been adequately remedied. In the particular case, the Court found that while there had been procedural irregularities, they did not rise to the level of a violation of Article 47 that would require the review and setting aside of the judgments delivered by the panel in question.\n\nThe decision is significant for the constitutional law of the EU because it confirms that the rule of law and the principle of a tribunal established by law apply within the EU's own institutional framework, and that the CJEU will scrutinise the validity of its own appointment procedures under Article 47. It is an important case for examinations on EU constitutional law and judicial independence.",
