    full_summary:
      "The plaintiff challenged the Electoral (Amendment) Act 2002 on the grounds that it established D\u00e1il constituencies that violated the requirements of Article 16 of the Constitution, in particular the requirement that the ratio of members to population be, so far as possible, the same throughout the country. The Supreme Court dismissed the challenge and confirmed the constitutionality of the Act. The Court reviewed the population data and the constituency boundaries established by the Act and found that, while there were some variations in the ratio of members to population between constituencies, these variations did not reach the level of constitutional invalidity. The Court affirmed the principle, established in earlier cases such as O'Donovan v. Attorney General [1961], that the Oireachtas has a degree of latitude in designing constituencies and that factors such as geography, community identity, and the practicalities of representation are legitimately taken into account. The constitutional standard is one of reasonable approximation and the courts will only intervene where the departures from equality are so significant as to amount to a systemic violation of the proportional representation guarantee. The case is a useful authority on the justiciability of electoral law questions and on the proper standard of constitutional review applicable to Oireachtas decisions on constituency design.",
