      "A further electoral law challenge brought by the plaintiff against constituency revision legislation on grounds of inequality in the member-to-population ratio. The Supreme Court applied and reinforced the principles already established in O'Donovan v. Attorney General [1961] and Kelly v. Minister for the Environment [2002]. The Court found that the constituencies as drawn were within the constitutional margin of tolerance and dismissed the challenge. The Court's reasoning elaborated on the nature of the constitutional obligation in Article 16.2, explaining that the phrase 'as far as practicable' imports a standard of genuine reasonable effort rather than one of mathematical exactitude. The Court also noted that the obligation to revise constituencies periodically, taken together with the inevitability of population movements between revisions, meant that some variation would always exist and could not of itself render legislation unconstitutional. The judgment is significant as part of a trilogy of constituency revision cases that together define the constitutional limits of the Oireachtas's power to design the D\u00e1il electoral map. It is regularly cited in electoral law questions as authority for the proposition that courts adopt a deferential approach to Oireachtas decisions on constituency design provided those decisions reflect a reasonable attempt to comply with the constitutional mandate.",
