      "The plaintiff challenged certain procedural requirements governing the exercise of the right to vote in D\u00e1il elections, arguing that they imposed unjustified restrictions on the constitutional franchise. The High Court examined the relationship between the constitutional right to vote guaranteed by Article 16 and the power of the Oireachtas to regulate the modalities of elections. The Court confirmed that the right to vote, while constitutionally protected, is not absolute in the sense that no procedural regulation is permissible; the Oireachtas may impose requirements directed at the orderly and legitimate conduct of elections, including registration requirements, identification procedures, and residency conditions. However, any such requirement must be proportionate to the aim pursued and must not have the effect of systematically excluding categories of citizens from the franchise in a manner not justified by the constitutional text. The case is a useful illustration of the balance between the constitutional guarantee of universal suffrage and the legitimate regulatory role of the legislature in administering elections, and it forms part of the broader body of electoral law jurisprudence that includes O'Donovan, Kelly, and King.",
