    legal_principle:
      'The separation of powers principle embodied in the Constitution precludes the courts from issuing a writ of mandamus to compel the executive to implement a specific legislative or policy measure, even where the courts are satisfied that the plaintiff has a constitutional entitlement that has not been vindicated. The courts may declare rights and grant relief in respect of established violations, but may not usurp the executive function by directing government to adopt particular policies or measures, as this would amount to an encroachment on the domain of the executive and legislature.',
