    full_summary:
      "The applicant sought an order of mandamus compelling the government to implement provisions of the Civil Liability Act 1961 that had not been brought into force by ministerial order. The Supreme Court refused the relief sought, holding that mandamus could not be used to compel the executive to exercise its discretion to bring statutory provisions into operation. The Court applied the separation of powers principle in a manner that reflected the institutional limits of judicial power: while the courts are the guardians of constitutional rights and may grant appropriate remedies for their breach, they may not substitute their judgment for that of the executive in matters that fall within the executive's domain. The decision draws a clear distinction between the judicial function of identifying and remedying constitutional violations and the executive function of determining how and when legislative measures are to be implemented. This limitation on judicial relief has been affirmed in subsequent cases and is significant for understanding the scope of constitutional remedies in Ireland. The case is frequently contrasted with decisions in which courts have been willing to make declarations of constitutional invalidity and to grant other remedies, illustrating the precise contours of what courts will and will not do when executive inaction is at issue.",
