    court: 'Supreme Court',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      "The constitutional rights of Irish citizen children, including the right to the care and company of their parents, must be weighed against the State's power to deport non-national parents, and in certain circumstances the deportation of the parents of Irish citizen children may constitute an unconstitutional interference with those children's rights under Article 40.3 and Article 41. The Supreme Court held that the Minister for Justice is not obliged in all cases to permit a non-national parent to remain in the State solely by reason of having an Irish citizen child, but must consider the constitutional rights of the child as part of the deportation decision.",
    key_quote:
      'The fact that a non-national has an Irish citizen child does not confer an automatic right of residency, but the constitutional rights of the citizen child, including the right to the care and company of both parents, are matters that must be considered and weighed by the Minister in the exercise of the deportation power.',
    full_summary:
      "These consolidated appeals raised the question of whether non-national parents of Irish citizen children born in Ireland were entitled to remain in the State by virtue of their children's citizenship. The cases arose in the context of a very large number of applications for leave to remain and related to what was then a significant legal and political controversy in Ireland about 'citizenship tourism'. The Supreme Court rejected the argument that the constitutional rights of Irish citizen children automatically precluded the deportation of their non-national parents, but affirmed that the Minister must have regard to those rights in the exercise of the deportation power. The Court drew a distinction between a right of the child to reside in Ireland, which could not be denied, and an asserted right of the non-national parent to reside in Ireland by derivation from the child's citizenship, which the Court declined to recognise as absolute. The decision had major practical consequences for immigration law and ultimately contributed to the political context for the Twenty-seventh Amendment of the Constitution (the Citizenship Referendum) of 2004, which removed the automatic entitlement to Irish citizenship of children born in Ireland to non-national parents. The case is significant at the intersection of constitutional rights, immigration law, and the rights of the family under Article 41.",
