    case_name: 'The Attorney General v. X',
    citation: '[1992] 1 IR 1',
    year: 1992,
    court: 'Supreme Court',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'Article 40.3.3 of the Constitution, as inserted by the Eighth Amendment, protects the equal right to life of the unborn and the mother, and where there is a real and substantial risk to the life of the mother, including a risk of suicide, the right of the unborn does not take precedence over the right of the mother to have that risk averted. The Supreme Court held that an injunction preventing a fourteen-year-old rape victim from travelling to England for an abortion was wrongly granted and set it aside, confirming that a termination of pregnancy is constitutionally permissible in Ireland where there is a real and substantial risk to the life, as distinct from the health, of the mother that can only be averted by the termination.',
    key_quote:
      'Where there is a real and substantial risk to the life of the mother, as distinct from her health, which can only be avoided by the termination of her pregnancy, such termination is lawful, having regard to the true meaning of Article 40.3.3, which requires the courts to balance the equal right to life of the unborn and the mother.',
    full_summary:
      "This is perhaps the most significant and controversial constitutional law decision of the twentieth century in Ireland. The plaintiff, a fourteen-year-old girl who had been raped, was brought by her parents to England to obtain an abortion. The Attorney General obtained an injunction in the High Court restraining her from travelling. The Supreme Court, by majority, set aside the injunction. The Court construed Article 40.3.3, which was inserted into the Constitution by the Eighth Amendment in 1983 and which guaranteed the equal right to life of the unborn with due regard to the equal right to life of the mother, as permitting a termination where there was a real and substantial risk to the life of the mother, including a risk of suicide. The Court rejected the argument that the constitutional guarantee protected the life of the unborn absolutely in all circumstances. The decision caused enormous controversy and political debate. It gave rise to three further constitutional referenda: the Thirteenth Amendment, protecting the right to travel; the Fourteenth Amendment, protecting the right to information about abortion services abroad; and a failed referendum on the suicide ground itself. The issue was not fully legislatively resolved until the Protection of Life During Pregnancy Act 2013, and the Eighth Amendment itself was repealed by the Thirty-sixth Amendment in 2018. The X case is a foundational authority on constitutional interpretation, the relationship between rights, and the courts' power to develop constitutional doctrine from sparse text.",
