    case_name: 'A v. Governor of Arbour Hill Prison',
    citation: '[2006] IESC 45, [2006] 4 IR 88',
    year: 2006,
    court: 'Supreme Court',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'A declaration of unconstitutionality of a statute does not have automatic retrospective effect entitling all persons convicted under that statute to release or to have their convictions set aside. The Supreme Court held that, applying principles of legal certainty and finality, the retrospective effect of a declaration of unconstitutionality is limited and does not operate to disturb convictions that have been finally determined, even where those convictions were obtained under a provision subsequently held unconstitutional. The courts may, in the interests of justice, mould the retrospective effect of such declarations to avoid disproportionate disruption to the legal order.',
    key_quote:
      'A declaration that a statute is inconsistent with the Constitution does not require the courts to treat as void every act done and every conviction obtained under that statute while it remained in force; the retrospective effect of such a declaration is limited by considerations of finality, justice and the avoidance of disproportionate disruption to the legal order.',
    full_summary:
      'This case arose directly from the decision in CC v. Ireland [2006], in which the Supreme Court had declared unconstitutional the provision of the Criminal Law Amendment Act 1935 creating a strict liability offence of unlawful carnal knowledge of girls under fifteen. The applicant in Arbour Hill, who had been convicted under the same provision and whose conviction had become final, sought his release on the basis that he had been convicted under an unconstitutional statute. The Supreme Court refused the application and confirmed that the declaration of unconstitutionality in CC did not operate to require the release of persons already lawfully convicted under the provision before it was struck down. The Court carefully distinguished between the position of persons whose convictions were still subject to appeal or challenge at the time of the declaration and those whose convictions had already become final. The Court reasoned that the legal certainty principle and the presumption of constitutionality supported the view that convictions obtained under a statute in force at the time were not automatically rendered void by a later declaration of unconstitutionality. This was a significant constitutional development that departed from the absolutist view that unconstitutional statutes are void ab initio and that nothing done under them can have legal effect. The case is a cornerstone of the law on constitutional remedies and retroactivity and is invariably examined in conjunction with Murphy v. Attorney General and CC v. Ireland.',
