    legal_principle:
      'A person detained who fails to challenge the legality of their detention at the earliest practicable opportunity may be found to have acquiesced in their detention and may thereby lose the right to seek a conditional order of habeas corpus under Article 40 at a later stage. The Supreme Court held that the doctrines of acquiescence, laches, and delay operate in constitutional proceedings under Article 40, and that a detained person who sits on their rights and allows substantial time to pass without objecting to their detention may be estopped from subsequently relying on a technical invalidity in the warrant or the means of detention.',
    key_quote:
      'A person who delays substantially in seeking an inquiry into the legality of their detention under Article 40, and who has in the meantime participated in the proceedings giving rise to that detention without objection, may be found to have acquiesced in their detention and will not be heard to challenge it on a technical ground that could and should have been raised at the outset.',
    full_summary:
      'The applicant, who had been convicted and was serving a sentence, sought a conditional order of habeas corpus under Article 40 of the Constitution, alleging that a technical irregularity in the warrant of detention rendered his detention unlawful. The Supreme Court refused the application on the basis that the applicant had acquiesced in his detention by participating throughout the trial without raising any objection to the alleged irregularity, and had further delayed without explanation before bringing the Article 40 inquiry. The Court held that the equitable doctrine of acquiescence and the related concept of estoppel operate in constitutional proceedings, including in the context of the fundamental right to liberty guaranteed by Article 40.4. The Court was at pains to note that this did not mean that a detained person who has a real and substantial ground for challenging the legality of their detention would be refused relief merely because of delay; but where the ground of challenge is purely technical and where the conduct of the applicant is inconsistent with a genuine belief that the detention was unlawful, the courts will not grant relief. Byrne v. Frawley is an important qualification on the broad constitutional right to challenge detention under Article 40 and is relevant to any question on constitutional remedies and their limits.',
