      'At the time of this decision the State enjoyed a broad immunity from suit in tort by reason of its sovereign status, and the courts declined to hold the State liable in the same manner as a private defendant. This decision established the foundational doctrine of State immunity in Irish tort law, which was subsequently fundamentally altered by the Supreme Court in Byrne v. Ireland [1972], in which the Court held that the doctrine of sovereign immunity had no place in Irish constitutional law and that the State could be sued in tort in the same manner as any other defendant.',
