      "The plaintiff sought to recover damages from the Minister for Finance in respect of a loss caused by an agent of the State. The Supreme Court, following the pre-existing doctrine that the State and its Ministers enjoyed immunity from suit in tort, declined to impose liability. The decision represents the pre-Byrne v. Ireland position of Irish law on State liability in tort and is primarily significant as a point of contrast with the later development of the law. In Byrne v. Ireland [1972] the Supreme Court carried out a fundamental re-examination of the question and held, by reference to the constitutional text and the principle that the State derives its authority from and is accountable to the people, that sovereign immunity had no basis in the Irish constitutional order. O'Byrne v. Minister for Finance is therefore most useful in constitutional law study as an illustration of how judicial doctrine can evolve dramatically through constitutional interpretation, and it is typically examined as the 'before' to the 'after' of Byrne v. Ireland. It is also relevant to the history of Article 29.1 and discussions of sovereignty and State accountability in constitutional law courses.",
