    full_summary:
      'The applicant sought leave to apply for judicial review of a decision by the Director of Public Prosecutions. The Supreme Court took the opportunity to clarify the applicable standard for the grant of leave to judicially review decisions in constitutional and public law matters. The Court confirmed that the threshold is one of arguable grounds, a standard lower than that of a prima facie case but higher than the mere formality of asserting a ground of challenge. The leave stage is intended to be a filter against clearly unmeritorious or abusive applications, not a preliminary trial of the issues. The Court also addressed the procedural requirements for applications for leave, including the need for full and frank disclosure of all relevant facts, the time limits for bringing applications, and the circumstances in which an extension of time may be granted. G v. Director of Public Prosecutions is a foundational procedural authority in Irish judicial review and constitutional litigation, and it is relevant whenever a question touches on standing, leave requirements, or the procedural architecture of constitutional challenges.',
