      'Every person accused of a criminal offence has a constitutional right to a trial with reasonable expedition under Article 38 of the Constitution, and where prosecutorial delay is of such duration and character as to create a real risk of an unfair trial or to constitute oppression of the accused, an order prohibiting the trial may be granted. The Supreme Court set out a two-limbed test for the prohibition of a criminal trial on grounds of delay: the applicant must establish both that the delay was significant and blameworthy, and that the accused suffered actual or real prejudice as a result of that delay.',
