    full_summary:
      'The applicant, who had been charged with historical sexual offences, sought to prohibit his trial on the grounds of prosecutorial delay, arguing that the delay of several decades between the alleged offences and the commencement of proceedings gave rise to a real risk of an unfair trial and violated his constitutional right under Article 38 to a trial with reasonable expedition. The Supreme Court granted the order of prohibition and articulated the two-limbed test for delay cases in the criminal context. First, the applicant must show that the delay was blameworthy in the sense that it was attributable to the prosecution or the investigating authorities rather than to the accused himself. Second, the applicant must demonstrate real and actual prejudice \u2014 such as the death of witnesses, the loss of evidence, or a specific and demonstrable inability to mount an effective defence \u2014 caused by the delay. The Court emphasised that the mere passage of time, without evidence of concrete prejudice, will not generally suffice to justify prohibiting a trial, but where both elements are established the courts will act to vindicate the constitutional right to a fair trial. DC v. DPP is the leading authority on delay and the right to trial with reasonable expedition, and it is a key case for FE-1 questions on Article 38 and fair trial rights.',
