    legal_principle:
      'The State has a constitutional obligation under Article 40.3 to take positive steps to vindicate the personal rights of citizens, and this positive obligation may in certain circumstances require the Oireachtas to enact legislation to protect those rights where the absence of legislation leaves a constitutional right unprotected. The High Court held that the failure to provide adequate healthcare to prisoners amounted to a breach of the constitutional right to bodily integrity and that the State was obliged to remedy the situation, though the Court was careful to respect the separation of powers by framing its order as declaratory rather than prescriptive of the specific measures to be adopted.',
    key_quote:
      "The State's obligation to vindicate personal rights under Article 40.3 is not discharged merely by refraining from acting against those rights; in appropriate cases the Constitution imposes a positive duty to act to protect rights, and failure to provide adequate healthcare to persons in State custody may constitute a breach of the right to bodily integrity.",
    full_summary:
      "The plaintiff, a prisoner, brought proceedings against the State challenging the adequacy of healthcare provision in Irish prisons, arguing that the failure to provide appropriate medical treatment violated his constitutional right to bodily integrity under Article 40.3. The High Court found in favour of the plaintiff, holding that the State was under a positive constitutional obligation to vindicate the right to bodily integrity, which included the provision of reasonably adequate healthcare to persons held in State custody. The Court was careful, however, to limit its order to a declaration that the plaintiff's constitutional rights had been violated, rather than making a prescriptive order directing specific measures, in order to respect the separation of powers and the executive's function in determining how constitutional obligations are implemented. The case is significant as an illustration of the positive dimensions of constitutional rights under Article 40.3 and of the willingness of the courts to impose enforceable constitutional obligations on the State to provide services. It is also relevant to the broader question of the extent to which social and economic rights are protected by the Constitution, and it is frequently examined alongside cases such as State (Sheehan) v. Government of Ireland for its treatment of the limits on judicial prescription of remedies.",
