    case_name: "O'Reilly v. Limerick Corporation",
    citation: '[1989] ILRM 181',
    year: 1989,
    court: 'High Court',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'The Irish High Court held that the courts cannot impose a positive obligation on the State or a local authority to provide accommodation for persons in need of housing, and that socio-economic rights of this kind are not justiciable as against the State in the same manner as civil and political rights. Costello J drew a fundamental distinction between negative rights \u2014 which the State must not infringe \u2014 and positive rights \u2014 which would require the State to expend public resources \u2014 and concluded that the enforcement of the latter belongs to the political branches of government, not the judiciary. The case is the leading Irish authority for the proposition that the separation of powers constrains the extent to which Article 40.3 can be invoked to compel the executive to provide welfare services or housing.',
    key_quote:
      'To compel the State to provide a particular form of social service would be to compel the executive to exercise its administrative and political functions in a particular way \u2014 that is a function which is not vested in the courts by the Constitution.',
    full_summary:
      'The plaintiffs were members of the Traveller community who lived in conditions of severe poverty and inadequate shelter on the outskirts of Limerick. They sought to rely on Article 40.3 of the Constitution \u2014 the guarantee of personal rights \u2014 to compel Limerick Corporation to provide them with adequate accommodation. Costello J in the High Court dismissed the claim. He reasoned that a sharp distinction must be drawn between negative constitutional rights, which prohibit the State from interfering with protected interests, and positive socio-economic rights, which would require the State to deploy public resources to improve the material conditions of citizens. The former are fully justiciable; the latter are, in his view, non-justiciable in the sense that their implementation requires political choices about the allocation of public funds, choices that fall within the domain of the executive and legislature rather than the courts. He rejected the argument that Article 40.3 could be construed as imposing an enforceable positive duty to provide housing. The decision has remained a foundational authority in Irish constitutional law for the limits on judicially enforceable socio-economic rights, and is frequently contrasted with South African and Indian jurisprudence where positive rights have been enforced. The case anticipates the later Supreme Court authority of TD v. Minister for Education in holding that separation of powers restrains judicial intervention in resource allocation.',
