    full_summary:
      "RAS Medical Ltd challenged a decision by the Royal College of Surgeons in Ireland (RCSI) relating to accreditation of a private hospital for the purposes of surgical training. RCSI argued that, as a body incorporated by royal charter rather than statute, its decisions were not subject to constitutional fair procedures and could only be challenged in contract. The Supreme Court rejected this argument and held that the constitutional guarantees of fair procedures apply wherever a body, regardless of its formal legal character, exercises functions that are effectively public in scope and whose decisions have significant adverse effects on individuals' rights or livelihoods. The court reasoned that the constitutional guarantee of fair procedures \u2014 derived from Article 40.3 and the general principles of constitutional justice \u2014 is not merely a constraint on statutory decision-making but reflects a fundamental commitment to procedural fairness throughout Irish law. The decision is significant in confirming that the public/private divide does not determine the application of constitutional procedural guarantees; rather, the nature of the function and its impact on affected parties is the controlling consideration. This has implications for decisions made by professional bodies, sporting associations, and other quasi-public entities. The case is also relevant to administrative law and is sometimes examined in the context of judicial review of private bodies.",
