    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'The Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of COVID-19 emergency regulations restricting movement and commercial activity, finding that the restrictions pursued a legitimate aim of protecting public health and were proportionate to that aim in the circumstances of a declared public health emergency. The court affirmed that constitutional rights, including the right to earn a livelihood and the right to liberty, are not absolute and may be restricted by law where the restriction is rationally connected to a pressing objective and goes no further than necessary. The case is a significant modern authority on proportionality review of emergency legislation affecting fundamental rights.',
    key_quote:
      'Constitutional rights do not disappear in a public health emergency; but they may be proportionately limited where the State demonstrates a pressing need, a rational connection between the restriction and its objective, and that the interference is no greater than is necessary to achieve that objective.',
    full_summary:
      'The applicant, Mr. Braney, operated a business that was required to close under COVID-19 emergency regulations made pursuant to the Health (Preservation and Protection and other Emergency Measures in the Public Interest) Act 2020. He challenged the constitutional validity of those regulations, arguing that they unjustifiably interfered with his right to earn a livelihood, his property rights, and his right to liberty. The Supreme Court dismissed the challenge. The court applied the proportionality test as developed in Irish constitutional jurisprudence, examining whether the restrictions (i) pursued a legitimate aim; (ii) were rationally connected to that aim; (iii) impaired the relevant rights as little as possible; and (iv) maintained a fair balance between the rights of the individual and the interests of the community. In the context of an unprecedented global pandemic, the court held that the Government had established sufficient justification for the measures, noting the deference owed to expert public health judgment in conditions of genuine scientific uncertainty. The decision is notable for its discussion of the margin of appreciation afforded to the executive in times of emergency, the role of judicial review during crises, and the continued application of proportionality analysis even in emergency conditions. It is contrasted with cases involving disproportionate peacetime restrictions on rights.',
