    full_summary:
      'Digital Rights Ireland Ltd, a company concerned with digital rights advocacy, challenged the constitutionality of legislative provisions requiring telecommunications companies to retain data \u2014 including records of calls, texts, and internet activity \u2014 relating to all subscribers, for periods of up to two years, for law enforcement purposes. The company argued that the blanket and indiscriminate data retention regime violated the constitutional right to privacy protected under Article 40.3 and the EU Charter rights under Articles 7 (privacy) and 8 (data protection). The High Court (McKechnie J) found that the provisions raised serious constitutional and EU law concerns, particularly regarding proportionality \u2014 the retention applied to all persons without any requirement of suspicion of involvement in criminal activity. The court referred questions to the CJEU under Article 267 TFEU as to the validity of the Data Retention Directive (2006/24/EC) under the Charter. The subsequent CJEU ruling in Digital Rights Ireland (C-293/12) in 2014 invalidated the Directive as disproportionate under EU law. The domestic constitutional challenge was ultimately not fully adjudicated in light of the CJEU ruling, but the case is a leading Irish authority on the constitutional dimensions of digital privacy, data retention, and the interaction between constitutional rights and EU fundamental rights law. It is frequently tested in both constitutional law and EU law contexts.',
