    legal_principle:
      'The UK Supreme Court held that a mandatory injunction \u2014 compelling a local authority to comply with its positive duty to provide suitable accommodation for a homeless person under the Housing Act 1996 \u2014 was an available remedy and should have been granted by the lower courts, reversing the traditional reluctance to issue mandatory orders against public authorities in housing cases. The court affirmed that where a statutory positive duty has been clearly established and persistently breached, the courts may enforce compliance through mandatory injunctive relief, not merely through declaratory orders or judicial review. The case is a significant comparative authority in the Irish socio-economic rights debate, indicating that even in common law systems without a directly enforceable constitutional right to housing, courts can enforce statutory positive housing obligations through coercive orders.',
