    legal_principle:
      'The High Court held that the decision to permit the use of Shannon Airport by US military aircraft during the Iraq War was a matter of foreign policy and defence, falling within the non-justiciable domain of executive discretion under Article 29 of the Constitution, and that the courts had no role in reviewing the substantive wisdom or legality of such foreign policy decisions under domestic constitutional law. Peart J affirmed that Article 29 vests the conduct of foreign affairs exclusively in the Government and that the courts will not substitute their judgment for that of the executive in this sphere, even where the plaintiff asserts that the State is in breach of international law. The case is a significant authority on the limits of justiciability in the foreign policy domain.',
    key_quote:
      'The conduct of foreign affairs, including decisions relating to the use of Irish territory for military purposes by friendly states, falls within the exclusive domain of the executive under Article 29 of the Constitution and is not justiciable before the courts on the merits.',
    full_summary:
      "The plaintiff, Edward Horgan, a former army officer and peace activist, challenged the decision of the Irish Government to permit United States military transport aircraft to transit through Shannon Airport during the 2003 invasion of Iraq. He argued that this decision was unconstitutional as it rendered Ireland a co-belligerent in an unlawful war, in breach of Ireland's obligations under international law, in breach of Ireland's traditional policy of neutrality, and in breach of the right to peace which he argued was an unenumerated right under Article 40.3. The High Court dismissed the claim entirely. On the question of foreign policy, the court held that Article 29 vests the conduct of foreign relations in the Government, and that the courts have no jurisdiction to review the merits of such decisions. On the question of an unenumerated right to peace, the court declined to recognise such a right as justiciable and enforceable. The case is important for the breadth of the non-justiciability doctrine in foreign affairs, and illustrates how the courts defer almost entirely to the executive in matters of international relations, defence, and diplomatic policy. It is also relevant to discussions of the constitutional status of international law in Ireland, the nature of Irish neutrality, and the limits of unenumerated rights.",
