      "The Court of Appeal upheld the constitutionality of Revenue Commissioners' powers in the context of a tax assessment and enforcement action, finding that the relevant provisions pursued a legitimate aim of ensuring tax compliance and the protection of public finances, and that any interference with the plaintiff's property rights was proportionate to that aim. The court applied the established proportionality test and confirmed that broad statutory powers conferred on the Revenue Commissioners do not violate constitutional property rights under Article 43 or personal rights under Article 40.3, provided they operate within a framework of fair procedures and are rationally connected to a legitimate legislative purpose. The case affirms the constitutional permissibility of wide Revenue enforcement powers subject to oversight and review.",
