    full_summary:
      'Mr. Brady challenged the constitutional validity of certain powers exercised by the Revenue Commissioners in connection with a tax assessment and enforcement process. He argued that the statutory powers in question \u2014 which allowed the Revenue to make assessments and take enforcement action affecting his financial affairs and property \u2014 violated his property rights under Article 43 and his personal rights under Article 40.3, in particular his right to livelihood and to fair procedures. The Court of Appeal rejected the constitutional challenge. Applying the proportionality test as formulated in Heaney v. Ireland and later refined in Irish jurisprudence, the court found that the statutory powers pursued the legitimate aim of ensuring tax compliance and protecting public revenues, that they were rationally connected to that aim, and that the means employed were proportionate and accompanied by adequate procedural protections including rights of appeal to the Tax Appeals Commission and the courts. The court emphasised that tax collection is a core function of the State and that the Oireachtas has broad latitude in designing revenue enforcement mechanisms. The case is a useful authority on the interaction between constitutional property rights, the right to livelihood, and broad regulatory powers conferred on State bodies, and on the application of proportionality review in this context.',
