    full_summary:
      "The applicant, B.F., sought an order prohibiting his prosecution for a large number of historical sexual offences said to have been committed many years before the complaint was made to the Garda\u00ed. He argued that the delay between the alleged offences and the date of trial was so lengthy as to render a fair trial impossible, and that he was constitutionally entitled to have the prosecution stayed under Article 38.1. The Supreme Court considered the principles governing delay in historical sexual abuse cases, which present particular difficulties because victims may not report abuse until many years after it occurred, often as adults, following psychological recovery. The court held that, in such cases, a distinction must be drawn between complainant delay (delay caused by the victim's failure to report promptly) and prosecutorial delay (delay between the complaint being made and the charge or trial). The constitutional right to trial with expedition is primarily engaged by the latter category. The court also confirmed that the applicant must establish either specific prejudice \u2014 such as the death of a witness whose evidence would have assisted the defence \u2014 or that the delay is so grossly excessive that prejudice can be inferred. The case remains a foundational authority on delay in Irish criminal proceedings, particularly historical abuse prosecutions, and is frequently tested at FE-1.",
