    case_name: 'Donoghue v. Director of Public Prosecutions',
    citation: '[2014] IESC 56; [2014] 2 IR 762',
    year: 2014,
    court: 'Supreme Court',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      "The Supreme Court clarified and restated the principles governing applications to prohibit criminal trials on the ground of delay, holding that the key question is whether delay has given rise to a real risk of an unfair trial, and that mere lapse of time, without identifiable prejudice, will not of itself justify a stay on proceedings. The court emphasised that prosecutorial delay is assessed by reference to whether delay is inordinate and inexcusable and whether it has caused actual prejudice to the accused's ability to defend himself; where such prejudice is established, the court must then balance the accused's rights against the public interest in prosecution. The judgment is the leading modern authority consolidating the Irish law of delay in criminal proceedings.",
    key_quote:
      'The mere passage of time, without more, will not justify the prohibition of a trial. The applicant must establish that delay was inordinate and inexcusable, that it caused real prejudice to his ability to defend himself, and that, in all the circumstances, the trial should not proceed.',
    full_summary:
      "The applicant sought judicial review to prohibit his trial on criminal charges, arguing that prosecutorial delay in bringing the case to trial had violated his constitutional right under Article 38.1 to a trial with reasonable expedition and had prejudiced his ability to defend himself. The Supreme Court delivered a comprehensive restatement of the legal principles applicable to delay applications in criminal proceedings. The court held that the test requires the applicant to establish: first, that delay was inordinate and inexcusable; second, that the delay caused real prejudice to the applicant's ability to mount a defence; and third, that, weighing all the circumstances, the balance of justice requires that the trial be prohibited. The court moved away from the earlier formulation that suggested some categories of prejudice were presumed, clarifying that identifiable prejudice must generally be demonstrated. The judgment distinguishes between different sources of delay \u2014 pre-charge delay, prosecutorial delay, and court list delay \u2014 and provides guidance on the weight to be given to each. Donoghue is the most frequently cited modern authority on delay in criminal proceedings and has substantially clarified and simplified the applicable principles since the earlier cases of P.M. v. Malone and B.F. v. DPP. It is an essential case for FE-1 candidates studying Article 38 and the right to a fair trial.",
