      "D.K. sought to prohibit his trial on charges of historical sexual abuse, arguing that delay between the alleged offences and the date of trial rendered it impossible for him to receive a fair trial. The offences were alleged to have taken place many years before the complaint, and the applicant contended that memories of potential witnesses had faded, that alibi evidence was no longer available, and that the sheer passage of time had fundamentally compromised his defence. The Supreme Court dismissed the application. The court affirmed the framework established in B.F. v. DPP for addressing delay in historical abuse cases but provided additional guidance on the balance to be struck between the accused's rights and the rights of complainants. It held that the courts must not treat complainant delay as equivalent to prosecutorial delay: where a victim did not report abuse promptly due to psychological trauma, shame, or fear, this form of delay cannot be attributed to the State and does not of itself ground a prohibition. The court also addressed the question of whether general prejudice \u2014 arising simply from the passage of time \u2014 could justify a stay without specific identifiable prejudice, finding that the threshold is high. D.K. is an important complement to B.F. v. DPP and Donoghue v. DPP, completing the trilogy of leading Supreme Court authorities on constitutional delay in abuse cases.",
