      "The Court of Appeal restated and applied the principles governing applications to stay criminal prosecutions on grounds of delay, confirming that the test requires establishment of inordinate and inexcusable delay that has caused real prejudice to the applicant, and that the court must then weigh all relevant circumstances including the public interest in prosecution and the gravity of the alleged offences. The court emphasised that applications to prohibit trials on delay grounds face a high threshold and that, in the absence of identifiable specific prejudice to the ability to mount a defence, prohibitions will rarely be granted. The judgment represents the Court of Appeal's most recent comprehensive application of the Donoghue v. DPP framework.",
