      "The Supreme Court held that Article 38 of the Constitution, which provides that no person shall be tried on any criminal charge save in due course of law, enshrines minimum procedural standards of fairness and legality that must be observed in every criminal trial, and that any procedure which departs materially from those minimum standards will result in the trial being constitutionally invalid. The case is a foundational early authority on the constitutional minimum of criminal procedure, establishing that the phrase 'due course of law' in Article 38.1 is not merely descriptive but imposes substantive requirements of procedural justice. It anticipates the more elaborate later development of constitutional justice principles in Irish criminal law.",
