      "The phrase 'due course of law' in Article 38.1 is not a merely formal requirement; it imports minimum substantive standards of procedural fairness and legality without which no criminal trial can be said to have taken place in accordance with the Constitution.",
    full_summary:
      "The applicant challenged the legality of his criminal trial on the basis that certain procedural requirements had not been observed, and that as a result his conviction was rendered constitutionally void under Article 38.1. The Supreme Court examined the meaning and scope of the phrase 'in due course of law' in Article 38.1. The court held that this phrase requires compliance not merely with the formal procedural steps prescribed by statute and court rules, but with minimum substantive standards of fairness and legality derived from the Constitution itself. The court reasoned that Article 38 would be reduced to an empty form if it merely required that a trial follow the steps prescribed by the legislature without any minimum constitutional content. Accordingly, any trial conducted in flagrant disregard of fundamental procedural rights would fall outside the protection of Article 38.1. While the court did not provide an exhaustive catalogue of what 'due course of law' requires, the case establishes the foundational principle that constitutional minimum procedural standards apply in all criminal proceedings. It is an early and frequently cited authority on the constitutional basis of criminal procedure in Ireland and is read alongside later cases such as State (O'Rourke) v. Kelly and Re Haughey as part of the development of constitutional justice in the criminal context.",
