    case_name: 'R. v. Oakes',
    citation: '[1986] 1 SCR 103',
    year: 1986,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Canada',
    jurisdiction: 'CA',
    legal_principle:
      "The Supreme Court of Canada established the foundational proportionality framework \u2014 known as the Oakes test \u2014 for determining whether a law that infringes a right guaranteed by the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms can be justified under s.1 as a 'reasonable limit.' The government must demonstrate that the legislative objective is pressing and substantial, and then satisfy a three-part proportionality analysis: the measure must be rationally connected to the objective, must minimally impair the right, and the effects of the limitation must be proportionate to the objective pursued. The Oakes test has been widely adopted and adapted in common law jurisdictions, including Ireland, where proportionality review of rights-limiting legislation is now an established constitutional methodology.",
    key_quote:
      'To establish that a limit is reasonable and demonstrably justified in a free and democratic society, two central criteria must be satisfied. First, the objective of the measure must be pressing and substantial. Second, the means chosen must be proportional \u2014 rationally connected to the objective, minimally impairing of the right, and proportionate in their effects.',
    full_summary:
      "David Oakes was charged with unlawful possession of a narcotic for the purpose of trafficking under the Narcotic Control Act. The Act provided that once possession of a narcotic was proved, the accused was presumed to have it for the purpose of trafficking unless the contrary was established on the balance of probabilities. Oakes challenged this reverse onus provision as inconsistent with the presumption of innocence guaranteed by s.11(d) of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms. The Supreme Court of Canada agreed that the provision violated the presumption of innocence. The court then turned to s.1 of the Charter, which permits rights to be limited by 'reasonable limits prescribed by law as can be demonstrably justified in a free and democratic society.' Chief Justice Dickson, writing for the court, laid down the celebrated Oakes test as the standard for justifying Charter infringements under s.1. The test requires: first, that the objective of the law be pressing and substantial; and second, that the means be proportional in three respects \u2014 (i) the measure must be rationally connected to the objective, (ii) it must minimally impair the right (the least restrictive means reasonably available), and (iii) the effects on the right must be proportionate to the objective achieved. On the facts, the court found the provision could not be justified under s.1 and struck it down. The Oakes test has become one of the most cited constitutional law propositions in the common law world and is directly relevant to Irish proportionality review, which the Supreme Court has adopted in cases such as Heaney v. Ireland and the later development of proportionality analysis under Article 40 and the European Convention on Human Rights Act 2003.",
