    case_name: 'Andrews v. Law Society of British Columbia',
    citation: '[1989] 1 SCR 143',
    year: 1989,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Canada',
    jurisdiction: 'CA',
    legal_principle:
      'The Supreme Court of Canada delivered its first interpretation of s.15 of the Charter, the equality rights provision, rejecting a purely formal conception of equality in favour of a substantive approach focused on the impact of laws on disadvantaged groups. The court held that equality under s.15 is not simply about treating everyone the same but requires that the law not discriminate on the basis of enumerated or analogous grounds, with citizenship identified as an analogous ground to the listed characteristics. Substantive equality under s.15 demands attention to the actual effects of a distinction on those affected and the broader social context of disadvantage.',
    key_quote:
      'Equality must be substantive, not merely formal. A law does not violate equality simply by treating people differently; it violates equality when it draws a distinction on the basis of a personal characteristic that has the effect of imposing burdens or withholding benefits in a way that perpetuates disadvantage or prejudice.',
    full_summary:
      'Mark Andrews, a British subject who had fulfilled all the requirements to practise law in British Columbia except the citizenship requirement imposed by the Barristers and Solicitors Act, challenged the citizenship requirement as discriminatory on the basis of citizenship contrary to s.15 of the Charter. The Supreme Court of Canada used the case as the vehicle to give its first authoritative interpretation of the equality guarantee in s.15. Justice McIntyre, writing for the majority on the s.15 issue, rejected the formal equality approach \u2014 which would require only that the law treat similarly-situated people the same \u2014 and articulated a substantive conception of equality. The court held that s.15 prohibits discrimination on enumerated grounds (race, national or ethnic origin, colour, religion, sex, age, mental or physical disability) and on analogous grounds. Citizenship was identified as an analogous ground because non-citizens are a relatively powerless group in society and subject to political marginalization. The citizenship requirement imposed a burden on non-citizens that was not imposed on citizens, and this constituted discrimination on an analogous ground. The law was then subjected to s.1 justification analysis and was struck down as not justifiable. Andrews v. Law Society is the foundational equality case under the Canadian Charter and its articulation of substantive equality, analogous grounds, and the relationship between formal and substantive equality has been cited extensively in Irish equality litigation, particularly in cases dealing with analogous grounds under the Employment Equality Acts and the Equal Status Acts.',
