    case_name: 'Law v. Canada (Minister of Employment and Immigration)',
    citation: '[1999] 1 SCR 497',
    year: 1999,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Canada',
    jurisdiction: 'CA',
    legal_principle:
      "The Supreme Court of Canada reformulated the approach to equality under s.15 of the Charter by making human dignity the central touchstone of the analysis, introducing a three-stage test asking: does the law draw a formal or substantive distinction on an enumerated or analogous ground? Does the distinction result in disadvantage by perpetuating prejudice or stereotyping? And does the distinction violate the essential human dignity of the claimant, assessed contextually? The judgment was the leading Canadian equality authority for nearly a decade and its human dignity analysis has influenced Irish courts in equality cases addressing the O'Meara and Donnelly lines of authority under Article 40.1.",
    key_quote:
      'The purpose of s.15(1) is to prevent the violation of essential human dignity and freedom through the imposition of disadvantage, stereotyping, or political or social prejudice, and to promote a society in which all persons enjoy equal recognition at law as human beings or as members of Canadian society, equally capable and equally deserving of concern, respect and consideration.',
    full_summary:
      "Nancy Law, a young widow who had been left without survivor's pension benefits under the Canada Pension Plan because she was under 35 and had no dependent children or disability, challenged the age-based distinctions in the CPP scheme as discriminatory under s.15 of the Charter. The Supreme Court unanimously dismissed the challenge but used the case to deliver a comprehensive recalibration of the s.15 equality analysis. Justice Iacobucci, writing for a unanimous court, reformulated the approach from Andrews v. Law Society of British Columbia and articulated a three-stage contextual test for s.15 claims: first, whether the law imposes differential treatment, either on its face or in its effects, between the claimant and others; second, whether the differential treatment is based on one or more enumerated or analogous grounds; and third, whether the differential treatment constitutes substantive discrimination in that it violates the claimant's human dignity by perpetuating disadvantage, prejudice, or stereotyping. The court identified four contextual factors relevant to the dignity analysis: (1) pre-existing disadvantage of the affected group; (2) correspondence between the distinction and actual needs, capacities, or circumstances; (3) the ameliorative purpose or effect of the law on a more disadvantaged group; and (4) the nature of the interest affected. On the facts, the court held that the age-based distinctions in the CPP reflected the actual circumstances of younger widows who were better placed to re-enter the workforce and did not violate human dignity. Law v. Canada has been cited comparatively in Irish equality jurisprudence, particularly in discussions of the O'Meara v. Minister for Social and Family Affairs decision on gender-neutral contributory widow's pension entitlements.",
