    case_name: 'R. v. Kapp',
    citation: '[2008] 2 SCR 485',
    year: 2008,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Canada',
    jurisdiction: 'CA',
    legal_principle:
      'The Supreme Court of Canada revisited and modified the s.15 equality analysis from Law v. Canada, moving away from the centrality of human dignity and restoring a more workable two-stage framework for equality claims while affirming the distinct role of s.15(2) in shielding affirmative action programmes from equality challenges. The court held that s.15(2) operates as a substantive provision permitting laws or programmes that have as their object the amelioration of disadvantaged groups, and that such measures are not discriminatory within the meaning of s.15 even if they confer benefits exclusively on a group defined by an enumerated or analogous ground. The Kapp reformulation has been cited comparatively in Irish academic commentary on affirmative action, positive equality measures, and the permissibility of preferential treatment under Article 40.1.',
    key_quote:
      'Section 15(2) is not merely an interpretive aid to s.15(1) but a substantive provision that protects ameliorative programmes targeting disadvantaged groups from Charter challenge; a programme with a genuine ameliorative purpose aimed at a disadvantaged group does not violate the equality guarantee even if it draws distinctions on enumerated or analogous grounds.',
    full_summary:
      "A group of commercial fishermen challenged a federal government programme that granted a communal fishing licence exclusively to three First Nations bands for a limited salmon fishery as an affirmative measure. The fishermen argued this constituted discrimination on the basis of race, contrary to s.15 of the Charter. The Supreme Court dismissed the challenge and used the case to significantly recalibrate the approach to equality analysis under s.15. The court acknowledged that Law v. Canada's human dignity framework had proved difficult to apply in practice and restored a more workable two-step analysis: first, does the law draw a distinction based on an enumerated or analogous ground? Second, does the distinction create a disadvantage by perpetuating prejudice or stereotyping? The court also provided a definitive interpretation of s.15(2), holding that it is a substantive provision that protects genuinely ameliorative programmes aimed at disadvantaged groups from s.15(1) challenge, provided the programme (1) has an ameliorative purpose, (2) targets a disadvantaged group, and (3) the distinction is made on an enumerated or analogous ground. On the facts, the salmon fishing programme was a valid exercise of ameliorative action under s.15(2). R. v. Kapp is cited comparatively in Irish discussions of affirmative action, positive measures, and the extent to which Article 40.1 of the Constitution permits differential treatment in favour of disadvantaged groups.",
