    case_name: 'Schachter v. Canada',
    citation: '[1992] 2 SCR 679',
    year: 1992,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Canada',
    jurisdiction: 'CA',
    legal_principle:
      "The Supreme Court of Canada provided the definitive framework for choosing between the available constitutional remedies when a law is found to violate the Charter, distinguishing between reading-in (adding words to extend coverage of a law to cure unconstitutional under-inclusiveness), reading-down (narrowing the scope of a provision to remove its unconstitutional application), and striking down (declaring the law void). The court identified the factors relevant to each remedial choice and held that courts should generally prefer the remedy least intrusive of Parliament's legislative intent while fully vindicating the constitutional right. Schachter has been directly cited in Irish constitutional proceedings, including Heneghan v. Minister for Housing and Planning, as comparative authority for the proposition that reading-in is an available remedy for unconstitutional under-inclusion of a class of persons.",
    key_quote:
      'The choice of remedy for a Charter violation must be guided by the twin considerations of the seriousness of the Charter violation and the extent to which the chosen remedy respects the role of the legislature; reading-in is appropriate where the violation is one of under-inclusiveness and where the extension of benefits is consistent with the legislative objective.',
    full_summary:
      'Shalom Schachter was denied natural parental benefits under the Unemployment Insurance Act because those benefits were available only to adoptive parents and not biological fathers. He challenged this distinction as discriminatory under s.15 of the Charter. The court agreed that the exclusion of biological fathers was discriminatory and turned to the question of remedy. The Supreme Court used the case to deliver a comprehensive analysis of the remedial options available when legislation is found to violate the Charter. Chief Justice Lamer identified three main remedial options: (1) striking down \u2014 declaring the provision void, either immediately or by way of a suspended declaration; (2) reading-down \u2014 construing the provision narrowly to avoid the constitutional infirmity; and (3) reading-in \u2014 adding words to an under-inclusive provision to extend its benefits to the excluded class and thereby cure the constitutional defect. The court identified factors governing the choice: whether the legislature would have passed the extended measure had it known of the invalidity, the relative cost of each remedy, the nature of the violation (over-inclusion versus under-inclusion), and the degree of deference owed to legislative choices about benefit entitlement. Reading-in was held appropriate where a law is under-inclusive because it omits a group that should be included. Schachter has been cited in Irish constitutional proceedings, most notably in Heneghan v. Minister for Housing and Planning [2023], where the Irish Supreme Court considered the appropriate remedy for unconstitutional exclusion of a class of voters, and in comparative commentary on remedial flexibility in Irish constitutional adjudication.',
