    full_summary:
      "George Swain was charged with assault causing bodily harm. At the conclusion of his defence, the Crown sought to raise the issue of insanity without Swain's consent, relying on the common law rule permitting this. Swain objected. The Supreme Court held that the common law rule allowing the Crown to raise the insanity defence without the accused's consent violated s.7 of the Charter because it could result in the accused being confined as a 'Lieutenant Governor's pleasure' detainee even when he had not sought to raise insanity as a defence, depriving him of liberty without conforming to the principles of fundamental justice. The existing statutory framework for what happened after a verdict of not guilty by reason of insanity was also found unconstitutional under s.9 of the Charter for permitting indefinite detention without review. The court held that the proper remedy was to read into the Criminal Code a requirement for prompt review by a review board rather than immediately striking down the entire scheme and leaving a legal vacuum. The court applied a suspended declaration of invalidity to give Parliament time to enact a comprehensive regime. R. v. Swain is a leading authority on the combination of reading-in and suspended declarations of invalidity and has been studied comparatively in the Irish context alongside Schachter and Heneghan in mapping the landscape of available constitutional remedies for unconstitutional statutory under-inclusiveness.",
