    court: 'Supreme Court of the United States',
    jurisdiction: 'US',
    legal_principle:
      'The Supreme Court of the United States held that race-based affirmative action admissions programmes at Harvard University and the University of North Carolina violated the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment to the US Constitution, overruling the line of authority from Grutter v. Bollinger (2003) and Gratz v. Bollinger (2003) that had permitted the use of race as a factor in university admissions to achieve diversity. The court held that the Equal Protection Clause is colour-blind and that racial classifications \u2014 even those intended to benefit minority groups \u2014 must satisfy strict scrutiny and are unconstitutional absent a compelling interest and narrow tailoring that individual race-based admissions schemes cannot satisfy. The decision is a significant comparative reference point in Irish equality jurisprudence on affirmative action and the permissibility of race-conscious policies under equality guarantees.',
