    full_summary:
      "Students for Fair Admissions, an advocacy group, brought separate lawsuits against Harvard University and the University of North Carolina, arguing that their race-conscious admissions programmes discriminated against Asian-American and White applicants in violation of the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment. The Supreme Court of the United States, in a 6-3 decision authored by Chief Justice Roberts, held that both programmes violated the Equal Protection Clause. The court overruled Grutter v. Bollinger [2003], which had held that the educational benefits of diversity constituted a compelling interest sufficient to permit the limited use of race in law school admissions, and had been relied upon by universities across the United States for twenty years. The court held that the diversity rationale was insufficiently coherent and measurable to satisfy the requirements of strict scrutiny, and that race-based programmes inevitably involved the stereotyping of individuals by reference to their racial group. The court held that the Constitution's guarantee of equality demands individual rather than group-based assessment. The decision generated significant controversy globally and has been cited in comparative constitutional law discussions in Ireland on the limits of affirmative action under equality guarantees, particularly in academic debates about whether Article 40.1 of the Irish Constitution would permit race-conscious admissions policies and whether positive measures in favour of disadvantaged groups are constitutionally permissible.",
