    legal_principle:
      "The UK Supreme Court held that the two-child limit on the child element of Child Tax Credit and Universal Credit engaged Article 14 of the ECHR read with Article 8 (right to family life) and Article 1 Protocol 1 (right to property), and that the benefit cap policy required justification as potentially discriminating against children and women. The court gave important guidance on the approach to Article 14 ECHR in social welfare cases, including the concept of the 'ambit' of a Convention right, the standard of justification required for indirect discrimination in welfare law, and the margin of appreciation available to the state in social and economic policy. The judgment is a significant comparative authority for Irish equality claims in welfare law contexts involving child-related benefits.",
