    full_summary:
      'The claimants challenged the two-child limit on Child Tax Credit and Universal Credit \u2014 which restricted the child element of those benefits to the first two children in a family \u2014 arguing that it violated Article 14 ECHR read with Article 8 (right to family life) and Article 1 of Protocol 1 (peaceful enjoyment of possessions) by indirectly discriminating against women (who are disproportionately the principal carers of large families), against children (who constitute an especially vulnerable group), and on grounds of religion (since some religious groups encourage larger families). The UK Supreme Court, in a complex multi-opinion judgment, held that the measure engaged Article 14 and required justification. The majority held that the Government had established sufficient justification for the limit as a matter of social and economic policy, emphasising the wide margin of appreciation available to states in welfare design. However, the court gave important guidance on the approach to Article 14 in welfare cases, confirming that children constitute a particularly vulnerable group whose interests demand special scrutiny, and that indirect discrimination on grounds of sex and religion in welfare systems requires genuine objective justification. The case is studied comparatively in Ireland in the context of equality challenges to welfare reforms under the Constitution and the European Convention on Human Rights Act 2003, particularly in discussions of child-related benefit entitlements and gender equality in social security.',
