      'The question under Article 14 is not whether a different solution might have been adopted but whether the legislature, in choosing the solution it did, exceeded the wide margin of appreciation afforded to states in the design of social security systems; differential treatment based on primary caring responsibility pursues a legitimate aim and bears a reasonable relationship of proportionality.',
    full_summary:
      "Mr. Humphreys, a lone father with shared care of his child, challenged the rules of the Working Tax Credit and Child Tax Credit schemes which effectively allocated the child element of the credit to the mother (or the primary carer, who was almost invariably the mother) rather than splitting it between parents sharing care. He argued that this constituted sex discrimination contrary to Article 14 ECHR read with Article 1 of Protocol 1 (peaceful enjoyment of possessions). The UK Supreme Court rejected the challenge. Baroness Hale, writing the lead judgment, confirmed that the allocation of child tax credit to the primary carer was rationally connected to the scheme's purpose of supporting the day-to-day costs of bringing up children and that targeting the benefit at the primary carer \u2014 who is statistically more likely to bear those costs \u2014 was a rational and proportionate approach. The court applied the 'manifestly without reasonable foundation' standard appropriate for social and economic policy decisions by the legislature. The case provides detailed guidance on the application of Article 14 in social welfare contexts, the relevance of statistical evidence of disadvantage in indirect discrimination claims, and the margin of appreciation in welfare design. Humphreys v. Revenue and Customs Commissioners has been cited in Irish comparative equality proceedings, including academic and practitioner commentary on the constitutional position of unmarried fathers and the design of child benefit and lone-parent payment rules under Irish social welfare legislation.",
