    case_name: 'Neulinger and Shuruk v. Switzerland',
    citation: '(2010) 54 EHRR 1087',
    year: 2010,
    court: 'European Court of Human Rights (Grand Chamber)',
    jurisdiction: 'ECHR',
    legal_principle:
      "The Grand Chamber of the European Court of Human Rights held that Switzerland's obligation under the Hague Convention on International Child Abduction to return a child to the jurisdiction from which he had been wrongfully removed had to be assessed in light of Article 8 ECHR and the best interests of the child as a primary consideration, and that where return would expose the child to an intolerable situation, Article 8 required refusal of the return order. The court confirmed that the best interests of the child are a paramount consideration in all decisions affecting children under Article 8, including international abduction proceedings, and that a formalistic application of the Hague Convention return mechanism is incompatible with the Convention where it ignores the actual circumstances and welfare of the child. Neulinger has been cited in Irish family law constitutional cases dealing with the paramountcy of children's welfare under Article 42A and the application of the Hague Convention.",
    key_quote:
      "In all decisions concerning children, the child's best interests must be a primary consideration; the obligation to return a child under the Hague Convention must be applied in a manner compatible with Article 8 of the Convention, and return must be refused where it would place the child in an intolerable situation, taking full account of the child's individual circumstances.",
    full_summary:
      "Ms. Neulinger, an Israeli national living in Switzerland, removed her son Noam from Israel to Switzerland without the consent of the child's father, who was an Israeli national. She argued that she had fled to protect herself and her child from the father, who was a member of a religious group from which she feared it would be difficult to extricate the child if he were returned to Israel. The father applied under the Hague Convention for the child's return to Israel. The Swiss Federal Court ordered the return. Ms. Neulinger applied to the European Court of Human Rights, arguing that return would violate her and her son's rights under Article 8. The Grand Chamber held, by 16 votes to 1, that to enforce the return order would violate Article 8. The Grand Chamber conducted an extensive review of the relevant facts and concluded that returning the child to Israel would expose him to a real risk of being raised in a closed religious community against his will and would deprive him of his relationship with his mother, with whom he had lived since infancy. The court held that in all decisions affecting children, the best interests of the child are a primary consideration under Article 8, and that the automatic application of the Hague Convention without careful attention to the child's welfare is inconsistent with the Convention. While Neulinger was subsequently the subject of considerable debate as to its compatibility with the Hague Convention system, it has been cited in Irish family law constitutional proceedings dealing with the welfare of children in the context of Article 42A of the Constitution and the Guardianship of Infants Act, and remains a significant ECHR authority on children's rights in the family law context.",
    subjects: ['constitutional'],
    topics: [
      'Article 8 ECHR',
      'right to family life',
      'child abduction',
      'Hague Convention',
      'best interests of child',
      'Article 42A',
      "children's rights",
      'comparative constitutional law',
    ],
    is_frequently_tested: false,
    past_paper_appearances: [],
