    court: 'Court of Justice of the European Union (Grand Chamber)',
    jurisdiction: 'EU',
    legal_principle:
      "The Grand Chamber held that the Racial Equality Directive (2000/43/EC) may apply to a situation where an electricity distribution company places meters at inaccessible heights in a neighbourhood inhabited predominantly by persons of Roma origin, without any objective justification, where that practice places persons of a particular ethnic origin at a particular disadvantage compared with other persons. The Court held that the concept of 'ethnic origin' in the Directive covers Roma populations, that indirect discrimination may be established by reference to a group of persons sharing a characteristic even where the claimant does not personally belong to that group, and that the Directive can be invoked against a private company performing a public service.",
    key_quote:
      "The concept of 'indirect discrimination' in Article 2(2)(b) of Directive 2000/43 covers a situation where a measure, although formulated in neutral terms, puts persons of a particular ethnic origin at a particular disadvantage, unless that measure is objectively justified by a legitimate aim and the means of achieving that aim are appropriate and necessary.",
    full_summary:
      "CHEZ Razpredelenie arose from a Bulgarian case in which an electricity distribution company installed electricity meters at a height of six metres in a predominantly Roma neighbourhood, while in other areas meters were installed at 1.7 metres. The official justification was to prevent illegal connections to the electricity network, which the company alleged were particularly prevalent in the neighbourhood concerned. Ms Nikolova, who ran a grocery store in the neighbourhood and was not herself of Roma origin, complained that the practice subjected her to discrimination on grounds of ethnic origin. The CJEU held that the Racial Equality Directive's broad scope encompassed this situation. First, persons of Roma origin fall within the concept of 'ethnic origin.' Second, the concept of indirect discrimination does not require the claimant to be personally a member of the protected group \u2014 it is sufficient that the claimant suffers a particular disadvantage as a consequence of a practice directed at a group defined by ethnic origin. Third, the practical impossibility of reading one's meter and the stigma attached to living in a neighbourhood targeted by such practices constituted a particular disadvantage. The case significantly expanded the scope of EU race discrimination law and is relevant for FE-1 constitutional law candidates studying how EU equality directives interact with constitutional equality guarantees in Ireland under Article 40.1.",
