    full_summary:
      "A.B. and Others arose from the controversy in Poland surrounding the reform of the judicial appointments process to the Polish Supreme Court under legislation enacted by the Polish government between 2017 and 2018. The Polish National Council of the Judiciary (KRS), which had been restructured to give the ruling political party dominant influence over judicial appointments, recommended candidates for Supreme Court appointments. Candidates who were passed over challenged the KRS's resolutions before the Administrative Chamber of the Supreme Court, which subsequently referred questions to the CJEU. The CJEU held that Article 19(1) TEU, read in light of Article 2 TEU (the rule of law as a foundational EU value), requires Member States to maintain courts and tribunals that satisfy objective requirements of independence and impartiality, and that national legislation precluding judicial review of judicial appointment decisions where there are systemic rule-of-law concerns is incompatible with EU constitutional requirements. The case is central to the EU's constitutionally enforceable doctrine of judicial independence and illustrates how EU constitutional law can constrain domestic constitutional arrangements for the organisation of the judiciary. For FE-1 constitutional law candidates, A.B. and Others is relevant to understanding how EU constitutional norms \u2014 particularly the rule of law \u2014 function as constraints on national constitutional arrangements and how they compare to Irish constitutional provisions for judicial independence under Articles 34 and 35 of Bunreacht na h\u00c9ireann.",
