    citation: '[1999] IESC 47, [1999] 4 IR 26',
    year: 1999,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Ireland',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      "The Supreme Court held that a statutory provision purporting to confer on the Minister for Justice a power to designate countries as 'safe countries of origin' for the purposes of determining asylum applications \u2014 and thereby to accelerate or curtail asylum procedures in respect of nationals of those countries \u2014 constituted an impermissible sub-delegation of primary legislative power contrary to Article 15.2.1\u00b0 of Bunreacht na h\u00c9ireann, which vests the sole and exclusive power of making laws for the State in the Oireachtas. The principle against sub-delegation of legislative power prevents the Oireachtas from conferring on ministers or other bodies an unconstrained or inadequately constrained power to make rules that have the force of law in contexts touching on constitutional rights. This case is the leading Irish authority on the constitutional limits of delegated legislation in the immigration and asylum context.",
    key_quote:
      'The Oireachtas cannot confer on any person or body the power to make laws; it may delegate limited powers of a legislative nature but only if adequate principles and policies are laid down in the primary legislation to guide and constrain the exercise of the delegated power.',
    full_summary:
      "Laurentiu v. Minister for Justice arose from proceedings by a Romanian national whose asylum application was processed under an accelerated procedure pursuant to a ministerial order designating Romania as a safe country of origin under the Refugee Act 1996. The applicant challenged the validity of the ministerial designation on the ground that it constituted an unconstitutional sub-delegation of the Oireachtas's exclusive legislative power under Article 15.2.1\u00b0 of Bunreacht na h\u00c9ireann. The Supreme Court upheld the challenge. The Court applied the principle established in Cityview Press v. An Chomhairle Oili\u00fana [1980] IR 381 that the Oireachtas may delegate subsidiary and detailed matters of administration to ministers but that the primary Act must itself lay down adequate principles and policies governing the exercise of the delegated function. Where the primary Act gives a minister an essentially unconstrained power to determine a matter of fundamental significance \u2014 such as which persons are entitled to have their asylum claims fairly considered \u2014 that power is an unconstitutional sub-delegation of legislative authority. The Court's ruling had immediate practical consequences for Irish asylum procedures and required legislative reform. For FE-1 constitutional law candidates, Laurentiu is essential for understanding the constitutional limits on delegated legislation, the Cityview Press principle, and how Article 15.2.1\u00b0 operates as a constitutional check on executive power in the immigration context.",
