    full_summary:
      "East Donegal Co-operative arose from a challenge to provisions of the Livestock Marts Act 1967, which granted the Minister for Agriculture wide discretionary powers to attach conditions to licences for livestock marts, to refuse licences, and to revoke licences. The plaintiffs argued that the breadth of these ministerial powers rendered the Act unconstitutional as an impermissible delegation of legislative power and as an unjustified interference with property rights under Article 43 and the right to earn a livelihood under Article 40. The Supreme Court (Walsh J delivering the leading judgment) dismissed the challenge, but in doing so articulated principles of constitutional construction of far-reaching significance. The Court held that the presumption of constitutionality is not merely a procedural presumption but a substantive one: courts must read statutory provisions in a manner consistent with the Constitution even if that requires reading in limitations or qualifications not express on the face of the statute. Walsh J laid down that the Constitution must be read as a whole, that it reflects a fundamental ordering of rights and values, and that statutes must be construed to accord with that ordering. The Court also confirmed that the Minister's discretionary powers were subject to implied constitutional constraints \u2014 in particular, requirements of fair procedures and equality. For FE-1 constitutional law candidates, East Donegal is among the most frequently examined cases and is essential for every question touching on constitutional interpretation, delegated legislation, or the constitutional validity of statutes.",
