      'The Supreme Court upheld the constitutional validity of provisions of the Road Traffic Act 1961 challenged as an unconstitutional delegation of legislative power, applying the Cityview Press principle that the Oireachtas may delegate subsidiary and administrative matters to the executive provided that adequate principles and policies are contained in the primary Act to guide the exercise of the delegated function. The case further confirmed that the presumption of constitutionality applies to delegated legislation made pursuant to a constitutionally valid enabling Act, and that the courts must adopt a constitutional construction of both the primary Act and any delegated instrument made under it.',
