      'Attorney General v. Paperlink arose from proceedings by the Attorney General to restrain Paperlink Ltd from operating a private courier service for letters and documents in competition with An Post, which held a statutory monopoly over the carriage of letters under the Post Office Act 1908. Paperlink defended on the ground that the statutory monopoly was unconstitutional as an infringement of the right to communicate. Costello J in the High Court held that there exists, derived from the nature of human communication and the constitutional protection of personal rights in Article 40.3, an unenumerated constitutional right to communicate \u2014 the right of citizens to convey and receive information and ideas. The judge held that this right is not exhausted by the express guarantee of freedom of expression in Article 40.6.1\u00b0 but is a distinct personal right protected by the broader guarantee in Article 40.3.1\u00b0. However, the Court held that the State could constitutionally restrict this right for legitimate public interest reasons \u2014 in this case, the need to maintain a universal postal service \u2014 and that the An Post monopoly, though a restriction, was a proportionate and constitutionally justifiable one. For FE-1 constitutional law candidates, Paperlink is central to understanding unenumerated personal rights under Article 40.3, the right to communicate, and how the courts balance constitutional rights against legitimate State regulatory interests.',
