      "The Supreme Court held that the constitutional guarantee of fair procedures \u2014 encompassing the principles of natural justice, including the right to be heard (audi alteram partem) and the rule against bias (nemo iudex in causa sua) \u2014 applies not only to courts and public administrative bodies but also to private professional disciplinary proceedings where a person's constitutional rights to their good name, livelihood, or professional standing are at stake. The case established that the constitutional right to fair procedures under Article 40.3 imposes obligations on private decision-making bodies when they exercise disciplinary powers affecting the fundamental rights of individuals.",
    key_quote:
      'The requirements of natural justice and fair procedures are not confined to courts and public bodies; they apply to any body, whether public or private, that exercises a disciplinary or adjudicative function which may deprive a person of a constitutional right to their good name or their livelihood.',
    full_summary:
      "Hynes-O'Sullivan v. O'Driscoll arose from proceedings in which a medical practitioner challenged disciplinary decisions made by a private professional body \u2014 the Irish Medical Council \u2014 on the ground that the procedures adopted in the disciplinary hearing failed to comply with the requirements of natural justice and, in particular, the right to a fair hearing. The Supreme Court held that the constitutional protection for fair procedures is not confined to public law proceedings but extends to private bodies exercising disciplinary powers over individuals whose constitutional rights \u2014 including the right to a good name under Article 40.3.2\u00b0 and the right to earn a livelihood \u2014 may be affected by the outcome of those proceedings. The Court held that any adjudicative or disciplinary body that can determine outcomes affecting constitutional rights is obliged to comply with the principles of audi alteram partem (the right to be heard) and nemo iudex in causa sua (the rule against bias). The Court examined the procedures actually applied by the Medical Council and found them wanting in particular respects, confirming the applicant's entitlement to have the decision set aside. Hynes-O'Sullivan is a landmark in the constitutionalisation of natural justice in Ireland and extends the reach of Article 40.3 fair procedures protections into private professional contexts. For FE-1 constitutional law candidates, the case is essential for understanding the constitutional dimension of natural justice and its application beyond the traditional public law sphere.",
