    citation: '368 US 871 (1961)',
    year: 1961,
    court: 'Supreme Court of the United States',
    jurisdiction: 'US',
    legal_principle:
      'The Supreme Court held that the Fourth Amendment exclusionary rule applies to the states through the Due Process Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment, overruling Wolf v. Colorado (1949) to the extent that Wolf permitted state courts to admit evidence obtained through unconstitutional searches. The decision unified federal and state evidentiary standards and established that the constitutional right to be free from unreasonable searches would be meaningless without an effective judicial remedy applicable in all courts.',
