    full_summary:
      "Ohio police officers entered the home of Dollree Mapp without a valid warrant, ostensibly searching for a bombing suspect. They found no suspect but discovered obscene materials and prosecuted Mapp for possession. The Ohio Supreme Court upheld the conviction on the basis that, under Wolf v. Colorado, states were not bound to apply the federal exclusionary rule. The US Supreme Court reversed. Justice Clark, writing for the majority, concluded that the Weeks rule must apply in full vigour to the states, since the security of persons against government intrusion through unreasonable searches and seizures is guaranteed by the Constitution and must be protected by consistent judicial enforcement regardless of the forum. The Court reasoned that allowing states to admit evidence that federal courts would reject creates an anomalous and unjust two-tier system of constitutional protection. Mapp is a landmark of US constitutional law because it completed the nationalisation of the Fourth Amendment's exclusionary remedy. In the Irish context, the case is relevant as a comparative authority on the relationship between constitutional guarantees and their enforcement mechanisms. The Irish Supreme Court in People (DPP) v. O'Brien [1965] and People (DPP) v. Kenny [1990] each had occasion to consider whether an absolute exclusionary remedy was appropriate in Ireland; the Mapp decision and the American experience of applying a near-absolute rule informed that debate, and subsequent cases including People (DPP) v. JC [2017] explicitly engaged with the US model.",
