    case_name: 'United States v. Leon',
    citation: '468 US 897 (1984)',
    year: 1984,
    court: 'Supreme Court of the United States',
    jurisdiction: 'US',
    legal_principle:
      "The Supreme Court created a 'good faith exception' to the Fourth Amendment exclusionary rule, holding that evidence seized by police officers acting in reasonable reliance on a search warrant issued by a detached and neutral magistrate is admissible even if the warrant is subsequently found to be unsupported by probable cause. The exclusionary rule is a judicially created remedy designed to deter police misconduct, not a personal constitutional right; where officers act in objective good faith, suppression serves no deterrent purpose and its costs to the justice system outweigh its benefits.",
    key_quote:
      "When the officer's conduct is objectively reasonable, excluding the evidence will not further the ends of the exclusionary rule in any appreciable way; for it is painfully apparent that almost all of the cases in which the exclusionary rule is applied involve situations in which the officer conducting the search believed that the relevant legal requirements had been satisfied.",
    full_summary:
      "Federal agents obtained a search warrant from a magistrate judge on the basis of an informant's tip and surveillance. The warrant was subsequently challenged and found by the district court to lack probable cause. The Supreme Court held that the evidence should nevertheless be admitted because the officers had acted in objective good faith reliance on the facially valid warrant. Justice White, writing for the majority, conducted an explicit cost-benefit analysis of the exclusionary rule, concluding that the rule's primary purpose is deterrence of unlawful police conduct. Where officers act in good faith on a warrant issued by a neutral magistrate, exclusion cannot deter future misconduct and its social costs \u2014 chiefly the suppression of probative evidence and the acquittal of guilty defendants \u2014 are not justified. The Court identified four situations where the good faith exception would not apply: where the magistrate was misled by deliberate or reckless falsehoods in the affidavit; where the magistrate wholly abandoned the judicial role; where the warrant was so facially deficient as to preclude reasonable reliance; and where the affidavit was so lacking in probable cause that belief in its sufficiency was entirely unreasonable. Leon is the leading US authority counterposing the Irish absolute rule established in People (DPP) v. Kenny [1990]. The Irish Supreme Court in People (DPP) v. JC [2017] rejected the absolute rule of Kenny and moved towards a discretionary balancing model, explicitly considering the arguments underlying Leon and the Canadian approach in R v. Grant.",
