      "Police conducted a search of a passenger's bag incident to arrest in conformity with the then-binding precedent of New York v. Belton (1981), which permitted a full search of a car's passenger compartment incident to a lawful arrest. While Davis's case was on appeal, the Supreme Court decided Arizona v. Gant (2009), which substantially narrowed Belton and would have rendered the search of Davis's bag unlawful. The Court held that the good faith exception applied and the evidence was admissible. Justice Alito, writing for the majority, emphasised that the exclusionary rule is a deterrence-based remedy and is not a personal constitutional guarantee. Where officers act in strict compliance with then-binding circuit precedent, exclusion cannot meaningfully deter future unconstitutional conduct since the officers did nothing wrong under the law as it then stood. The case illustrates the deterrence rationale's limits as a foundation for an absolute exclusionary rule. In the Irish context, Davis is relevant to the debate that preceded People (DPP) v. JC [2017], where the Supreme Court ultimately replaced the absolute Kenny rule with a discretionary approach sensitive to the conduct of the officer and the circumstances of the breach. The analysis in JC drew on US scholarship concerning the costs and benefits of automatic exclusion and the relevance of officer culpability.",
