    full_summary:
      'Two state prisoners sought federal habeas corpus relief, arguing that evidence used to convict them had been obtained in violation of the Fourth Amendment. The Supreme Court held that the exclusionary rule does not apply on federal habeas review where the state courts provided a full and fair opportunity to litigate the Fourth Amendment claim. Justice Powell, writing for the majority, conducted a cost-benefit analysis of the rule and concluded that its purpose \u2014 deterrence of unlawful police conduct \u2014 is substantially served by its application at trial and on direct appeal. The social costs of excluding reliable probative evidence, the disruption to finality of convictions, and the minimal additional deterrence gained from extending the rule to collateral proceedings all weighed against its application in habeas cases. Stone v. Powell is significant as a demonstration that even within the US system, which created the exclusionary rule, courts have consistently sought to rationalise its scope by reference to its deterrence rationale rather than treating it as an absolute constitutional imperative. This analysis was influential in the comparative jurisprudential debate in Ireland leading to People (DPP) v. JC [2017], where the Supreme Court moved away from the absolute exclusionary rule of People (DPP) v. Kenny [1990] toward a balancing framework that weighs the interests of justice against the gravity of the constitutional breach.',
