    case_name: 'Illinois v. Gates',
    citation: '462 US 213 (1983)',
    year: 1983,
    court: 'Supreme Court of the United States',
    jurisdiction: 'US',
    legal_principle:
      "The Supreme Court replaced the rigid two-pronged Aguilar-Spinelli test for evaluating informant-based probable cause with a flexible 'totality of the circumstances' standard. A magistrate must make a practical, common-sense determination of whether, given all the circumstances including the informant's veracity, reliability, and basis of knowledge, there is a fair probability that contraband or evidence of a crime will be found in a particular place. This holistic approach to probable cause is the current governing standard for issuance of search warrants in the United States.",
    key_quote:
      "The task of the issuing magistrate is simply to make a practical, commonsense decision whether, given all the circumstances set forth in the affidavit before him, including the 'veracity' and 'basis of knowledge' of persons supplying hearsay information, there is a fair probability that contraband or evidence of a crime will be found in a particular place.",
    full_summary:
      "Police received an anonymous letter alleging that the Gates couple were engaged in drug trafficking and detailing a pattern of travel to Florida to collect drugs. Officers corroborated the tip through surveillance and obtained a search warrant on the basis of the anonymous letter and the corroboration. The Illinois Supreme Court suppressed the evidence on the ground that the tip failed the two-pronged Aguilar-Spinelli test, which required separate showings of the informant's veracity and basis of knowledge. The US Supreme Court reversed, holding that probable cause must be assessed under a totality of the circumstances standard that is practical and non-technical. Justice Rehnquist, writing for the majority, noted that the Aguilar-Spinelli test had become unduly rigid and that its mechanical application frustrated the Fourth Amendment's central purpose of protecting citizens while permitting the government to detect and prosecute crime. The totality standard allows corroboration of specific details to compensate for deficiencies in one prong. In the Irish context, the standards for obtaining and executing search warrants under legislation such as the Criminal Justice Act 2006 and the Offences Against the State Act 1939 have been extensively litigated, and the US approach to probable cause offers useful comparative framing for understanding the constitutional underpinnings of warrant requirements and the standard of judicial scrutiny applied.",
