    case_name: 'Brown v. Illinois',
    citation: '422 US 590 (1975)',
    year: 1975,
    court: 'Supreme Court of the United States',
    jurisdiction: 'US',
    legal_principle:
      'The Supreme Court held that the administration of Miranda warnings after an unlawful arrest does not, by itself, attenuate the taint of the prior Fourth Amendment violation so as to make a subsequent confession admissible under the fruit of the poisonous tree doctrine. Whether derivative evidence is sufficiently attenuated from the underlying constitutional violation must be determined by reference to all the circumstances, including the temporal proximity of the violation and the evidence, the presence of intervening circumstances, and the purpose and flagrancy of the police misconduct.',
    key_quote:
      "The Miranda warnings are an important part of an effective constitutional rule, but they are not a substitute for the protection of other constitutional rights. The exclusionary rule's purposes of deterrence of police misconduct and of judicial integrity are served by suppression of a confession that is the direct result of an unlawful arrest.",
    full_summary:
      "Police arrested Brown without probable cause, administered Miranda warnings, and obtained confessions that were used to convict him of murder. The Supreme Court held that the confessions should have been suppressed as fruit of the unlawful arrest. Justice Blackmun, writing for the Court, rejected the argument that Miranda warnings automatically break the causal chain between an unlawful arrest and a subsequent confession. The Court identified three factors relevant to the attenuation inquiry that remain the governing framework: the temporal proximity between the illegality and the acquisition of the evidence; the presence of intervening circumstances; and the purpose and flagrancy of the police misconduct. Brown is foundational for the attenuation doctrine as a limit on the fruit of the poisonous tree principle and demonstrates that confessions as well as physical evidence may be suppressed as derivative of a constitutional violation. In the Irish context, the question of whether an arrest that is found to be unlawful taints a subsequent detention and any admissions made during that detention has been a recurring issue. Brown's attenuation framework has informed academic and judicial analysis of the circumstances in which Irish courts will or should exclude confessional evidence flowing from procedurally defective arrests, and the balancing exercise in People (DPP) v. JC [2017] draws on analogous considerations.",
