    case_name: 'R v. Collins',
    citation: '[1987] 1 SCR 265',
    year: 1987,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Canada',
    jurisdiction: 'CA',
    legal_principle:
      'The Supreme Court of Canada established the original framework for excluding evidence under section 24(2) of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms, requiring courts to consider whether admission of evidence obtained in breach of a Charter right would bring the administration of justice into disrepute. The analysis focused on three broad factors: the effect of admission on trial fairness; the seriousness of the Charter violation; and the effect of exclusion on the repute of the administration of justice. This framework preceded and was ultimately replaced by R v. Grant [2009].',
    key_quote:
      'Evidence should be excluded if it is established that, having regard to all the circumstances, the admission of the evidence would bring the administration of justice into disrepute.',
    full_summary:
      "Police conducted a throat-hold search of Ruby Collins, suspected of drug dealing, in circumstances where the officer lacked the required reasonable grounds. The search revealed heroin. The Supreme Court of Canada addressed the test for excluding evidence under s.24(2) of the Canadian Charter for the first time in a thorough and systematic way. Lamer J, writing for the majority, articulated a three-part framework that structured the judicial discretion to exclude evidence. The first group of factors concerned whether admission of the evidence would render the trial unfair, with particular emphasis on whether the evidence was conscriptive (obtained through the accused's own participation, such as a breath sample or confession) or non-conscriptive (independently existing, such as a weapon found in a search). The second group concerned the seriousness of the violation, including whether it was deliberate or in good faith, and whether urgency or necessity existed. The third group concerned the effect of exclusion on the long-term repute of the administration of justice. Collins was the leading Canadian authority for over two decades and was the precursor to the more refined and unified three-part test established in R v. Grant [2009]. In the Irish context, the Canadian approach to excluding evidence under a structured discretionary framework \u2014 balancing the seriousness of the breach against the interests of the administration of justice \u2014 has been closely examined by the Irish Supreme Court, particularly in People (DPP) v. JC [2017], where Clarke J drew on both Collins and Grant in reformulating the Irish exclusionary rule.",
