    case_name: 'R v. Grant',
    citation: '[2009] 2 SCR 353',
    year: 2009,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Canada',
    jurisdiction: 'CA',
    legal_principle:
      "The Supreme Court of Canada replaced the Collins framework with a unified three-part test for determining whether evidence obtained in breach of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms should be excluded under section 24(2). Courts must assess: (1) the seriousness of the Charter-infringing conduct and whether admission would bring the administration of justice into disrepute; (2) the impact of the breach on the Charter-protected interests of the accused; and (3) society's interest in an adjudication on the merits. No single factor is determinative and the inquiry is holistic.",
    key_quote:
      "The three lines of inquiry identified above \u2014 the seriousness of the Charter-infringing state conduct, the impact of the breach on the Charter-protected interests of the accused, and society's interest in the adjudication of the case on its merits \u2014 provide a structure for the s.24(2) inquiry.",
    full_summary:
      "Grant was detained and questioned by police officers who, in circumstances that the courts found to breach ss.9 and 10(b) of the Charter (arbitrary detention and right to counsel), obtained an incriminating statement and observed him in possession of a firearm. The Supreme Court of Canada, in a joint judgment by McLachlin CJC and Charron J, comprehensively restated the law on s.24(2) exclusion of evidence. The Court expressly abandoned the conscriptive/non-conscriptive distinction from Collins as having proved unworkable and insufficiently principled. The new framework requires a court to balance all relevant considerations under three headings: the seriousness of the state conduct, which may range from inadvertent technical breaches to deliberate and flagrant violations; the impact on the accused's Charter rights, assessed by examining the extent to which the breach violated the protected interest and the seriousness of the intrusion; and society's interest in a determination of the case on the merits, which includes the reliability of the evidence and the gravity of the alleged offence. Grant is the leading authority on the Canadian approach to exclusion of evidence and is one of the most important comparative constitutional law cases for Irish constitutional law purposes. The Irish Supreme Court in People (DPP) v. JC [2017] explicitly cited Grant and the three-part balancing framework as informing the new Irish approach to excluding evidence obtained in breach of constitutional rights, departing from the near-absolute rule of People (DPP) v. Kenny [1990].",
