    citation: '[2009] SCC 34, [2009] 2 SCR 494',
    year: 2009,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Canada',
    jurisdiction: 'CA',
    legal_principle:
      'Applying the newly articulated Grant test for the first time, the Supreme Court of Canada held that evidence of drug trafficking must be excluded under section 24(2) of the Canadian Charter where the police conduct constituting the Charter breach was serious and deliberate, even though the evidence itself was reliable and the offence charged was grave. The case demonstrates that under Grant, sufficiently serious and deliberate Charter violations will result in exclusion of evidence notwithstanding the societal interest in prosecution of serious crime.',
