    full_summary:
      "An Ontario Provincial Police officer stopped Harrison's vehicle on a highway, ostensibly because it lacked a front licence plate, which the officer later admitted was not required in Alberta where the vehicle was registered. The stop was found to be a pretext and a serious breach of s.9 of the Charter (arbitrary detention). During the stop, police discovered 35 kilograms of cocaine. The Supreme Court of Canada applied the freshly stated Grant test and excluded the evidence. McLachlin CJC, writing for the majority, found that the officer's conduct was deliberate and wilful, that the impact on Harrison's Charter-protected rights was severe, and that while society had a strong interest in the conviction of large-scale drug traffickers, admitting the evidence would bring the administration of justice into disrepute given the brazen nature of the breach. Harrison is important because it demonstrates that the Grant test is not simply a more permissive version of Collins but is capable of requiring exclusion of highly probative and reliable evidence in cases of serious and deliberate police misconduct. In the Irish context, the case is relevant to the spectrum of judicial responses contemplated by the JC framework and illustrates how a balancing approach can still produce exclusion in egregious cases, countering the concern that moving away from an absolute rule necessarily leads to systematic admission of unconstitutionally obtained evidence.",
