      "The Supreme Court of Canada held that the common law power to search incident to arrest extends to the search of a mobile phone seized from an arrested person, but that such a search must be conducted subject to specific constraints to protect the arrested person's reasonable expectation of privacy. The phone may only be searched where the search is truly incidental to the arrest; only the contents reasonably capable of providing evidence related to the offence for which the arrest was made may be searched; the search must be conducted promptly; and the officer must take notes sufficient to permit judicial review.",
