    full_summary:
      'Fearon was arrested following an armed robbery and police searched his mobile phone without a warrant incident to arrest, finding photos of a gun, cash, and a draft text message incriminating him in the robbery. The trial judge admitted the evidence and the conviction was upheld. The Supreme Court of Canada, by a 4-3 majority, upheld the admission of evidence but significantly limited the warrantless search of cell phones incident to arrest. The majority, written by Cromwell J, emphasised the heightened privacy interest that individuals have in their mobile phones given the vast amounts of personal information stored on them. While declining to require a warrant for all cell phone searches incident to arrest, the Court imposed four conditions designed to ensure that the warrantless power remains genuinely incidental to the lawful arrest and proportionate to the privacy interests at stake. The three dissenting justices would have required a warrant in almost all circumstances. In the Irish context, Fearon has been noted in academic commentary and in some judicial analysis concerning searches of digital devices, including the question of whether a person arrested and detained under Irish criminal procedure legislation may have their mobile phone searched without a warrant. Cases such as People (DPP) v. Quirke and People (DPP) v. Behan have engaged with the constitutional dimension of digital searches, and the Fearon analysis provides a structured framework for assessing proportionality in that context.',
