    full_summary:
      "Police officers entered C\u00f4t\u00e9's home without a warrant during a murder investigation, relying on purported consent from a co-occupant and exigency arguments that the courts did not accept. The search produced significant incriminating evidence. The Supreme Court of Canada held that the warrantless entry breached s.8 of the Charter, which guarantees the right to be secure against unreasonable search and seizure. Applying the Grant three-part framework, the Court found that the breach was serious because the home occupies a privileged position in the constitutional order as the primary domain of personal privacy, that the impact on C\u00f4t\u00e9's Charter rights was substantial, and that while the offence was grave, admission of evidence obtained through a warrantless residential search would bring the administration of justice into disrepute. Evidence was excluded and the conviction was set aside. C\u00f4t\u00e9 confirms that within the Canadian balancing framework, the nature of the location searched \u2014 particularly the home \u2014 is a weighty factor favouring exclusion. In Irish constitutional law, the dwelling has an explicit and elevated constitutional protection under Article 40.5 of Bunreacht na h\u00c9ireann, which provides that the dwelling of every citizen is inviolable and shall not be forcibly entered except in accordance with law. Cases such as People (DPP) v. Damache [2012] IESC 11 have explored the scope of that protection; C\u00f4t\u00e9 offers a comparative lens on how privacy in the home interacts with the exclusionary rule.",
