    full_summary:
      "The Attorney General sought to enforce a statutory liability against Ryan's Car Hire on the basis of a previous Supreme Court decision. The Court took the occasion to address directly the question of whether the Supreme Court was bound by its own prior decisions. The Court held, in a judgment of lasting constitutional importance, that it was not so bound. The Irish Supreme Court reasoned that the nature of a final court of appeal exercising constitutional jurisdiction demanded that it retain the freedom to correct its own errors. To hold otherwise would entrench constitutional misinterpretation indefinitely and deprive the Court of the capacity to adapt the Constitution's interpretation to evolving circumstances. This power has been exercised on a number of significant subsequent occasions, most notably when the Supreme Court in People (DPP) v. JC [2017] overruled People (DPP) v. Kenny [1990], and when the Court departed from earlier interpretations of constitutional rights in light of changed social, legal, or factual circumstances. For FE-1 candidates, Ryan's Car Hire is the foundational authority on the doctrine of stare decisis in the Irish Supreme Court and on the flexibility of constitutional interpretation. Understanding this case is essential for appreciating how and why Irish constitutional law continues to evolve.",
