      'Chief Justice Marshall held that the federal government of the United States possesses not only the powers expressly enumerated in the Constitution but also all powers that are reasonably implied by and necessary and proper for the execution of enumerated powers. The Constitution should be broadly construed to allow the federal government to fulfil its constitutional purposes; a constitution that enumerated every detail would be as prolix as a legal code and could scarcely be embraced by the human mind.',
