      "M v. Child and Family Agency [2023] IEHC 557 concerned an unaccompanied minor who had arrived in Ireland seeking international protection and who came into the care of the Child and Family Agency. The central constitutional question was whether the State's obligations under Article 42A extended to taking positive steps toward family reunification or family-based placement for such a child. The High Court held that Article 42A's guarantee of the natural and imprescriptible rights of all children is universal in its application and is not confined to children born to Irish parents or children who are nationals of the State. The CFA was accordingly required to consider the child's right to family life and to pursue family reunification actively as part of its statutory mandate. The Court found that the constitutional imperative of Article 42A supplemented and informed the statutory duties of the CFA under the Child Care Act 1991. The judgment drew on earlier authority establishing that the rights of the child are now constitutionally grounded independently of the rights of parents or guardians, and confirmed that the best interests of the child must be the paramount consideration in all decisions made by the State and its agencies concerning the child. The case is significant for extending the reach of Article 42A to children in the international protection system and for affirming the positive rather than merely defensive character of the State's constitutional obligations toward children in its care.",
