      "Article 42A introduced a constitutional basis for statutory adoption of a child against the wishes of birth parents, but the threshold for such adoption is stringent and requires the court to be satisfied that it is in the best interests of the child having regard to the rights and welfare of the child, the duty of parents and the duty of the State. The Court of Appeal confirmed that the tension between the rights of birth parents under Article 41 and the rights of the child under Article 42A must be resolved through a proportionality analysis, in which adoption without parental consent is reserved for cases where it is clearly in the child's best interests and all lesser interventions have been considered. The constitutional rights of birth parents, while not absolute, impose a significant burden of justification on the State before adoption can be ordered.",
