    citation: '[2021] IESC 1',
    year: 2021,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Ireland',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'The Supreme Court confirmed that the constitutional rights of children born outside of marriage are recognised under both Article 42A and the evolving concept of the family under Article 41, and that the de facto family formed by an unmarried couple and their children can attract constitutional protection. The decision represents a significant departure from the restrictive approach established in The State (Nicolaou) v. An Bord Ucht\u00e1la [1966] IR 567, in which the Supreme Court had declined to recognise the constitutional family rights of the unmarried father, and signals that the post-Thirty-First Amendment constitutional order extends greater protection to the non-marital family. The Court held that constitutional evolution must be acknowledged and that the unenumerated rights jurisprudence, combined with Article 42A, supports recognition of the rights of children of unmarried parents on terms more closely aligned with those enjoyed by children of married parents.',
