    full_summary:
      'In re J.J. [2021] IESC 1 was a Supreme Court decision of considerable constitutional significance concerning the status of children born outside marriage under the Irish Constitution. The case required the Court to revisit the long-standing precedent of The State (Nicolaou) v. An Bord Ucht\u00e1la [1966] IR 567, which had held that the constitutional concept of the family in Article 41 was confined to the marital family and that an unmarried father had no constitutional family rights in relation to his child. The Supreme Court, in a carefully reasoned majority judgment, held that the constitutional position had evolved significantly since Nicolaou. The combination of the unenumerated rights jurisprudence developed since Ryan v. Attorney General [1965] IR 294, the enactment of Article 42A by the Thirty-First Amendment in 2012, and developments in ECHR case law together supported a more expansive reading of constitutional family protection for the non-marital family. The Court confirmed that children of unmarried parents have constitutional rights that the State must vindicate and that the de facto family formed by an unmarried couple and their children is not constitutionally invisible. While the Court stopped short of fully equating marital and non-marital family rights, the judgment represents a landmark step in the constitutionalisation of non-marital family life and is essential reading for FE-1 candidates on the evolution of family rights under the Irish Constitution.',
