    citation: '[2009] IESC 59; [2010] 1 IR 262',
    year: 2009,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Ireland',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'The constitutional right of access to the courts under Article 34.3 may be restricted by the Oireachtas for legitimate purposes, but any restriction must be proportionate and must not amount to a practical denial of the constitutional right. A statutory scheme establishing a redress mechanism for victims of institutional abuse may constitutionally limit access to courts as a trade-off for guaranteed compensation, but such a limitation must be freely chosen by the claimant and must not involve an unconstitutional abrogation of the right of access. The State cannot retrospectively extinguish legal rights of abuse survivors without constitutional justification.',
    key_quote:
      'The right of access to the courts is a constitutional right of fundamental importance; while the Oireachtas may legitimately create alternative dispute resolution mechanisms, it may not constitutionally compel a person to surrender that right without adequate and proportionate justification.',
    full_summary:
      "D. v. Residential Institutions Redress Review Committee [2009] IESC 59 arose from the statutory scheme established by the Residential Institutions Redress Act 2002 to provide compensation for persons who had suffered abuse in residential institutions in Ireland. The applicant challenged aspects of the scheme, including review procedures and limitations on access to courts, as unconstitutional interferences with their constitutional rights. The Supreme Court examined the constitutional right of access to the courts, derived from Article 34.3 and recognised as an unenumerated personal right under Article 40.3, and assessed whether the statutory framework constitutionally limited that right. The Court acknowledged that the Oireachtas has legitimate authority to establish alternative redress mechanisms and that voluntary participation in such schemes does not infringe constitutional rights. However, the Court stressed that the constitutional right of access to courts cannot be retrospectively withdrawn or made practically unavailable without meeting a stringent proportionality test. The judgment also addressed the constitutional dimension of the State's obligations toward survivors of institutional abuse, including the positive obligation under Article 40.3 to protect the personal rights of citizens against non-State actors. This case is significant for its analysis of the limits on Oireachtas power to restrict constitutional rights through legislation and for its treatment of the constitutional position of abuse survivors seeking redress.",
