    citation: '[2016] IEHC 210',
    year: 2016,
    court: 'High Court of Ireland',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'The constitutional right to an expeditious trial under Article 38.1 applies to prosecutions for historical child sexual abuse offences, and an accused may apply to prohibit a trial where the delay, whether prosecutorial or systemic, has caused real and demonstrable prejudice to their ability to defend the proceedings. The High Court applied the test established in DK v. Crowley [2002] 2 IR 744, requiring the applicant to establish that the delay was inordinate, that it was attributable to the prosecution or the system, and that real prejudice has resulted that cannot be remedied by appropriate trial directions. The mere passage of time does not of itself entitle an accused to prohibition; the applicant must demonstrate specific, identifiable prejudice.',
    key_quote:
      'The right to an expeditious trial is a constitutional right, and while the gravity of the alleged offences is a relevant consideration, it cannot override the constitutional entitlement of an accused to a fair and speedy trial where inordinate delay has caused demonstrated prejudice.',
    full_summary:
      'M. MCD. v. Director of Public Prosecutions [2016] IEHC 210 was a High Court judicial review application in which the applicant sought to prohibit his trial on historical child sexual abuse charges on the ground of delay. The High Court examined the constitutional right to an expeditious trial, derived from the constitutional guarantee of fair procedures under Article 38.1, and applied the test set out by the Supreme Court in DK v. Crowley [2002] 2 IR 744. That test requires the court to assess: whether the delay was inordinate; whether the delay was excusable or attributable to the accused; whether, having regard to the nature of the delay, the accused had waived their right to object; and whether real prejudice, not capable of being remedied at trial, had resulted. The High Court noted the particular difficulties presented by historical sexual abuse cases, where both the interests of complainants and the rights of accused persons carry constitutional weight. The Court declined to prohibit the trial on the facts, finding that while significant time had elapsed, the applicant had not demonstrated specific, identifiable prejudice sufficient to outweigh the public interest in the prosecution of serious crime. The judgment illustrates the constitutional balancing exercise between the rights of the accused and the interests of complainants in the prosecution of historical sexual offences.',
