    case_name: 'In re Abortion Services (Safe Access Zones) (Northern Ireland) Bill',
    citation: '[2022] UKSC 32; [2023] AC 505',
    year: 2022,
    court: 'UK Supreme Court',
    jurisdiction: 'UK',
    legal_principle:
      'The UK Supreme Court held that the Abortion Services (Safe Access Zones) (Northern Ireland) Bill, passed by the Northern Ireland Assembly, exceeded the legislative competence of the Assembly under the Northern Ireland Act 1998 because it engaged an excepted matter \u2014 the law relating to abortion \u2014 which is reserved to the Westminster Parliament under Schedule 2 of the 1998 Act. The case is constitutionally significant as an illustration of the devolved constitutional architecture of the United Kingdom, including the distinction between transferred, reserved, and excepted matters, which is analogous in structural terms to the distinction between legislative competences in federal and quasi-federal constitutional systems. The constitutional limitation on Assembly competence was enforced by the courts as a constitutional constraint, not merely a statutory one, on the exercise of devolved legislative power.',
    key_quote:
      'The Assembly has no competence to legislate in respect of excepted matters; abortion law is an excepted matter under the Northern Ireland Act 1998, and the Bill accordingly exceeds the legislative competence of the Assembly and is not law.',
    full_summary:
      "In re Abortion Services (Safe Access Zones) (Northern Ireland) Bill [2022] UKSC 32 arose from a referral to the UK Supreme Court under the Northern Ireland Act 1998 of a Bill passed by the Northern Ireland Assembly establishing safe access zones around abortion service providers to prevent harassment of service users. The Attorney General for Northern Ireland referred the Bill on the ground that it touched upon the law relating to abortion, which was an excepted matter under Schedule 2 of the 1998 Act and therefore outside the legislative competence of the Assembly. The Supreme Court agreed, holding that the Bill was beyond the Assembly's competence because it inevitably engaged the legal framework governing access to and regulation of abortion services, which remained a Westminster matter under the constitutional settlement established by the Northern Ireland Act 1998. The judgment provides a detailed analysis of the devolved constitutional architecture of Northern Ireland, explaining the tripartite division of matters into excepted (permanently reserved to Westminster), reserved (capable of devolution by agreement), and transferred (within Assembly competence). The case is instructive for Irish constitutional law students because it illustrates a structured constitutional division of legislative competence and demonstrates how constitutional courts enforce the boundaries of legislative authority. The structural parallels with debates in Irish constitutional law about the scope of Oireachtas competence and constitutional limitations on legislative power make this case a useful comparative authority.",
