    case_name: 'The People (DPP) v. Madden',
    citation: '[1977] IR 337',
    year: 1977,
    court: 'Court of Criminal Appeal',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      "A statement made by an accused person during a period of detention is admissible only if it was made voluntarily and in circumstances where the accused's constitutional rights were respected throughout the period of custody. The constitutional rights of a detained person, including the right to be informed of the reason for arrest, the right of access to a solicitor, and the right to silence, impose positive obligations on the Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na, and any breach of those rights that is causally connected to the taking of a statement may render the statement inadmissible. The voluntariness of a statement must be assessed having regard to all the circumstances of the detention, including the conditions of custody and whether the accused was apprised of and given a meaningful opportunity to exercise their constitutional rights.",
    key_quote:
      'The constitutional rights of a detained person are not suspended by arrest; the Garda\u00ed must respect those rights throughout the period of detention, and any statement obtained in circumstances where those rights were not respected will be excluded if the breach was causally connected to the obtaining of the statement.',
    full_summary:
      'The People (DPP) v. Madden [1977] IR 337 is a leading early authority on the admissibility of statements obtained from persons in Garda custody and on the constitutional obligations that attach to the exercise of Garda detention powers. The case involved a challenge to the admissibility of a statement made by the accused during a period of detention, on the grounds that the statement had not been taken in accordance with the constitutional requirements governing voluntariness and the protection of constitutional rights in custody. The Court of Criminal Appeal examined the constitutional framework for detention, noting that the arrest and detention of a person engages their fundamental constitutional right to personal liberty under Article 40.4 and their right to fair procedures under Article 38.1. The Court held that the constitutional rights of a detained person are positive rights that impose active obligations on the detaining authority: the accused must be informed of the reason for their arrest, must be given a meaningful opportunity to consult a solicitor, must be informed of their right to silence, and must not be subjected to oppressive or improper questioning. A statement obtained in breach of these requirements is tainted by constitutional infirmity and may be excluded. The case is part of the foundational body of Irish constitutional jurisprudence on the rights of persons in custody and contributes to the constitutional framework subsequently developed in cases such as The People (DPP) v. Quilligan [1986] IR 495 and the criminal procedure reforms enacted in the Criminal Justice Act 1984.',
