      'The constitutional rights of a person in Garda custody include the right to be treated with dignity, the right to have the conditions of custody conform to basic constitutional standards, and the right to have the protections of the Custody Regulations observed, as those Regulations give effect to the constitutional rights of detained persons. Where Garda conduct in the course of custody falls below the constitutional standard required by Article 38.1 and Article 40.4, evidence obtained as a result of that conduct may be excluded, even if the initial arrest was lawful, on the ground that the constitutional rights of the accused were violated during the period of detention.',
