    legal_principle:
      'The civil forfeiture regime under the Proceeds of Crime Act 1996, operated by the Criminal Assets Bureau, is constitutionally permissible as it is directed at the property itself rather than at the personal punishment of the individual, and therefore does not offend the constitutional presumption of innocence under Article 38.1 or the right to property under Article 43. The Supreme Court confirmed that the constitutional right to private property under Article 43 is not absolute and may be regulated by the Oireachtas in the public interest, provided the regulation is proportionate; the deprivation of property representing the proceeds of crime is a proportionate measure in pursuit of the legitimate State objective of combating organised crime.',
