    full_summary:
      "Criminal Assets Bureau v. Murphy [2018] IESC 12 was a Supreme Court decision upholding the constitutionality of the civil forfeiture regime operated by the Criminal Assets Bureau (CAB) under the Proceeds of Crime Act 1996. The respondent challenged the constitutionality of the forfeiture application on the grounds that it violated the constitutional right to property under Article 43, the presumption of innocence under Article 38.1, the right to silence, and the right to a fair trial under Article 38.1 more broadly, arguing that the civil standard of proof used in CAB proceedings was insufficient protection for constitutional rights. The Supreme Court rejected these challenges. The Court held that the Proceeds of Crime Act operates in rem \u2014 it targets property which is the proceeds of crime, not the person who may have acquired it \u2014 and therefore does not engage the constitutional presumption of innocence in the same way as a criminal prosecution. The civil standard of proof is constitutionally adequate for forfeiture proceedings that do not result in criminal conviction or punishment. The Court also upheld the constitutionality of the provisions permitting the drawing of adverse inferences from the respondent's failure to provide information about the source of their assets, finding that this was proportionate to the legitimate public interest in depriving criminals of the proceeds of their crimes. The judgment is significant for its analysis of the constitutional limits on property rights under Article 43 and is a leading authority on the constitutional status of civil asset forfeiture.",
