    full_summary:
      "Dillon v. O'Brien and Davis (1887) 20 LR Ir 300 is a historical Irish authority from the Court of Exchequer on the common law power of search and seizure incident to a lawful arrest. The case arose from a civil action in which the plaintiff challenged the seizure of documents by police officers at the time of his arrest. The Court of Exchequer held that a police officer who has effected a lawful arrest of a person suspected of a serious crime has, as an incident of that lawful arrest, the power to search the arrested person and to seize property in their possession that is reasonably believed to be evidence of the crime for which the arrest was made. The basis for this power is both practical \u2014 to prevent the destruction of evidence \u2014 and legal: the law recognises that a lawful arrest creates a temporary dominion over the arrested person and their immediate possessions sufficient to justify the preservation of relevant evidence. The case is significant for Irish constitutional and evidence law as the foundational pre-independence authority on search and seizure incident to arrest. It predates the constitutional order established by Bunreacht na h\u00c9ireann in 1937 but informs the interpretation of Article 40.5 (inviolability of the dwelling) and the statutory framework governing search powers. The principle that the legality of a search is dependent upon the legality of the underlying arrest remains fundamental to contemporary constitutional analysis of evidence obtained through police searches.",
