    full_summary:
      "Jennings v. Quinn [1968] IR 305 is a Supreme Court decision on the constitutional protection of the home under Article 40.5 of the Constitution and the requirements for a lawful search of a private dwelling. The case arose from a challenge to the legality of a search conducted by Garda\u00ed who entered the plaintiff's home without a valid warrant. The Supreme Court held that Article 40.5, which guarantees the inviolability of the dwelling of every citizen, is a substantive constitutional right that imposes a strict requirement on the Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na and other State authorities: entry into and search of a private home is constitutionally impermissible unless it is conducted in accordance with law, meaning there must be a valid statutory authorisation for the entry, typically in the form of a warrant issued by a District Court judge. The Court held that the absence of a valid warrant rendered the entry a breach of the constitutional right under Article 40.5. The case established that Article 40.5 is of particular importance in the constitutional hierarchy of rights because the home is a place where the individual should be most secure from State intrusion, and that the courts will examine any claimed legal basis for a home search rigorously. Jennings v. Quinn is a foundational authority on Article 40.5 and is an important antecedent to the constitutional exclusionary rule jurisprudence developed in The People (AG) v. O'Brien [1965] IR 142 and The People (DPP) v. Kenny [1990] 2 IR 110.",
