      'The constitutional right to an expeditious trial under Article 38.1 may be violated by prosecutorial delay as well as systemic delay, and where delay in bringing a prosecution is attributable to the prosecution authorities and has caused real prejudice to the accused, the court may prohibit the trial. The Supreme Court confirmed the principles governing delay in historical sexual abuse cases, including that the delay inherent in the late reporting of such offences must be taken into account in assessing the overall delay and its constitutional consequences. However, the prejudice to the accused must be real and specific rather than merely speculative, and the court must balance the right of the accused to an expeditious trial against the constitutional right of the complainant to have the alleged crime prosecuted.',
