    full_summary:
      "O'Regan v. DPP [1999] IESC 59 is a Supreme Court authority on the constitutional right to an expeditious trial in the context of historical sexual abuse allegations and the principles governing applications to prohibit a trial on grounds of delay. The applicant sought judicial review and an order prohibiting his trial on historical sexual offences, arguing that the delay in bringing the prosecution \u2014 spanning many years from the alleged offences to the commencement of proceedings \u2014 had violated his constitutional right to an expeditious trial under Article 38.1 and had caused him real and specific prejudice in preparing his defence. The Supreme Court examined the principles governing delay in criminal proceedings established in its earlier case law and confirmed the distinction between delay attributable to the complainant's late disclosure of abuse and delay attributable to the prosecution authorities or the system. The Court acknowledged that late reporting in historical sexual abuse cases is a well-recognised phenomenon with its own psychological dimensions, and that the inevitable delay in such cases does not of itself constitute a constitutional violation. However, where prosecutorial delay \u2014 delay in the conduct of the investigation or the bringing of the prosecution after the complaint was made \u2014 has compounded the overall delay and caused specific, identifiable prejudice to the accused, constitutional prohibition of the trial may be warranted. The Court declined to prohibit the trial on the facts, finding that the accused had not demonstrated sufficient specific prejudice. The case is an important authority in the FE-1 constitutional law syllabus on the right to an expeditious trial and is frequently tested in the context of delay applications in historical criminal cases.",
