      "The Court of Common Pleas held that a general warrant issued by the Secretary of State authorising the search of Entick's home and seizure of his papers was unlawful, as no legal authority existed for such a warrant. The judgment established the foundational common law principle that every invasion of private property, however slight, must be justified by law, and that executive officials have no inherent power to invade the homes or property of citizens except as authorised by clear positive law. Entick v. Carrington is the historical common law antecedent of constitutional rights to privacy of the dwelling and freedom from arbitrary search, and has been cited in Irish courts as a foundational authority underpinning Article 40.5.",
