      "The People (DPP) v. Balfe concerned a search warrant that was technically defective on its face and the question of whether evidence obtained during the search authorised by that warrant was admissible in criminal proceedings. The Court of Criminal Appeal held that the defect was not a mere procedural irregularity that could be overlooked, but a failure to comply with the statutory requirements that governed the issue of search warrants. Because the entry into and search of the accused's dwelling was not authorised by a lawfully issued warrant, it constituted a breach of the constitutional right to the inviolability of the dwelling under Article 40.5. The Court applied the principle, long established in Irish constitutional criminal procedure, that evidence obtained by deliberate or conscious violation of constitutional rights is prima facie inadmissible. The exclusionary rule as applied in Balfe is grounded not in a discretionary balancing exercise but in the constitutional imperative to vindicate rights. The case is important for understanding the relationship between Article 40.5, the law of search and seizure, and the constitutional exclusionary rule in Irish criminal procedure, and is regularly cited in assessments of the rights of the accused at the investigative stage.",
