    legal_principle:
      "The Supreme Court confirmed the constitutional and procedural principles governing appellate review of findings of fact made at first instance, holding that an appellate court should not disturb findings of fact by a trial judge who had the benefit of seeing and hearing witnesses unless they are plainly wrong. The decision has a constitutional dimension in that it reflects the constitutional architecture allocating fact-finding to courts of first instance and confining the appellate jurisdiction principally to errors of law. The principle ensures that the administration of justice, as contemplated by Article 34, operates through a coherent hierarchy in which the trial court's primary constitutional role as trier of fact is respected.",
