      'The Court of Criminal Appeal held that the constitutional rights of an accused person attach from the moment of arrest and must be respected throughout all stages of custody and investigation. The decision was an early application of the principle that the protections guaranteed by the Constitution \u2014 including those under Articles 38, 40.3, and 40.5 \u2014 are not abstract entitlements but have immediate operational effect in criminal procedure. The case reinforced that Garda conduct during arrest, search, and detention must conform to constitutional standards, and that evidence obtained in breach of those standards may be subject to challenge.',
