      "The High Court held that the Revenue Commissioners' refusal to recognise for tax purposes a same-sex marriage lawfully solemnised in Canada did not constitute an unconstitutional breach of Article 40.1 equality, on the basis that the Constitution's definition of marriage as understood at the time of enactment did not include same-sex marriage and that Article 41 was not intended to protect such relationships. The case was a significant constitutional landmark, however, in raising squarely the question of whether the equality guarantee required recognition of same-sex unions, anticipating the constitutional and legislative developments that ultimately led to the Marriage Equality referendum in 2015.",
