      "Zappone v. Revenue Commissioners was a High Court case brought by Katherine Zappone and Ann Louise Gilligan, who had married in Canada and sought recognition of their marriage in Ireland for tax purposes. McKechnie J was asked to determine whether the refusal of the Revenue Commissioners to recognise the marriage constituted a breach of the constitutional equality guarantee under Article 40.1 and an infringement of their personal rights under Article 40.3. The Court held that it could not extend the constitutional definition of marriage to include same-sex unions, as such an extension would require either constitutional amendment by referendum or a finding that the Constitution's original meaning included same-sex marriage, neither of which was open to the Court. McKechnie J expressed considerable sympathy for the applicants and acknowledged that the constitutional and legislative position might be inappropriate from a rights perspective, but held that reform lay with the people through the amendment process rather than with the courts through judicial interpretation. The case is foundational in the history of constitutional litigation on same-sex rights in Ireland, and is regularly cited in constitutional law courses as an illustration of the limits of judicial constitutionalism and the role of popular sovereignty in constitutional change, culminating in the Marriage Equality referendum of 2015.",
