      "The Supreme Court held that the constitutional right of access to the courts under Article 34 is not absolute and may be limited by proportionate measures necessary for the efficient administration of justice, including orders restraining vexatious litigants from issuing further proceedings without leave of court. The Court confirmed that delay and abuse of process in the course of litigation may justify restrictive orders that limit access to court, provided such orders are proportionate and do not wholly deprive a party of the constitutional right to litigate genuine claims. The decision balances the individual's constitutional right of access to justice against the court's inherent jurisdiction to protect the integrity of the judicial process.",
