    legal_principle:
      'The Supreme Court upheld the constitutional validity of emergency health regulations restricting freedom of movement during the COVID-19 pandemic, holding that the restrictions were proportionate limitations on the personal rights guaranteed by Article 40.3 and Article 40.4. The Court confirmed that the Oireachtas may validly delegate power to the executive to make regulations restricting constitutional rights in a public health emergency, provided the delegation is sufficiently defined, the restrictions are proportionate, and adequate oversight mechanisms exist. The decision is a landmark in Irish constitutional law concerning the constitutional permissibility of emergency measures that curtail fundamental rights.',
