      'The Supreme Court held that Irish citizens enjoy a constitutional right to travel protected by Article 40.3 as an unenumerated personal right, and that the refusal by the State to issue a passport to an Irish citizen constitutes an interference with that right which must be proportionate and grounded in clear legal authority. The Court confirmed that the right to travel is a fundamental personal right which the State must vindicate, and that executive decisions restricting it are subject to constitutional review for proportionality.',
