      "The court established the common law baseline rule that evidence is admissible regardless of the manner in which it was obtained, even if obtained illegally or by theft. The judge articulated the principle that the origin of the evidence is irrelevant to its admissibility at common law, provided it is otherwise relevant and cogent. This English historical rule forms the direct foil against which the Irish constitutional exclusionary rule is measured and from which Irish constitutional jurisprudence deliberately departs. Understanding this case is essential for appreciating why the People (AG) v. O'Brien [1965] IR 142 represented a foundational constitutional innovation.",
