      "The Northern Ireland Court of Appeal examined the admissibility of evidence obtained during a search conducted in circumstances where the proportionality of the interference with the accused's rights was challenged, affirming that in assessing admissibility of evidence obtained through searches, courts must consider whether the conduct of the searching authorities was proportionate to the legitimate aim pursued. The decision reflects the incorporation of ECHR proportionality analysis into Northern Irish criminal procedure via the Human Rights Act 1998, offering a comparative perspective for analysing Art 40.5 inviolability of the dwelling and Article 8 ECHR-influenced proportionality review in Irish constitutional law.",
