      'The Court of Criminal Appeal examined the constitutional dimensions of prolonged detention under section 2 of the Criminal Justice (Drug Trafficking) Act 1996, holding that extended detention periods must be judicially authorised and that the right to silence retains constitutional force even under statutory regimes that permit extended custody. The court affirmed that while the Oireachtas may legislate for extended detention in serious cases, any such regime must be compatible with the right to a fair trial under Article 38.1 and the general personal rights guaranteed by Article 40.3, and that adverse inferences from silence must be carefully circumscribed to avoid constitutional invalidity.',
