      "Tuite arose in the context of detention under the Offences Against the State Act 1939, which provided for extended detention in connection with offences against the security of the State. The accused challenged the admissibility of statements made during his detention on the ground that proper procedures had not been followed and that his constitutional rights had not been vindicated. The Court of Criminal Appeal held that the constitutional framework applies to all forms of Garda detention, including detention under special security legislation. It affirmed that where custody regulations or constitutional standards are not observed \u2014 whether through failure to inform the detainee of his rights, denial of access to a solicitor, or improper conduct of interviews \u2014 the resulting statements are tainted and inadmissible if the breach constitutes a deliberate and conscious violation of constitutional rights. Tuite is historically significant because it was decided before the Criminal Justice Act 1984 and the Custody Regulations of 1987, demonstrating the courts' willingness to impose constitutional constraints in the absence of detailed statutory rules. For FE-1 candidates, Tuite is relevant to questions on the Offences Against the State Act, the constitutional rights of persons in security-related detention, and the general principle that constitutional rights cannot be displaced by legislative provision for special detention regimes.",
