      "In R v. Vu, police executed a search warrant at premises suspected of involvement in cannabis cultivation. During the search they found and searched two computers without any specific warrant authority to do so. The Supreme Court of Canada held that the search of the computers was unconstitutional, requiring exclusion of the digital evidence obtained. The Court reasoned that computers occupy a unique position in the constitutional privacy landscape: they routinely contain intimate details of a person's life \u2014 communications, financial records, photographs, browsing history, and location data \u2014 in quantities and of a sensitivity far exceeding anything that could be stored in a physical space. Because the privacy interests engaged by a computer search are so distinct and so substantial, a general warrant to search premises cannot be read as implicitly authorising a search of computers found there. A separate, specific judicial pre-authorisation addressing the computer or device is constitutionally required. The decision firmly rejected a simple trespass-based or incidental-search rationale for computer access. It has been influential in Irish jurisprudence: the High Court in DPP v. Behan and related digital evidence cases have drawn on Vu to articulate the heightened constitutional standard applicable under Article 40.3 of the Irish Constitution when An Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na seek to search and analyse digital devices. The case stands as a leading common-law authority for the proposition that the digital search and seizure context demands a sui generis constitutional framework rather than an extension of pre-digital search principles.",
