      'The Supreme Court held that the right of freedom of association guaranteed by Article 40.6.1.iii of the Constitution includes not only the right to form and join associations, but also the correlative right not to join an association. Legislation compelling persons to join a particular trade union or to remain in membership of a union as a condition of employment constitutes an unconstitutional interference with the negative aspect of the right of association. This was one of the earliest and most significant decisions establishing the dual character \u2014 positive and negative \u2014 of the constitutional right of association in Ireland.',
