      'The Supreme Court upheld an interlocutory injunction restraining the defendants from providing information to pregnant women about abortion services available outside Ireland, holding that the unenumerated personal right to life of the unborn recognised in Article 40.3.3 created a correlative constitutional obligation on the State \u2014 and on courts as organs of the State \u2014 to restrain conduct that would frustrate or undermine that right. The Court further held that the freedom of expression guaranteed by Article 40.6.1 does not extend to the provision of information whose dominant purpose is to facilitate termination of a pregnancy, because that freedom, like all personal rights, is subject to the superior constitutional right to life of the unborn. The injunction was upheld pending a full Supreme Court determination of the substantive issues, reinforcing the priority accorded to Article 40.3.3 in the hierarchy of constitutional rights.',
