      "SPUC v. Coogan arose from proceedings brought by the Society for the Protection of Unborn Children seeking injunctions against named defendants \u2014 counsellors and advisors \u2014 who were providing information to pregnant women, including the names, addresses, and contact details of abortion clinics operating lawfully in Great Britain. The defendants argued that providing factual information of this kind was protected by the freedom of expression guarantee in Article 40.6.1 and by the right to freedom of communication generally. The Supreme Court, affirming the High Court's grant of an interlocutory injunction, held that the constitutional framework created by the Eighth Amendment in 1983 \u2014 which inserted Article 40.3.3 \u2014 imposed a positive obligation on the courts, as organs of the State, to protect and vindicate the right to life of the unborn. In that context, the provision of information that would enable a pregnant woman to travel to and obtain an abortion abroad was held to constitute assistance in the destruction of that right, and fell outside the protection of Article 40.6.1. The Court distinguished the defendant's role from that of a newspaper providing general information in the public interest, emphasising the targeted and purposeful nature of the counselling activity. The case is a direct precursor to SPUC v. Open Door Counselling and to the X Case (Attorney General v. X [1992] 1 IR 1), and illuminates the constitutional trajectory that ultimately led to referenda on the right to information and the right to travel. It is an essential case for understanding the interplay between Article 40.3.3, freedom of expression, and the limits of constitutional rights in the Irish system.",
