      "The Supreme Court granted a permanent injunction restraining the defendants from assisting pregnant women to travel abroad to obtain abortions by providing information about abortion clinics outside Ireland, holding that such assistance constituted a direct and proximate threat to the constitutionally guaranteed right to life of the unborn under Article 40.3.3. The Court held that the right to life of the unborn is a superior constitutional value that takes precedence over the counselling organisations' claimed rights of expression and communication, and that no right \u2014 whether framed as professional advice, freedom of expression, or freedom of association \u2014 can override a constitutionally guaranteed right to life. The decision was subsequently challenged before the European Court of Human Rights, which held in Open Door and Dublin Well Woman v. Ireland (1992) that the injunction violated Article 10 of the European Convention on Human Rights.",
