      'Ryanair DAC v. An Taoiseach was a judicial review challenge brought by the airline Ryanair against emergency travel restriction regulations made by the Government of Ireland in the early stages of the COVID-19 pandemic. The regulations restricted non-essential travel into and out of Ireland and imposed requirements and limitations on aviation operations, with direct and significant financial consequences for the applicant. Ryanair argued that the regulations constituted an unjustified and disproportionate interference with its constitutionally protected right to earn a livelihood under Article 40.3 and with the personal liberty of individuals under Article 40.4. The company further argued that the statutory basis for the emergency regulations was itself of doubtful validity, raising questions about the scope of permissible delegated legislative power. The High Court dismissed all grounds of the challenge. Applying the Heaney v. Ireland proportionality test, the Court found that the public health emergency created by the pandemic furnished a compelling and constitutionally legitimate basis for the restrictions, and that the regulations were carefully calibrated to pursue that aim while minimising their impact on rights to the extent consistent with the public health objective. The case illustrates the judicial approach to constitutional rights review in genuine emergency conditions, and the significant but not unlimited deference accorded to the executive in such circumstances. It is a useful modern illustration of proportionality analysis and the constitutional limitations on economic rights.',
