      'Grace v. An Bord Plean\u00e1la concerned a challenge to the constitutional validity of provisions of planning legislation that restricted the circumstances in which, and the time within which, a person could bring judicial review proceedings to challenge a decision of An Bord Plean\u00e1la. The applicant argued that these statutory restrictions \u2014 including leave requirements, short limitation periods, and costs rules \u2014 collectively operated to deprive affected persons of their constitutional right of access to the courts under Article 34. The Supreme Court, in an important judgment on the relationship between statutory planning procedure and constitutional rights, held that the right of access to the courts is a constitutional guarantee that the Oireachtas may regulate but may not effectively abolish or render meaningless. The Court applied a proportionality analysis to the impugned provisions, asking whether the restrictions on judicial review were rationally connected to the legitimate legislative objective of providing certainty and finality in planning decisions, and whether they impaired the constitutional right to access justice no more than was necessary. The Court confirmed that the constitutional right of access to courts applies to administrative decisions with significant effects on individuals and that the planning statutory scheme must be interpreted so as to preserve a genuine and effective right of access. The case is significant for constitutional law students for its analysis of Article 34 access rights and the constitutional scrutiny of statutory limitations on judicial review in the planning context.',
