      "The High Court considered the constitutional framework governing the historical criminalisation of attempted suicide, holding that any statutory provision which criminalised a person for attempting to take their own life was in fundamental conflict with the constitutional right to bodily integrity under Article 40.3 and with the dignity of the human person guaranteed by the Constitution. The case examined the constitutional status of mental health legislation and the extent to which the State's constitutional obligation to protect life under Article 40.3.2 can be reconciled with respect for the personal autonomy and bodily integrity of persons in mental health crises.",
