    full_summary:
      "Mohan v. Ireland and the Attorney General raised constitutional questions about the historical provision in the Criminal Law (Suicide) Act 1993, which abolished the criminal offence of suicide and attempted suicide, and about the preceding legal framework under which attempts to take one's own life had been treated as criminal acts. The applicant challenged the constitutionality of aspects of the mental health legal framework as they had operated historically, arguing that the criminalisation of attempted suicide \u2014 which had prevailed under Irish law until the 1993 Act \u2014 was incompatible with the constitutional right to bodily integrity recognised in Ryan v. Attorney General [1965] IR 294, with the right to personal autonomy derived from Article 40.3, and with the constitutional guarantee of the dignity of the human person. The High Court engaged with the constitutional analysis of bodily integrity and personal liberty in the context of mental health, considering the tension between the State's positive obligation under Article 40.3.2 to protect citizens' lives and the prohibition on using criminal law as an instrument of State intervention in mental health crises in a manner that itself violates constitutional rights. The case contributes to Irish constitutional jurisprudence on the unenumerated rights doctrine and the constitutional framework for mental health law, and is useful for students examining the development of personal rights under Article 40.3.",
