    citation: '[2020] IEHC',
    year: 2020,
    court: 'High Court of Ireland',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'The High Court upheld the constitutional protection of freedom of expression and journalistic activity under Article 40.6.1, affirming that the press occupies a constitutionally recognised role in a democratic society and that restrictions on publication or on the dissemination of information of genuine public interest must satisfy a proportionality test before they can be permitted. The Court further examined the interface between the constitutional right to freedom of expression, the law of defamation, and the constitutional rights of private individuals to their good name and reputation under Article 40.3.2, holding that these competing rights must be balanced with reference to the nature, context, and public interest value of the expression in question.',
