      'The High Court considered the constitutional requirements applicable to professional disciplinary proceedings conducted by the Medical Council, holding that such proceedings \u2014 though not an administration of justice in the Article 34 sense \u2014 must comply with the constitutional guarantee of fair procedures under Article 40.3 and the principles of natural and constitutional justice. The Court held that a medical professional facing sanctions, including erasure from the register, is entitled to the full panoply of fair procedure protections: the right to be heard, the right to know the case to be met, the right to an unbiased tribunal, and the right to have the matter determined on the evidence without irrelevant considerations.',
