      'Medical Council v. T.M. arose from disciplinary proceedings conducted by the Medical Council of Ireland against a registered medical practitioner under the Medical Practitioners Act. The practitioner challenged the conduct of the proceedings, alleging that the process had been conducted in breach of the principles of natural and constitutional justice, in particular the right to know the full case to be met, the right to cross-examine witnesses, and the right to have the matter determined by an independent and unbiased panel. The High Court examined the constitutional obligations imposed on statutory professional regulatory bodies when exercising their disciplinary function. The Court confirmed the established Irish principle that, while professional disciplinary proceedings are not an administration of justice within the exclusive domain of the courts under Article 34, they nevertheless engage the constitutional rights of the practitioner under Article 40.3 and must meet the standards of constitutional justice. The level of procedural protection required is calibrated to the gravity of the proceedings and the severity of the potential consequences: where the sanction under consideration includes erasure from the medical register \u2014 effectively permanent exclusion from a regulated profession \u2014 the constitutional obligation of fair procedures is at its most demanding. The case is a useful authority on the constitutional justice requirements applicable to professional regulatory tribunals and the limits of the purely executive characterisation of such functions.',
