    full_summary:
      'NECI v. The Labour Court was a landmark Supreme Court decision on the constitutional boundaries of delegated legislation in Ireland. The National Electrical Contractors Ireland challenged the constitutional validity of provisions of the Industrial Relations (Amendment) Act 2012, under which Joint Labour Committees \u2014 tripartite bodies comprising employer, trade union, and independent members \u2014 were empowered to make Employment Regulation Orders setting minimum pay rates and conditions for entire employment sectors, enforceable by criminal penalty. The Supreme Court held these provisions unconstitutional on the ground that they violated Article 15.2.1 of the Constitution, which vests the sole and exclusive power to make laws for the State in the Oireachtas. The Court applied and refined the principles-and-policies test, originating in Cityview Press v. An Chomhairle Oili\u00fana [1980] IR 381, under which delegated legislation is constitutionally permissible only if the parent Act itself determines the essential principles and policies and merely delegates the administrative filling in of detail. In NECI, the Court found that the 2012 Act had crossed the constitutional line, conferring on the Labour Court and Joint Labour Committees an effectively unlimited normative power to determine the substantive content of employment regulation without the Oireachtas having set any meaningful guiding principles or policies. The decision is one of the most significant modern Irish constitutional cases on the non-delegation doctrine and the separation of legislative power, and is essential study for FE-1 candidates examining Article 15 and delegated legislation.',
