    full_summary:
      'Walsh v. Irish Red Cross Society arose from the dismissal of an employee of the Irish Red Cross Society following an internal disciplinary process. The plaintiff challenged the validity of the dismissal on the ground that the process had been conducted in breach of the constitutional principles of natural justice, in particular the right to be heard before an adverse decision was taken. The Irish Red Cross Society, as a voluntary and charitable organisation, argued that the constitutional justice requirements applicable to statutory or public decision-making bodies did not apply to it. The High Court rejected this argument, holding that the duty to afford fair procedures to persons whose employment or other significant interests are at stake is not confined to statutory bodies or those exercising public law functions. The Court held that the right to fair procedures before dismissal is rooted in the constitutional right to earn a livelihood under Article 40.3 and in the constitutional principle that every person whose rights or interests may be adversely affected by a decision is entitled to be heard before that decision is made. The decision that the plaintiff had not been given adequate notice of the case against him and had not been afforded a genuine opportunity to respond rendered the dismissal procedurally invalid. The case is an important authority on the reach of natural and constitutional justice beyond the statutory sector and on the employment-related dimension of Article 40.3.',
