    legal_principle:
      'The Supreme Court struck down a provision of the Misuse of Drugs Act 1977 conferring power on the Government by regulation to add substances to the schedule of controlled drugs carrying criminal penalties, holding that the provision unconstitutionally delegated the law-making power of the Oireachtas under Article 15.2.1 without defining the principles and policies within which that power was to be exercised. The Court applied the Cityview Press principles-and-policies test to find that the statutory delegation was unlimited and amounted to an impermissible transfer of the core legislative function \u2014 the decision to make conduct criminal \u2014 to the executive branch. The Oireachtas must itself determine the essential policy choices when criminalising behaviour; it cannot delegate this function wholesale to the Government.',
    key_quote:
      'The Oireachtas cannot delegate to the Government the power to designate substances as controlled drugs attracting criminal liability without defining the principles and policies governing that designation; such a delegation violates Article 15.2.1 of the Constitution.',
    full_summary:
      'Bederev v. Ireland arose from a criminal prosecution in which the defendant was charged with possession of a substance that had been added to the schedule of controlled drugs under the Misuse of Drugs Act 1977 not by the Oireachtas in primary legislation but by the Government acting under a wide regulation-making power conferred by section 2(2) of the Act. The defendant challenged the constitutional validity of this provision, arguing that it unconstitutionally delegated the exclusive law-making power of the Oireachtas to the executive. The Supreme Court upheld the challenge. Applying and extending the principles-and-policies doctrine established in Cityview Press v. An Chomhairle Oili\u00fana [1980] IR 381, the Court held that the decision to render possession or supply of a particular substance a criminal offence is a fundamental legislative choice that engages the constitutional rights and liberties of citizens. This is precisely the kind of core policy decision that the Constitution requires to be made by the Oireachtas itself. Section 2(2) of the 1977 Act conferred on the Government an effectively unconstrained power to criminalise behaviour involving any substance it chose to schedule, without any meaningful legislative guidance or criteria. This amounted to an unconstitutional delegation of the legislative function. The judgment is a landmark modern application of the non-delegation doctrine and is essential for FE-1 candidates studying Article 15, delegated legislation, and constitutional limits on executive power.',
