    full_summary:
      "SPUC v. Grogan involved an application by the Society for the Protection of Unborn Children for an injunction against officers of the Union of Students in Ireland and related student bodies, who had distributed and proposed to continue distributing information about abortion clinics operating in Great Britain. The student union defendants argued, in defence, that the restriction on distributing information about services lawfully available in another EU Member State constituted an unlawful interference with EU free movement of services law, which at the time prevailed over inconsistent provisions of domestic law including constitutional provisions. The High Court referred the EU law question to the Court of Justice of the European Communities (CJEU). The CJEU held in SPUC v. Grogan (Case C-159/90) [1991] that abortion services were indeed 'services' within the Treaty meaning, but that the link between the student bodies and the clinics was too indirect and non-commercial to bring the activity within the scope of the free movement of services provisions. As a result, EU law afforded no protection to the student union's activities, and the Irish constitutional prohibition under Article 40.3.3 could be given effect by the national court. The High Court accordingly granted the injunction. The case is significant both as an Irish constitutional law authority on Article 40.3.3 and as an illustration of the interaction between EU internal market law and national constitutional provisions protecting fundamental rights.",
