    citation: '[2019] IESC 81',
    year: 2019,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Ireland',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'The Supreme Court held that the State has a positive constitutional obligation under Article 40.4 and Article 40.3 to ensure that the conditions in which persons are detained meet a constitutional minimum standard compatible with their dignity and personal rights, and that Article 40.4 habeas corpus proceedings are an appropriate mechanism for a detained person to raise and have determined a complaint that the conditions of their detention violate constitutional rights. Where a prisoner establishes that the conditions of detention are so deficient as to constitute a breach of constitutional minimum standards, the court may order appropriate relief including conditional release or a declaration of constitutional invalidity of the detention conditions.',
