      'The State is under a positive constitutional obligation to ensure that the conditions in which prisoners are detained are consistent with their constitutional rights under Articles 40.3 and 40.4; detention in conditions that fall below the constitutional minimum may be challenged by way of habeas corpus inquiry.',
    full_summary:
      "Simpson v. Governor of Mountjoy Prison was a landmark Supreme Court decision addressing the constitutional obligations of the State in respect of prison conditions in Ireland. The applicant, a sentenced prisoner in Mountjoy Prison, brought Article 40.4 habeas corpus proceedings on the ground that the conditions of his detention \u2014 including severe overcrowding, the requirement to use in-cell buckets in the absence of integral sanitation, and the general deterioration of the physical environment \u2014 were so poor as to violate his constitutional rights under Articles 40.3 and 40.4 and to render his detention unconstitutional. The Supreme Court accepted that Article 40.4, which provides for the inquiry into the legality of detention, is not limited to formal legal challenges to the basis for detention but extends to challenges grounded on the conditions of detention themselves where those conditions violate fundamental constitutional rights. The Court held that the State owes a positive constitutional duty to every person it detains to ensure that detention conditions meet a minimum constitutional standard compatible with human dignity. This standard is derived from Article 40.3 \u2014 the personal rights guarantee \u2014 read alongside Article 40.4 and, where applicable, the State's obligations under the European Convention on Human Rights. The Court granted the applicant declaratory relief. The decision is the leading Irish authority on constitutional minimum standards in detention and the availability of habeas corpus as a remedy for rights-violating prison conditions, and is a significant case for FE-1 study of personal rights and Article 40.",
