      "The Supreme Court held that a child born via surrogacy in the United Kingdom to an Irish non-biological (commissioning) father could not derive Irish citizenship through that father under the Irish Nationality and Citizenship Act 1956, because the word 'parent' in that Act fell to be interpreted according to its ordinary meaning at the time of enactment \u2014 that is, the genetic or gestational parent. The Court applied Article 40.1 and Article 41 of the Constitution but declined to strike down any legislative provision, as no declaration of unconstitutionality was sought. The judgment instead exposed a significant legislative lacuna in Irish law regarding the citizenship rights of children born through assisted human reproduction, and effectively called on the Oireachtas to address the gap. Article 42A's guarantee of the best interests of the child was considered but could not supply a statutory entitlement to citizenship where Parliament had not provided one.",
