      "The Court of Appeal quashed an anti-social behaviour order (ASBO) that imposed a blanket prohibition on the applicant speaking in public throughout the entirety of Wexford Town, finding that the order constituted a disproportionate prior restraint on the constitutional right to freedom of expression guaranteed by Article 40.6.1(i) of the Constitution. Applying the proportionality test, the Court held that public expression on civic or community matters attracts a high degree of constitutional protection and that any restriction must be no more than is necessary to achieve the legitimate aim pursued. A geographically unlimited prior ban on all public expression without any individuated justification failed that standard. The case is a leading authority on the application of the 'as-applied' method of constitutional challenge to statutory orders affecting expressive rights.",
