    full_summary:
      "The applicant, Tallon, had been subject to an anti-social behaviour order under the Criminal Justice Act 2006 that prohibited him from speaking in public anywhere within Wexford Town. He brought an 'as-applied' constitutional challenge, conceding the facial validity of the ASBO regime but arguing that the specific order made against him was unconstitutional in its breadth and effect. The Court of Appeal agreed. Article 40.6.1(i) protects the right of citizens to express freely their convictions and opinions, subject only to the requirements of public order and morality and the authority of the State. The Court emphasised that expression on matters of civic and community interest \u2014 even when nuisance-adjacent \u2014 lies close to the core of constitutionally protected speech. Applying the proportionality framework derived from Heaney v. Ireland, the Court found the order was not rationally connected to an identified harm, was broader than necessary, and failed to engage with any tailored assessment of the applicant's actual conduct or realistic risk. The order was quashed. The case confirms that courts will scrutinise as-applied challenges to orders affecting constitutional rights with rigour, and that proportionality requires individual calibration, not blanket prohibition.",
