      "The Supreme Court examined the circumstances in which a court exercising judicial review jurisdiction may, in its discretion, refuse relief to an applicant whose immigration history is tainted by lack of candour or deliberate misconduct. The Court held that the discretionary nature of judicial review remedies means that material non-disclosure or misleading conduct in the context of immigration proceedings \u2014 including findings of a marriage of convenience \u2014 can, depending on the gravity of that conduct, justify refusing certiorari or other equitable relief even where a ground of challenge is established. Article 40.3's protection of personal rights does not automatically override the court's supervisory discretion in such cases. The judgment provides authoritative guidance on the intersection of good faith obligations and constitutional remedies in the immigration judicial review context.",
