    full_summary:
      "The applicant sought judicial review of a deportation order, arguing that the Minister had failed to properly consider her rights under Article 40.3 of the Constitution and Article 8 of the European Convention on Human Rights. The background was complicated by a prior finding that the applicant's marriage \u2014 which formed part of the basis of her residence claim \u2014 was a marriage of convenience. The Supreme Court was asked to clarify the extent to which courts can exercise their inherent discretion to refuse judicial review relief where an applicant's conduct before administrative bodies has been dishonest or otherwise reprehensible. The Court confirmed that judicial review remedies are inherently discretionary and that a finding of bad faith, deliberate misleading, or exploitation of the immigration system is a material factor in the relief calculus. The Court also addressed circularity concerns \u2014 where the very decision under review was informed by a credibility finding \u2014 but held that the discretionary refusal of relief was not incompatible with constitutional protections where the conduct was sufficiently serious. The case is instructive on the limits of constitutional rights claims when the applicant comes to court with 'unclean hands.'",
