      'Delaney v. Personal Injuries Assessment Board, the Judicial Council, Ireland and the Attorney General',
    citation: '[2024] IESC 10',
    year: 2024,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Ireland',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'A majority of the Supreme Court (4-3) held that section 7(2)(g) of the Judicial Council Act 2019, in so far as it compelled the judiciary to adopt binding personal injuries guidelines having the force of law, violated the principle of judicial independence guaranteed by Article 35.2 of the Constitution. The same majority separately held (6-1) that the personal injuries guidelines themselves \u2014 once ratified by the Oireachtas \u2014 were constitutionally valid as an exercise of delegated legislative power consistent with Article 15.2. The Court also held that no vested property right in the pre-existing Book of Quantum had been created such as to engage the Article 43 property guarantee. The decision is the leading modern authority on the scope of judicial independence under the Irish Constitution and on the relationship between delegated legislation and the separation of powers.',
