    case_name: 'Director of Public Prosecutions v. Smyth (2024)',
    citation: '[2024] IESC 22',
    year: 2024,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Ireland',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'The Supreme Court held, by a majority of six to one, that mobile phone traffic and location data obtained by An Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na under domestic legislation that was subsequently found to be incompatible with EU law was nonetheless admissible in criminal proceedings. Applying the JC test (The People (DPP) v. JC [2017] IESC 1), the majority held that the police had acted in good faith by relying on legislation that was on its face valid at the time of the search; the seriousness of the offences prosecuted outweighed any systemic exclusionary interest; and no deliberate or conscious violation of constitutional rights under Article 40.5 (privacy) or Article 38 (fair trial) had occurred. The case establishes the leading 2024 authority on the interface between EU law invalidity, the exclusionary rule, and the constitutional right to a fair trial.',
    key_quote:
      'Where evidence is obtained by An Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na in genuine good faith reliance on domestic legislation that is subsequently found to breach EU law, the JC test requires admission of that evidence where the public interest in prosecution of serious crime outweighs any countervailing exclusionary consideration.',
    full_summary:
      'This case \u2014 distinct from DPP v. Smyth [2010] 3 I.R. 688 \u2014 concerned the admissibility of mobile phone traffic and location data obtained under the Communications (Retention of Data) Act 2011, which was subsequently found to breach EU law in the aftermath of Digital Rights Ireland (CJEU, 2014) and subsequent CJEU jurisprudence on data retention. The accused argued that evidence obtained under the now-invalid legislation should be excluded under the constitutional exclusionary rule as formulated in JC. The Supreme Court majority rejected this argument. The Court applied the three-stage JC balancing test: (1) the garda\u00ed acted on a facially valid statutory authority and in objective good faith; (2) the breach was attributable to legislative failure, not deliberate police misconduct; and (3) the serious nature of the offences under investigation meant the community interest in prosecution clearly outweighed any exclusionary benefit. Hogan J dissented powerfully, arguing that systematic EU law non-compliance could not be treated as mere inadvertent error warranting good faith protection. The case is now the primary reference point for the admissibility of data obtained under subsequently invalidated EU law in Irish criminal proceedings.',
