    full_summary:
      "McAreavey was decided on the same day as DPP v. Smyth [2024] IESC 22 and raises materially identical issues. An Garda S\u00edoch\u00e1na had obtained phone traffic and location data under the Communications (Retention of Data) Act 2011 and subsequent amending legislation enacted in light of CJEU Digital Rights Ireland jurisprudence. This legislation was itself later found to fail EU law requirements on data retention under subsequent CJEU rulings. The accused challenged the admissibility of that data, arguing that the statutory basis for its retention and disclosure was incompatible with EU law and that the evidence should therefore be excluded pursuant to the JC exclusionary rule. The Supreme Court rejected this challenge for the same reasons as in Smyth. The Court emphasised that the legislative failure did not transform the garda\u00ed's conduct into a deliberate constitutional breach; that good faith reliance on facially valid domestic statute provided the required justification; and that the serious nature of the offences charged meant the community interest in admissibility was compelling. Together, McAreavey and Smyth establish the definitive Irish framework for cases involving post-CJEU data retention invalidity and criminal admissibility.",
