      "The Supreme Court upheld the constitutional validity of a mandatory retirement age of 70 for Revenue Commissioners' sheriffs, finding that age-based retirement conditions in public office can be objectively justified without requiring individual capacity assessments. The Court confirmed that Article 40.1's equality guarantee does not prohibit all age-based distinctions but requires that they not be arbitrary or irrational; here, the goals of workforce planning, intergenerational fairness, and administrative standardisation provided sufficient objective justification. The judgment provides the leading Irish constitutional authority on the permissibility of mandatory retirement ages in quasi-public officeholders and clarifies the interaction between constitutional equality and the employment equality statutory framework.",
