      "The Supreme Court upheld the constitutional validity of ministerial statutory instruments creating indictable criminal offences relating to turf-cutting in areas of ecological protection, finding that such instruments did not constitute an unconstitutional delegation of the Oireachtas's exclusive legislative power under Article 15.2.1. Applying the Conway v. Irish Language Commissioner test, the Court held that the parent Act sufficiently laid down the principles and policies governing the ministerial power and did not amount to an abdication of primary legislative responsibility. The Court also rejected the argument that 'democratic accountability' under Article 5 constitutes a separate and independent constitutional standard for reviewing delegated legislation.",
