    legal_principle:
      "The Supreme Court upheld the constitutional validity of the COVID-19 mandatory hotel quarantine regime, including the ministerial power to designate countries for quarantine purposes and the 'Designated Appeals Officer' review mechanism created under the Health (Amendment) Act 2021. The Court dismissed challenges based on Article 15.2.1 (separation of powers and delegated legislation), Article 34.1 (judicial power), and personal rights grounds, finding that the legislative scheme adequately prescribed the principles and policies governing ministerial designation decisions and that the non-judicial appeals mechanism did not encroach upon the administration of justice. Both applicants' constitutional arguments were described by the Court as 'wafer thin.'",
