    full_summary:
      "The two applicants had been subject to mandatory hotel quarantine under the Health (Amendment) Act 2021, which was enacted during the COVID-19 pandemic to require international travellers arriving from designated countries to quarantine in approved facilities at their own expense. The Act empowered the Minister for Health to designate countries by statutory instrument and created a Designated Appeals Officer (DAO) mechanism to review individual quarantine decisions. The applicants challenged the scheme on three principal constitutional grounds: first, that the ministerial designation power amounted to an unconstitutional delegation of Oireachtas legislative authority under Article 15.2.1; second, that the DAO mechanism involved the exercise of judicial power contrary to Article 34.1; and third, that the scheme violated personal rights including freedom of movement and bodily integrity. The Supreme Court rejected all grounds. On the delegation point, the Act's criteria for designation \u2014 epidemiological risk, WHO classifications, and proportionality \u2014 provided sufficient principles and policies to satisfy the Conway test. On the Article 34.1 point, the DAO did not determine criminal liability or binding civil rights and therefore did not engage the exclusive administration of justice. The personal rights claims were dismissed as insufficiently developed. The Court's description of the arguments as 'wafer thin' indicates the low weight accorded to challenges to pandemic emergency measures enacted in compliance with constitutional form.",
