    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      "The Supreme Court held that Article 41.2 of the Constitution \u2014 which acknowledges the life of a woman within the home and commits the State to ensure that mothers shall not be obliged to engage in labour to the neglect of their duties \u2014 does not create an individually enforceable right to any specific level of carer's allowance payment. The word 'may' in section 186(2) of the Social Welfare Consolidation Act 2005 is genuinely permissive, conferring a discretion on the decision-maker rather than imposing a mandatory obligation to grant or maintain any particular rate of payment. The judgment is the first detailed Supreme Court examination of Article 41.2 in the social welfare and carer's rights context.",
