    full_summary:
      "The applicants were carers who argued that Article 41.2 of the Constitution \u2014 which recognises the contribution of women who give their lives within the home and directs the State to ensure they are not obliged to engage in labour to the neglect of those duties \u2014 created an enforceable constitutional entitlement to maintain or increase carer's allowance payments. They challenged adverse social welfare decisions on the basis that reduction or restriction of the carer's allowance violated Article 41.2. The Supreme Court rejected the challenge. The Court undertook a careful historical and textual analysis of Article 41.2, acknowledging that the provision has been the subject of considerable criticism for its gendered framing but noting that it was not amended in the 2018 or 2019 referendums (and was subsequently the subject of the 2024 referendum, ultimately rejected). The Court held that Article 41.2 is a statement of constitutional principle and policy \u2014 an acknowledgment and aspiration \u2014 rather than a source of individually enforceable subjective rights. The permissive language of section 186(2) ('the Minister may') was interpreted as a genuine legislative discretion that does not crystallise into a mandatory obligation by virtue of Article 41.2. The case is significant as it confirms that social and economic constitutional aspirations do not, of themselves, generate justiciable individual entitlements in the Irish constitutional order.",
