      "The High Court held that the imposition of a mandatory life sentence on defendants who committed the offence of murder as children but who were sentenced as adults \u2014 having 'aged out' of the Children Act 2001 regime before trial and conviction \u2014 violated Article 40.1 of the Constitution. The mandatory life sentence regime applicable to such defendants constituted an arbitrary and irrational classification that treated them identically to adult offenders who commit murder as adults, without any rational justification for the differential treatment of this cohort. The provision was declared unconstitutional and the legislature subsequently enacted the Criminal Justice (Amendment) Act 2024 to address the gap.",
