    full_summary:
      "The two applicants had committed murder while children (under 18) but had not been tried and convicted until they had reached adulthood, with the result that the Children Act 2001's more lenient sentencing regime \u2014 which does not permit mandatory life sentences for children \u2014 was no longer available to them. They were therefore subject to the mandatory life sentence applicable to adult murder convictions under the Criminal Justice Act 1964, despite the offences having been committed during childhood. They challenged the mandatory life sentence as unconstitutional. Simons J in the High Court agreed. The Court applied the Article 40.1 equality guarantee \u2014 which requires that like cases be treated alike and that distinctions be rationally justifiable \u2014 and held that there was no rational basis for treating a person who committed murder as a child identically to one who committed murder as an adult, simply because the passage of time had removed their eligibility for the Children Act regime. The classification was arbitrary and produced a result manifestly disproportionate to any legitimate penal aim. The mandatory life sentence provisions, as applied to 'aged out' child offenders, were declared unconstitutional. The Oireachtas responded with the Criminal Justice (Amendment) Act 2024, which introduced a judicial discretion in sentencing for this cohort. The case has significant implications for juvenile justice and constitutional equality.",
