    legal_principle:
      'The High Court held that an employee under active criminal investigation retains a constitutional right to silence under Article 40.3 that can be invoked to resist compelled disclosure in a parallel internal workplace investigation, even though the employment relationship is a private contractual one. The Court held that constitutional rights \u2014 in particular the privilege against self-incrimination \u2014 have some degree of horizontal effect in certain private relationships, especially where the consequences of the internal investigation may directly feed into or prejudice criminal proceedings. A contractual obligation to cooperate with an employer investigation cannot override the constitutional right to silence where criminal jeopardy is real and proximate.',
    key_quote:
      'The constitutional right to silence and the privilege against self-incrimination are not confined to the courtroom; they extend to circumstances in the private employment sphere where an employee faces genuine and proximate criminal jeopardy as a consequence of compelled disclosure in an internal investigation.',
    full_summary:
      "ESB sought to compel an employee, Sharkey, to cooperate fully with an internal workplace investigation into alleged misconduct, relying on contractual obligations in Sharkey's employment contract. Sharkey refused to answer certain questions in the internal investigation on the grounds that he was also under active criminal investigation in relation to substantially the same subject matter, and that answers given internally could be used against him in the criminal proceedings. ESB sought a court order compelling his participation. The High Court refused the order. The Court undertook a detailed examination of the constitutional privilege against self-incrimination in the private employment context. While acknowledging the foundational primacy of contract in regulating employment relationships, the Court found that constitutional rights do not stop at the courthouse door and that, in appropriate circumstances, they operate horizontally to limit what one private party can compel another to do. The critical factor was the real and proximate risk that answers given in the internal investigation would be disclosed to or used by prosecutorial authorities, creating genuine jeopardy for Sharkey's fair trial rights under Article 38. The Court declined to order compelled cooperation and held that ESB's contractual rights yielded to Sharkey's constitutional right to silence. The case is significant in its recognition of horizontal constitutional effect in the employment context and its integration of criminal and employment law considerations.",
