    case_name: 'Doe (No. 1), Doe (No. 2) and Doe (No. 3) v. Director of Public Prosecutions',
    citation: '[2025] IESC 17',
    year: 2025,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Ireland',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      "The Supreme Court held that prosecutorial delay resulting in child defendants 'aging out' of the anonymity and protective provisions of the Children Act 2001 before trial constitutes a violation of their constitutional rights under Article 38 (fair trial) and Article 40.3 (personal rights). Rather than prohibiting the trials outright, the Court exercised its inherent jurisdiction to impose 'Gilchrist orders' \u2014 permanent reporting restriction orders prohibiting the identification of the applicants in media and public reporting \u2014 as a proportionate constitutional remedy that restored the lost protections without sacrificing the community interest in prosecution. The case establishes the inherent judicial jurisdiction to fashion such orders as a constitutional remedy for procedural rights violations.",
    key_quote:
      'Where prosecutorial delay has caused child defendants to lose statutory anonymity and protective provisions, this Court has inherent jurisdiction to impose reporting restriction orders as a constitutional remedy that restores the lost protection proportionately and without the drastic consequence of prohibiting trial.',
    full_summary:
      "The three applicants had committed serious criminal offences as children (under 18) but, owing to prosecutorial delay, they were not tried until after they had turned 18. As a result, the anonymity protections of the Children Act 2001 \u2014 which would have prevented publication of their identities had they been tried as children \u2014 were no longer automatically available to them. Their identities had been or were at risk of being published in criminal proceedings that were now publicly reported. They sought either prohibition of their trials or some other constitutional remedy. The Supreme Court declined to prohibit the trials \u2014 finding that the public interest in prosecution of serious offences was too strong \u2014 but held that the delay had caused a real and identifiable constitutional injury by stripping the applicants of protections Parliament had specifically designed for child defendants. The Court drew on its inherent jurisdiction and the constitutional imperative of effective remedies to impose 'Gilchrist orders': permanent reporting restriction orders prohibiting any identification of the applicants in connection with the criminal proceedings, both past and future. These orders replicated, as nearly as possible, the protection the applicants would have enjoyed had their trials proceeded promptly. The case is important for its recognition that courts can fashion bespoke constitutional remedies short of prohibition, and for its treatment of children's rights, prosecutorial delay, and media freedom.",
