    case_name: 'Kirwan v. Connors and Ors',
    citation: '[2025] IESC 21',
    year: 2025,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Ireland',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'The Supreme Court reformulated the Irish test for dismissal of civil proceedings for want of prosecution on grounds of delay, moving beyond the traditional Primor three-part test. The Court held that significant and unexplained delay in prosecuting civil proceedings can justify dismissal even in the absence of identified specific evidentiary prejudice to the defendant, where the delay is of such duration and character as to render a fair trial impossible or to fundamentally undermine the constitutional imperative of timely justice. The judgment introduces a sliding scale approach: the more egregious the delay, the less weighty the specific prejudice that need be demonstrated.',
    key_quote:
      'Significant and unexplained delay in civil litigation can, of itself, justify dismissal for want of prosecution where the delay is so severe as to render a fair trial impossible, even absent proof of specific evidentiary prejudice; the constitutional right of access to justice includes the right of defendants to have claims against them determined within a reasonable time.',
    full_summary:
      "Kirwan arose from a civil action in which there had been very substantial delay between the initiation of proceedings and their progression toward trial. The defendants applied to have the proceedings struck out for want of prosecution. The central question for the Supreme Court was whether the established Primor v. Stokes Kennedy Crowley test \u2014 which required the defendant to establish (i) inordinate and inexcusable delay; (ii) a balance of justice favouring dismissal; and (iii) in most cases, specific identifiable prejudice \u2014 remained the correct framework, or whether it required refinement in light of constitutional requirements of timely justice. The Supreme Court reformulated the test. The Court affirmed that inordinate and inexcusable delay remains the threshold inquiry, but it significantly relaxed the prejudice requirement, holding that where delay is of a particularly grave character the court can infer prejudice to the defendant's ability to mount a fair defence from the passage of time itself. The Court introduced a sliding scale: the longer and more unexplained the delay, the less specific the prejudice need be before the balance of justice tips toward dismissal. The Court grounded this approach in the constitutional right of access to the courts under Article 34, the fair trial guarantee of Article 38, and the general constitutional principle that the administration of justice must be conducted in a timely and efficient manner. Kirwan is now the leading 2025 authority on delay and want of prosecution in Irish civil litigation.",
