    case_name: 'ZG and EW v. Ireland',
    citation: '[2025] IESC 49',
    year: 2025,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Ireland',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      'The Supreme Court upheld the constitutional validity of an age-based restriction in the Residential Tenancies Act 2004 that limited succession rights in tenancies to persons of a certain age, finding that the restriction did not violate Article 40.1 or Article 42A of the Constitution. Applying the irrationality standard from Donnelly v. Minister for Education [2022] IESC 50, the Court held that age, while a recognised characteristic, does not attract the same level of constitutional scrutiny as more fundamental personal attributes; the restriction was not irrational. The Court further held that Article 42A does not compel the Oireachtas to adopt any particular legislative policy in favour of children in the domain of housing and tenancy law; institutional deference on social housing policy was appropriate.',
    key_quote:
      'Article 40.1 does not require identical treatment on the basis of age where the legislative distinction is not irrational; Article 42A does not compel any specific legislative policy outcome in favour of children and cannot be invoked to override legitimate Oireachtas policy choices in the domain of housing.',
    full_summary:
      "The applicants challenged an age-based restriction in the Residential Tenancies Act 2004 that limited the right to succeed to a tenancy upon the death or departure of the original tenant to persons above a specified age, thereby excluding young adult children from succession in certain circumstances. They argued that the restriction violated Article 40.1's equality guarantee \u2014 because it discriminated on the basis of age without rational justification \u2014 and violated Article 42A's guarantee of children's rights \u2014 because it operated to the detriment of younger persons who might otherwise benefit from tenancy succession. The Supreme Court dismissed both grounds. Applying the Donnelly irrationality standard \u2014 which asks whether the legislative classification is so irrational or unreasonable that no legitimate legislature could have adopted it \u2014 the Court held that age is not as constitutionally sensitive a characteristic as race, gender, or disability, and that the restriction pursued recognisable housing policy goals (preventing intergenerational accumulation of social housing tenancies, managing stock, facilitating mobility) that were not irrational. On the Article 42A point, the Court emphasised that the constitutional guarantee of children's rights does not operate as a positive mandate compelling the Oireachtas to legislate in any particular way in favour of children in every domain of policy. Where the Oireachtas has made a choice about housing policy that does not specifically target or harm children, Article 42A does not require the court to override that choice in favour of a child-centred outcome. Institutional deference to Oireachtas policy choices on housing was held to be appropriate and constitutionally mandated.",
