    case_name: "O'Reilly v. Electricity Supply Board",
    citation: '[2025] IESC 27',
    year: 2025,
    court: 'Supreme Court of Ireland',
    jurisdiction: 'IE',
    legal_principle:
      "The Supreme Court held that the concept of 'injurious affection' under section 53 of the Electricity (Supply) Act 1927, as amended, extends to cover diminution in value across the entirety of a landowner's holding caused by the presence of overhead electricity transmission lines, not merely the specific strip of land over which the easement or wayleave is granted. Constitutional property rights under Article 43, while not directly creating a right to compensation, inform the purposive interpretation of statutory compensation schemes and require that ambiguity be resolved in favour of the landowner. The decision settles decades of valuation uncertainty in the ESB compensation context.",
    key_quote:
      "The concept of injurious affection in section 53 of the Electricity (Supply) Act 1927 must be interpreted purposively and in a manner consistent with the constitutional guarantee of property rights under Article 43; it encompasses diminution in the value of the entirety of the landowner's holding, not merely the directly affected parcel.",
    full_summary:
      "The applicant landowner, O'Reilly, was affected by the installation and maintenance of overhead electricity transmission lines by ESB across her property. She claimed compensation under section 53 of the Electricity (Supply) Act 1927, as amended, arguing that 'injurious affection' \u2014 the term used in the Act to capture compensable loss \u2014 extended beyond the immediate impact on the land directly traversed by the lines and encompassed the broader diminution in value caused to her entire landholding. ESB resisted this interpretation, arguing that compensation was confined to the specific strip or area directly affected by the physical installation. The Supreme Court resolved the long-running dispute in favour of the landowner. The Court applied purposive statutory interpretation, holding that the Oireachtas intended the compensation scheme to be broadly remedial and that Article 43's constitutional protection of property rights required that ambiguity be resolved in favour of the owner. 'Injurious affection' was held to include any diminution in the market value of the landowner's entire property portfolio that is directly attributable to the ESB's works, including blight caused by the visual and electromagnetic impact of the lines on adjacent or surrounding land. The judgment provides the definitive authority on the scope of section 53 compensation and resolves uncertainty that had persisted for decades in land compensation and electricity infrastructure disputes.",
